From hele (a ray; perhaps akin to the alternate of  (G138) haireomai); the sun; by implication, light -- + east, sun. see GREEK  (G138) haireomai
Of uncertain affinity; a stud, i.e. Spike -- nail.
Accusative case plural of  (G1473) ego; us -- our, us, we. see GREEK  (G1473) ego
Nominative plural of  (G1473) ego; we (only used when emphatic) -- us, we (ourselves). see GREEK  (G1473) ego

Feminine (with  (G5610) hora implied) of a derivative of hemai (to sit; akin to the base of  (G1476) hedraios) meaning tame, i.e. Gentle; day, i.e. (literally) the time space between dawn and dark, or the whole  (G24) aganaktesis hours (but several days were usually reckoned by the Jews as inclusive of the parts of both extremes); figuratively, a period (always defined more or less clearly by the context) -- age, + alway, (mid-)day (by day, (-ly)), + for ever, judgment, (day) time, while, years. see GREEK  (G5610) hora see GREEK  (G1476) hedraios
From  (G2349) thnetos; our -- our, your (by a different reading). see GREEK  (G2349) thnetos
A prolonged form of  (G2358) thriambeuo; I was -- be, was. (Sometimes unexpressed). see GREEK  (G2358) thriambeuo
From a presumed compound of the base of  (G2255) hemisu and  (G2348) thnesko; half dead, i.e. Entirely exhausted -- half dead. see GREEK  (G2255) hemisu see GREEK  (G2348) thnesko
Dative case plural of  (G1473) ego; to (or for, with, by) us -- our, (for) us, we. see GREEK  (G1473) ego
Neuter of a derivative from an inseparable prefix akin to  (G260) hama (through the idea of partition involved in connection) and meaning semi-; (as noun) half -- half. see GREEK  (G260) hama
From the base of  (G2255) hemisu and  (G5610) hora; a half-hour -- half an hour. see GREEK  (G2255) hemisu see GREEK  (G5610) hora
Genitive case plural of  (G1473) ego; of (or from) us -- our (company), us, we. see GREEK  (G1473) ego

column7: agree, be, have charge of, hold, use
column8: agree, be, have charge of, hold, use.
column9: Imperfect of  (G1510) eimi; I (thou, etc.) Was (wast or were) -- + agree, be, X have (+ charge of), hold, use, was(-t), were. see GREEK  (G1510) eimi
Of uncertain affinity; at which time -- when.
From  (G2228) e and  (G4007) per; than at all (or than perhaps, than indeed) -- than. see GREEK  (G2228) e see GREEK  (G4007) per
Probably from  (G2031) epos; properly, affable, i.e. Mild or kind -- gentle. see GREEK  (G2031) epos
Of Hebrew origin ( (H6147) Er); Er, an Israelite -- Er. see HEBREW  (H6147) Er
Perhaps by transposition from  (G2048) eremos (through the idea of stillness); tranquil -- quiet. see GREEK  (G2048) eremos

column7: perhaps "son of a hero", Herod, the name of several kings of the Jews
column9: Compound of heros (a "hero") and  (G1491) eidos; heroic; Herod, the name of four Jewish kings -- Herod. see GREEK  (G1491) eidos
Plural of a derivative of  (G2264) Herodes; Herodians, i.e. Partisans of Herod -- Herodians. see GREEK  (G2264) Herodes

column7: Herodias, granddaughter of Herod the Great
column9: From  (G2264) Herodes; Herodias, a woman of the Heodian family -- Herodias. see GREEK  (G2264) Herodes
From  (G2264) Herodes; Herodion, a Christian -- Herodion. see GREEK  (G2264) Herodes
Of Hebrew origin ( (H3470) Ysha'yah); Hesaias (i.e. Jeshajah), an Israelite -- Esaias. see HEBREW  (H3470) Ysha'yah
Of Hebrew origin ( (H6215) Esav); Esau, an Edomite -- Esau. see HEBREW  (H6215) Esav

column8: cease, hold peace, be quiet, rest.
column9: From the same as  (G2272) hesuchios; to keep still (intransitively), i.e. Refrain from labor, meddlesomeness or speech -- cease, hold peace, be quiet, rest. see GREEK  (G2272) hesuchios
Feminine of  (G2272) hesuchios; (as noun) stillness, i.e. Desistance from bustle or language -- quietness, silence. see GREEK  (G2272) hesuchios

A prolonged form of a compound probably of a derivative of the base of  (G1476) hedraios and perhaps  (G2192) echo; properly, keeping one's seat (sedentary), i.e. (by implication) still (undisturbed, undisturbing) -- peaceable, quiet. see GREEK  (G1476) hedraios see GREEK  (G2192) echo
From  (G2228) e and  (G5104) toi; either indeed -- whether. see GREEK  (G2228) e see GREEK  (G5104) toi
From the same as  (G2276) hetton; to make worse, i.e. Vanquish (literally or figuratively); by implication, to rate lower -- be inferior, overcome. see GREEK  (G2276) hetton
From  (G2274) hettao; a deterioration, i.e. (objectively) failure or (subjectively) loss -- diminishing, fault. see GREEK  (G2274) hettao
Neuter of comparative of heka (slightly) used for that of  (G2556) kakos; worse (as noun); by implication, less (as adverb) -- less, worse. see GREEK  (G2556) kakos
Third person singular imperative of  (G1510) eimi; let him (or it) be -- let... Be. see GREEK  (G1510) eimi

column7: to make a loud noise, to sound
column9: From  (G2279) echos; to make a loud noise, i.e. Reverberate -- roar, sound. see GREEK  (G2279) echos
Of uncertain affinity; a loud or confused noise ("echo"), i.e. Roar; figuratively, a rumor -- fame, sound.
Of uncertain origin; Thaddaeus, one of the Apostles -- Thaddaeus.
Probably prolonged from  (G251) hals; the sea (genitive case or specially) -- sea. see GREEK  (G251) hals
Probably akin to thallo (to warm); to brood, i.e. (figuratively) to foster -- cherish.
Of Hebrew origin ( (H8559) Tamar); Thamar (i.e. Tamar), an Israelitess -- Thamar. see HEBREW  (H8559) Tamar
From  (G2285) thambos; to stupefy (with surprise), i.e. Astound -- amaze, astonish. see GREEK  (G2285) thambos
Akin to an obsolete tapho (to dumbfound); stupefaction (by surprise), i.e. Astonishment -- X amazed, + astonished, wonder.
From  (G2288) thanatos; fatal, i.e. Poisonous -- deadly. see GREEK  (G2288) thanatos
From (the feminine form of)  (G2288) thanatos and  (G5342) phero; death-bearing, i.e. Fatal -- deadly. see GREEK  (G2288) thanatos see GREEK  (G5342) phero
From  (G2348) thnesko; (properly, an adjective used as a noun) death (literally or figuratively) -- X deadly, (be...) Death. see GREEK  (G2348) thnesko

column8: become dead, put to death, kill, mortify.
column9: From  (G2288) thanatos to kill (literally or figuratively) -- become dead, (cause to be) put to death, kill, mortify. see GREEK  (G2288) thanatos
A primary verb; to celebrate funeral rites, i.e. Inter -- bury.
Of Hebrew origin ( (H8646) Terach); Thara (i.e. Terach), the father of Abraham -- Thara. see HEBREW  (H8646) Terach

column8: be bold, have confidence, be confident.
column9: Another form for  (G2293) tharseo; to exercise courage -- be bold, X boldly, have confidence, be confident. Compare  (G5111) tolmao. see GREEK  (G2293) tharseo see GREEK  (G5111) tolmao
From  (G2294) tharsos; to have courage -- be of good cheer (comfort). Compare  (G2292) tharrheo. see GREEK  (G2294) tharsos see GREEK  (G2292) tharrheo
Akin (by transposition) to thrasos (daring); boldness (subjectively) -- courage.
Apparently from a form of  (G2300) theaomai; wonder (properly concrete; but by implication, abstract) -- admiration. see GREEK  (G2300) theaomai
From  (G2295) thauma; to wonder; by implication, to admire -- admire, have in admiration, marvel, wonder. see GREEK  (G2295) thauma
From  (G2295) thauma; wondrous, i.e. (neuter as noun) a miracle -- wonderful thing. see GREEK  (G2295) thauma
From  (G2296) thaumazo; wondered at, i.e. (by implication) wonderful -- marvel(-lous). see GREEK  (G2296) thaumazo
Feminine of  (G2316) theos; a female deity -- goddess. see GREEK  (G2316) theos

A prolonged form of a primary verb; to look closely at, i.e. (by implication) perceive (literally or figuratively); by extension to visit -- behold, look (upon), see. Compare  (G3700) optanomai. see GREEK  (G3700) optanomai

column8: to put to shame, expose publicly
column9: From  (G2302) theatron; to expose as a spectacle -- make a gazing stock. see GREEK  (G2302) theatron
From  (G2300) theaomai; a place for public show ("theatre"), i.e. General audience-room; by implication, a show itself (figuratively) -- spectacle, theatre. see GREEK  (G2300) theaomai
Probably neuter of  (G2304) theios (in its original sense of flashing); sulphur -- brimstone. see GREEK  (G2304) theios
From  (G2316) theos; godlike (neuter as noun, divinity): - divine, godhead. see GREEK  (G2316) theos
From  (G2304) theios; divinity (abstractly) -- godhead. see GREEK  (G2304) theios
From  (G2303) theion and  (G1491) eidos; sulphur-like, i.e. Sulphurous -- brimstone. see GREEK  (G2303) theion

From the prolonged form of  (G2309) ethelo; a determination (properly, the thing), i.e. (actively) choice (specially, purpose, decree; abstractly, volition) or (passively) inclination -- desire, pleasure, will. see GREEK  (G2309) ethelo
From  (G2309) ethelo; determination (properly, the act), i.e. Option -- will. see GREEK  (G2309) ethelo

Thel'-o or thel'-o or in certain tenses theleo thel-eh'-o, and etheleo eth-el-eh'-o, which are otherwise obsolete; apparently strengthened from the alternate form of  (G138) haireomai; to determine (as an active option from subjective impulse; whereas  (G1014) boulomai properly denotes rather a passive acquiescence in objective considerations), i.e. Choose or prefer (literally or figuratively); by implication, to wish, i.e. Be inclined to (sometimes adverbially, gladly); impersonally for the future tense, to be about to; by Hebraism, to delight in -- desire, be disposed (forward), intend, list, love, mean, please, have rather, (be) will (have, -ling, - ling(-ly)). see GREEK  (G138) haireomai see GREEK  (G1014) boulomai
From a derivative of  (G5087) tithemi; something put down, i.e. A substruction (of a building, etc.), (literally or figuratively) -- foundation. see GREEK  (G5087) tithemi
From  (G2310) themelios; to lay a basis for, i.e. (literally) erect, or (figuratively) consolidate -- (lay the) found(- ation), ground, settle. see GREEK  (G2310) themelios
From  (G2316) theos and  (G1321) didasko; divinely instructed -- taught of God. see GREEK  (G2316) theos see GREEK  (G1321) didasko
From  (G2314) theomachos; to resist deity -- fight against God. see GREEK  (G2314) theomachos
From  (G2316) theos and  (G3164) machomai; an opponent of deity -- to fight against God. see GREEK  (G2316) theos see GREEK  (G3164) machomai
From  (G2316) theos and a presumed derivative of  (G4154) pneo; divinely breathed in -- given by inspiration of God. see GREEK  (G2316) theos see GREEK  (G4154) pneo
Of uncertain affinity; a deity, especially (with  (G3588) ho) the supreme Divinity; figuratively, a magistrate; by Hebraism, very -- X exceeding, God, god(-ly, -ward). see GREEK  (G3588) ho
From  (G2318) theosebes; devoutness, i.e. Piety -- godliness. see GREEK  (G2318) theosebes
From  (G2316) theos and  (G4576) sebomai; reverent of God, i.e. Pious -- worshipper of God. see GREEK  (G2316) theos see GREEK  (G4576) sebomai
From  (G2316) theos and the base of  (G4767) stugnetos; hateful to God, i.e. Impious -- hater of God. see GREEK  (G2316) theos see GREEK  (G4767) stugnetos
From  (G2316) theos; divinity (abstractly) -- godhead. see GREEK  (G2316) theos

column7: friend of God, Theophilus, the addressee of Luke and Acts
column9: From  (G2316) theos and  (G5384) philos; friend of God; Theophilus, a Christian -- Theophilus. see GREEK  (G2316) theos see GREEK  (G5384) philos
From  (G2323) therapeuo; attendance (specially, medical, i.e. Cure); figuratively and collectively, domestics -- healing, household. see GREEK  (G2323) therapeuo
From the same as  (G2324) therapon; to wait upon menially, i.e. (figuratively) to adore (God), or (specially) to relieve (of disease) -- cure, heal, worship. see GREEK  (G2324) therapon
Apparently a participle from an otherwise obsolete derivative of the base of  (G2330) theros; a menial attendant (as if cherishing) -- servant. see GREEK  (G2330) theros
From  (G2330) theros (in the sense of the crop); to harvest -- reap. see GREEK  (G2330) theros
From  (G2325) therizo; reaping, i.e. The crop -- harvest. see GREEK  (G2325) therizo
From  (G2325) therizo; a harvester -- reaper. see GREEK  (G2325) therizo
From  (G2329) therme; to heat (oneself) -- (be) warm(-ed, self). see GREEK  (G2329) therme
From the base of  (G2330) theros; warmth -- heat. see GREEK  (G2330) theros
From a primary thero (to heat); properly, heat, i.e. Summer -- summer.
From  (G2332) Thessalonike; a Thessalonican, i.e. Inhabitant of Thessalonice -- Thessalonian. see GREEK  (G2332) Thessalonike
From Thessalos (a Thessalian) and  (G3529) nike; Thessalonice, a place in Asia Minor -- Thessalonica. see GREEK  (G3529) nike
Of uncertain origin; Theudas, an Israelite -- Theudas.

From a derivative of  (G2300) theaomai (perhaps by addition of  (G3708) horao); to be a spectator of, i.e. Discern, (literally, figuratively (experience) or intensively (acknowledge)) -- behold, consider, look on, perceive, see. Compare  (G3700) optanomai. see GREEK  (G2300) theaomai see GREEK  (G3708) horao see GREEK  (G3700) optanomai
From the same as  (G2334) theoreo; spectatorship, i.e. (concretely) a spectacle -- sight. see GREEK  (G2334) theoreo
From  (G5087) tithemi; a receptacle, i.e. Scabbard -- sheath. see GREEK  (G5087) tithemi
From thele (the nipple); to suckle, (by implication) to suck -- (give) suck(-ling).
From the same as  (G2337) thelazo; female -- female, woman. see GREEK  (G2337) thelazo
From ther (a wild animal, as game); hunting, i.e. (figuratively) destruction -- trap.
From  (G2339) thera; to hunt (an animal), i.e. (figuratively) to carp at -- catch. see GREEK  (G2339) thera

From a compound of  (G2342) therion and  (G3164) machomai; to be a beast-fighter (in the gladiatorial show), i.e. (figuratively) to encounter (furious men) -- fight with wild beasts. see GREEK  (G2342) therion see GREEK  (G3164) machomai
Diminutive from the same as  (G2339) thera; a dangerous animal -- (venomous, wild) beast. see GREEK  (G2339) thera

column8: lay up treasure, keep in store.
column9: From  (G2344) thesauros; to amass or reserve (literally or figuratively) -- lay up (treasure), (keep) in store, (heap) treasure (together, up). see GREEK  (G2344) thesauros
From  (G5087) tithemi; a deposit, i.e. Wealth (literally or figuratively) -- treasure. see GREEK  (G5087) tithemi
A prolonged form of an obsolete primary thigo (to finger); to manipulate, i.e. Have to do with; by implication, to injure -- handle, touch.
Akin to the base of  (G5147) tribos; to crowd (literally or figuratively) -- afflict, narrow, throng, suffer tribulation, trouble. see GREEK  (G5147) tribos
From  (G2346) thlibo; pressure (literally or figuratively) -- afflicted(-tion), anguish, burdened, persecution, tribulation, trouble. see GREEK  (G2346) thlibo
A strengthened form of a simpler primary thano than'-o (which is used for it only in certain tenses); to die (literally or figuratively) -- be dead, die.
From  (G2348) thnesko; liable to die -- mortal(-ity). see GREEK  (G2348) thnesko
From  (G2351) thorubos; to be in tumult, i.e. Disturb, clamor -- make ado (a noise), trouble self, set on an uproar. see GREEK  (G2351) thorubos
From the base of  (G2360) throeo; a disturbance -- tumult, uproar. see GREEK  (G2360) throeo
A primary verb; to crush -- bruise. Compare  (G4486) rhegnumi. see GREEK  (G4486) rhegnumi
From  (G5142) trepho; stock (as raised on a farm) -- cattle. see GREEK  (G5142) trepho
From  (G2355) threnos; to bewail -- lament, mourn. see GREEK  (G2355) threnos
From the base of  (G2360) throeo; wailing -- lamentation. see GREEK  (G2360) throeo
From a derivative of  (G2357) threskos; ceremonial observance -- religion, worshipping. see GREEK  (G2357) threskos
Probably from the base of  (G2360) throeo; ceremonious in worship (as demonstrative), i.e. Pious -- religious. see GREEK  (G2360) throeo

From a prolonged compound of the base of  (G2360) throeo; and a derivative of  (G680) haptomai (meaning a noisy iambus, sung in honor of Bacchus); to make an acclamatory procession, i.e. (figuratively) to conquer or (by Hebraism) to give victory -- (cause) to triumph (over). see GREEK  (G2360) throeo see GREEK  (G680) haptomai
Genitive case trichos, etc.; of uncertain derivation; hair -- hair. Compare  (G2864) kome. see GREEK  (G2864) kome
From threomai to wail; to clamor, i.e. (by implication) to frighten -- trouble.
Perhaps from  (G5142) trepho (in the sense of thickening); a clot -- great drop. see GREEK  (G5142) trepho
From thrao (to sit); a stately seat ("throne"); by implication, power or (concretely) a potentate -- seat, throne.
Of uncertain derivation; Thyatira, a place in Asia Minor -- Thyatira.
Apparently a primary word (compare "daughter"); a female child, or (by Hebraism) descendant (or inhabitant) -- daughter.

From  (G2596) kata and  (G1836) hexes; thereafter, i.e. Consecutively; as a noun (by ellipsis of noun) a subsequent person or time -- after(-ward), by (in) order. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G1836) hexes
From  (G2596) kata and heudo (to sleep); to lie down to rest, i.e. (by implication) to fall asleep (literally or figuratively) -- (be a-)sleep. see GREEK  (G2596) kata
From a compound of  (G2596) kata and  (G2233) hegeomai; a guide, i.e. (figuratively) a teacher -- master. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G2233) hegeomai
From  (G2596) kata and  (G2240) heko; to reach to, i.e. (neuter of present active participle, figuratively as adjective) becoming -- convenient, fit. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G2240) heko

From  (G2596) kata; and hemai (to sit; akin to the base of  (G1476) hedraios); to sit down; figuratively, to remain, reside -- dwell, sit (by, down). see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G1476) hedraios
From  (G2596) kata and  (G2250) hemera; quotidian -- daily. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G2250) hemera

column7: to make to sit down, to sit down
column9: Another (active) form for  (G2516) kathezomai; to seat down, i.e. Set (figuratively, appoint); intransitively, to sit (down); figuratively, to settle (hover, dwell) -- continue, set, sit (down), tarry. see GREEK  (G2516) kathezomai
From  (G2596) kata; and hiemi (to send); to lower -- let down. see GREEK  (G2596) kata

column8: appoint, be, conduct, make, ordain, set.
column9: From  (G2596) kata and  (G2476) histemi; to place down (permanently), i.e. (figuratively) to designate, constitute, convoy -- appoint, be, conduct, make, ordain, set. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G2476) histemi

column8: to the degree that, inasmuch as.
column9: From  (G2596) kata and  (G3739) hos; according to which thing, i.e. Precisely as, in proportion as -- according to that, (inasmuch) as. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G3739) hos
From  (G2596) kata and  (G3650) holos; on the whole, i.e. Entirely -- at all. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G3650) holos
From  (G2596) kata; and  (G3695) hoplizo; to equip fully with armor -- arm. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G3695) hoplizo
From  (G2596) kata and  (G3708) horao; to behold fully, i.e. (figuratively) distinctly apprehend -- clearly see. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G3708) horao

From  (G2596) kata; and  (G3739) hos and  (G5100) tis; according to which certain thing, i.e. As far (or inasmuch) as -- (according, forasmuch) as, because (that). see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G3739) hos see GREEK  (G5100) tis
From  (G2596) kata and  (G5613) hos; just (or inasmuch) as, that -- according to, (according, even) as, how, when. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G5613) hos

column8: and, also, both, but, even, for, if, or, so
column9: Apparently, a primary particle, having a copulative and sometimes also a cumulative force; and, also, even, so then, too, etc.; often used in connection (or composition) with other particles or small words -- and, also, both, but, even, for, if, or, so, that, then, therefore, when, yet.
Of Chaldee origin; the dell; Caiaphas (i.e. Cajepha), an Israelite -- Caiaphas.
From  (G2532) kai and  (G1065) ge; and at least (or even, indeed) -- and, at least. see GREEK  (G2532) kai see GREEK  (G1065) ge
Of Hebrew origin ( (H7014) Qayin); Cain, (i.e. Cajin), the son of Adam -- Cain. see HEBREW  (H7014) Qayin
Of Hebrew origin ( (H7018) Qeynan); Cainan (i.e. Kenan), the name of two patriarchs -- Cainan. see HEBREW  (H7018) Qeynan
Of uncertain affinity; new (especially in freshness; while  (G3501) neos is properly so with respect to age -- new. see GREEK  (G3501) neos
From  (G2537) kainos; renewal (figuratively) -- newness. see GREEK  (G2537) kainos
From  (G2532) kai and  (G4007) per; and indeed, i.e. Nevertheless or notwithstanding -- and yet, although. see GREEK  (G2532) kai see GREEK  (G4007) per
Of uncertain affinity; an occasion, i.e. Set or proper time -- X always, opportunity, (convenient, due) season, (due, short, while) time, a while. Compare  (G5550) chronos. see GREEK  (G5550) chronos
Of Latin origin; Caesar, a title of the Roman emperor -- Caesar.

column7: Caesarea, the name of two cities in Palestine
column9: From  (G2541) Kaisar; Caesaria, the name of two places in Palestine -- Caesarea. see GREEK  (G2541) Kaisar
From  (G2532) kai and  (G5104) toi; and yet, i.e. Nevertheless -- although. see GREEK  (G2532) kai see GREEK  (G5104) toi
From  (G2543) kaitoi and  (G1065) ge; and yet indeed, i.e. Although really -- nevertheless, though. see GREEK  (G2543) kaitoi see GREEK  (G1065) ge
Apparently a primary verb; to set on fire, i.e. Kindle or (by implication) consume -- burn, light.
From  (G2532) kai and  (G1563) ekei; likewise in that place -- and there, there (thither) also. see GREEK  (G2532) kai see GREEK  (G1563) ekei
From  (G2532) kai and  (G1564) ekeithen; likewise from that place (or time) -- and afterward (from) (thence), thence also. see GREEK  (G2532) kai see GREEK  (G1564) ekeithen

column8: and him, him also, them also
column9: From  (G2532) kai and  (G1565) ekeinos; likewise that (or those) -- and him (other, them), even he, him also, them (also), (and) they. see GREEK  (G2532) kai see GREEK  (G1565) ekeinos
From  (G2556) kakos; badness, i.e. (subjectively) depravity, or (actively) malignity, or (passively) trouble -- evil, malice(-iousness), naughtiness, wickedness. see GREEK  (G2556) kakos
From a compound of  (G2556) kakos and  (G2239) ethos; bad character, i.e. (specially) mischievousness -- malignity. see GREEK  (G2556) kakos see GREEK  (G2239) ethos
From a compound of  (G2556) kakos and  (G3056) logos; to revile -- curse, speak evil of. see GREEK  (G2556) kakos see GREEK  (G3056) logos
From a compound of  (G2256) hemiorion and  (G3806) pathos; hardship -- suffering affliction. see GREEK  (G2256) hemiorion see GREEK  (G3806) pathos
From the same as  (G2552) kakopatheia; to undergo hardship -- be afflicted, endure afflictions (hardness), suffer trouble. see GREEK  (G2552) kakopatheia
From  (G2555) kakopoios; to be a bad-doer, i.e. (objectively) to injure, or (genitive) to sin -- do(ing) evil. see GREEK  (G2555) kakopoios
From  (G2556) kakos and  (G4160) poieo; a bad-doer; (specially), a criminal -- evil-doer, malefactor. see GREEK  (G2556) kakos see GREEK  (G4160) poieo

Apparently a primary word; worthless (intrinsically, such; whereas  (G4190) poneros properly refers to effects), i.e. (subjectively) depraved, or (objectively) injurious -- bad, evil, harm, ill, noisome, wicked. see GREEK  (G4190) poneros
From  (G2556) kakos and the base of  (G2041) ergon; a wrong-doer, i.e. Criminal -- evil-doer, malefactor. see GREEK  (G2556) kakos see GREEK  (G2041) ergon
From a presumed compound of  (G2556) kakos and  (G2192) echo; to maltreat -- which suffer adversity, torment. see GREEK  (G2556) kakos see GREEK  (G2192) echo
From  (G2556) kakos; to injure; figuratively, to exasperate -- make evil affected, entreat evil, harm, hurt, vex. see GREEK  (G2556) kakos
From  (G2556) kakos; badly (physically or morally) -- amiss, diseased, evil, grievously, miserably, sick, sore. see GREEK  (G2556) kakos
From  (G2559) kakoo; maltreatment -- affliction. see GREEK  (G2559) kakoo
Feminine of  (G2563) kalamos; a stalk of grain, i.e. (collectively) stubble -- stubble. see GREEK  (G2563) kalamos
Or uncertain affinity; a reed (the plant or its stem, or that of a similar plant); by implication, a pen -- pen, reed.

Akin to the base of  (G2753) keleuo; to "call" (properly, aloud, but used in a variety of applications, directly or otherwise) -- bid, call (forth), (whose, whose sur-)name (was (called)). see GREEK  (G2753) keleuo
From the base of  (G2566) kallion and  (G1636) elaia; a cultivated olive tree, i.e. A domesticated or improved one -- good olive tree. see GREEK  (G2566) kallion see GREEK  (G1636) elaia
Neuter of the (irregular) comparative of  (G2570) kalos; (adverbially) better than many -- very well. see GREEK  (G2570) kalos
From  (G2570) kalos and  (G1320) didaskalos; a teacher of the right -- teacher of good things. see GREEK  (G2570) kalos see GREEK  (G1320) didaskalos

column7: Fair Havens, a harbor in Crete
column9: Plural of  (G2570) kalos and  (G3040) limen; Good Harbors, i.e. Fairhaven, a bay of Crete -- fair havens. see GREEK  (G2570) kalos see GREEK  (G3040) limen
From  (G2570) kalos and  (G4160) poieo; to do well, i.e. Live virtuously -- well doing. see GREEK  (G2570) kalos see GREEK  (G4160) poieo

Of uncertain affinity; properly, beautiful, but chiefly (figuratively) good (literally or morally), i.e. Valuable or virtuous (for appearance or use, and thus distinguished from  (G18) agathos, which is properly intrinsic) -- X better, fair, good(-ly), honest, meet, well, worthy. see GREEK  (G18) agathos
From  (G2572) kalupto; a cover, i.e. Veil -- vail. see GREEK  (G2572) kalupto
Akin to  (G2813) klepto and  (G2928) krupto; to cover up (literally or figuratively) -- cover, hide. see GREEK  (G2813) klepto see GREEK  (G2928) krupto
Adverb from  (G2570) kalos; well (usually morally) -- (in a) good (place), honestly, + recover, (full) well. see GREEK  (G2570) kalos
Of Hebrew origin ( (H1581) gamal); a "camel" -- camel. see HEBREW  (H1581) gamal
Probably from  (G2545) kaio; a furnace -- furnace. see GREEK  (G2545) kaio
From a compound of  (G2596) kata and the base of  (G3466) musterion; to shut down, i.e. Close the eyes -- close. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G3466) musterion
Apparently a primary verb; properly, to toil, i.e. (by implication) to tire (figuratively, faint, sicken) -- faint, sick, be wearied.
Apparently a primary verb; to bend -- bow.

column8: and if, at the least, though, yet.
column9: From  (G2532) kai and  (G1437) ean; and (or even) if -- and (also) if (so much as), if but, at the least, though, yet. see GREEK  (G2532) kai see GREEK  (G1437) ean
Of Hebrew origin (compare  (H7071) Qanah); Cana, a place in Palestine -- Cana. see HEBREW  (H7071) Qanah

column7: Cananaean, Aramaic for Zealot, surname of one of the twelve apostles
column9: Of Chaldee origin (compare  (H7067) qanna'); zealous; Cananites, an epithet -- Canaanite (by mistake for a derivative from  (G5477) Chanaan). see GREEK  (G5477) Chanaan see HEBREW  (H7067) qanna'
Of foreign origin -- Candace, an Egyptian queen -- Candace.
From kane (a straight reed, i.e. Rod); a rule ("canon"), i.e. (figuratively) a standard (of faith and practice); by implication, a boundary, i.e. (figuratively) a sphere (of activity) -- line, rule.
Of Hebrew origin (probably  (H3723) kaphar and  (H5151) Nachuwm); Capernaum (i.e. Caphanachum), a place in Palestine -- Capernaum. see HEBREW  (H3723) kaphar see HEBREW  (H5151) Nachuwm
From kapelos (a huckster); to retail, i.e. (by implication) to adulterate (figuratively) -- corrupt.
Of uncertain affinity; smoke -- smoke.

column7: Cappadocia, a province of Asia Minor
column9: Of foreign origin; Cappadocia, a region of Asia Minor -- Cappadocia.
Prolonged from a primary kar (Latin cor, "heart"); the heart, i.e. (figuratively) the thoughts or feelings (mind); also (by analogy) the middle -- (+ broken-)heart(-ed).
From  (G2588) kardia and  (G1097) ginosko; a heart-knower -- which knowest the hearts. see GREEK  (G2588) kardia see GREEK  (G1097) ginosko
Probably from the base of  (G726) harpazo; fruit (as plucked), literally or figuratively -- fruit. see GREEK  (G726) harpazo
Perhaps for  (G2590) karpos; Carpus, probably a Christian -- Carpus. see GREEK  (G2590) karpos
From  (G2593) karpophoros; to be fertile (literally or figuratively) -- be (bear, bring forth) fruit(-ful). see GREEK  (G2593) karpophoros
From  (G2590) karpos and  (G5342) phero; fruitbearing (figuratively) -- fruitful. see GREEK  (G2590) karpos see GREEK  (G5342) phero
From a derivative of  (G2904) kratos (transposed); to be strong, i.e. (figuratively) steadfast (patient) -- endure. see GREEK  (G2904) kratos
From karpho (to wither); a dry twig or straw -- mote.

A primary particle; (prepositionally) down (in place or time), in varied relations (according to the case (genitive, dative or accusative) with which it is joined) -- about, according as (to), after, against, (when they were) X alone, among, and, X apart, (even, like) as (concerning, pertaining to touching), X aside, at, before, beyond, by, to the charge of, (charita-)bly, concerning, + covered, (dai-)ly, down, every, (+ far more) exceeding, X more excellent, for, from... To, godly, in(-asmuch, divers, every, -to, respect of),... By, after the manner of, + by any means, beyond (out of) measure, X mightily, more, X natural, of (up-)on (X part), out (of every), over against, (+ your) X own, + particularly, so, through(-oughout, -oughout every), thus, (un-)to(-gether, -ward), X uttermost, where(-by), with. In composition it retains many of these applications, and frequently denotes opposition, distribution, or intensity.
From  (G2596) kata and the base of  (G939) basis; to descend (literally or figuratively) -- come (get, go, step) down, fall (down). see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G939) basis
From  (G2596) kata and  (G906) ballo; to throw down -- cast down, lay. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G906) ballo
From  (G2596) kata and  (G916) bareo; to impose upon -- burden. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G916) bareo
From  (G2597) katabaino; a declivity -- descent. see GREEK  (G2597) katabaino
From  (G2596) kata and a derivative of the base of  (G939) basis; to cause to go down, i.e. Precipitate -- bring (thrust) down. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G939) basis
From  (G2598) kataballo; a deposition, i.e. Founding; figuratively, conception -- conceive, foundation. see GREEK  (G2598) kataballo

From  (G2596) kata and  (G1018) brabeuo (in its original sense); to award the price against, i.e. (figuratively) to defraud (of salvation) -- beguile of reward. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G1018) brabeuo
From  (G2605) kataggello; a proclaimer -- setter forth. see GREEK  (G2605) kataggello
From  (G2596) kata and the base of  (G32) aggelos; to proclaim, promulgate -- declare, preach, shew, speak of, teach. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G32) aggelos
To laugh down, i.e. Deride -- laugh to scorn.
From  (G2596) kata and  (G1097) ginosko; to note against, i.e. Find fault with -- blame, condemn. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G1097) ginosko
From  (G2596) kata and the base of  (G4486) rhegnumi; to rend in pieces, i.e. Crack apart -- break. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G4486) rhegnumi
From  (G2596) kata and  (G71) ago; to lead down; specially, to moor a vessel -- bring (down, forth), (bring to) land, touch. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G71) ago
From  (G2596) kata and  (G75) agonizomai; to struggle against, i.e. (by implication) to overcome -- subdue. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G75) agonizomai
From  (G2596) kata and  (G1210) deo; to tie down, i.e. Bandage (a wound) -- bind up. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G1210) deo
From  (G2596) kata intensive and  (G1212) delos; manifest -- far more evident. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G1212) delos
From  (G2596) kata and a derivative of  (G1349) dike; to adjudge against, i.e. Pronounce guilty -- condemn. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G1349) dike
From  (G2596) kata and  (G1377) dioko; to hunt down, i.e. Search for -- follow after. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G1377) dioko
From  (G2596) kata and  (G1402) douloo; to enslave utterly -- bring into bondage. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G1402) douloo
From  (G2596) kata and a derivative of  (G1413) dunastes; to exercise dominion against, i.e. Oppress -- oppress. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G1413) dunastes

From  (G2596) kata and  (G153) aischunomai; to shame down, i.e. Disgrace or (by implication) put to the blush -- confound, dishonour, (be a-, make a-)shame(-d). see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G153) aischunomai
From  (G2596) kata and  (G2545) kaio; to burn down (to the ground), i.e. Consume wholly -- burn (up, utterly). see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G2545) kaio
From  (G2596) kata and  (G2572) kalupto; to cover wholly, i.e. Veil -- cover, hide. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G2572) kalupto
From  (G2596) kata and  (G2744) kauchaomai; to exult against (i.e. Over) -- boast (against), glory, rejoice against. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G2744) kauchaomai

column8: recline, lie, sit down at meals
column9: From  (G2596) kata and  (G2749) keimai; to lie down, i.e. (by implication) be sick; specially, to recline at a meal -- keep, lie, sit at meat (down). see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G2749) keimai
From  (G2596) kata and  (G2806) klao; to break down, i.e. Divide -- break. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G2806) klao
From  (G2596) kata and  (G2808) kleio; to shut down (in a dungeon), i.e. Incarcerate -- shut up. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G2808) kleio

From  (G2596) kata and a derivative of a compound of  (G2819) kleros and  (G1325) didomi; to be a giver of lots to each, i.e. (by implication) to apportion an estate -- divide by lot. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G2819) kleros see GREEK  (G1325) didomi

column8: make lie down or recline at meals
column9: From  (G2596) kata and  (G2827) klino; to recline down, i.e. (specially) to take a place at table -- (make) sit down (at meat). see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G2827) klino
From  (G2596) kata and the base of  (G2830) kludon; to dash (wash) down, i.e. (by implication) to deluge -- overflow. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G2830) kludon
From  (G2626) katakluzo; an inundation -- flood. see GREEK  (G2626) katakluzo
From  (G2596) kata and  (G190) akoloutheo; to accompany closely -- follow (after). see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G190) akoloutheo
From  (G2596) kata and  (G2875) kopto; to chop down, i.e. Mangle -- cut. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G2875) kopto
From  (G2596) kata and a derivative of  (G2911) kremnos; to precipitate down -- cast down headlong. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G2911) kremnos
From  (G2632) katakrino; an adverse sentence (the verdict) -- condemnation. see GREEK  (G2632) katakrino
From  (G2596) kata and  (G2919) krino; to judge against, i.e. Sentence -- condemn, damn. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G2919) krino
From  (G2632) katakrino; sentencing adversely (the act) -- condemn(-ation). see GREEK  (G2632) katakrino

column8: exercise dominion over, be lord over, overcome.
column9: From  (G2596) kata and  (G2961) kurieuo; to lord against, i.e. Control, subjugate -- exercise dominion over (lordship), be lord over, overcome. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G2961) kurieuo
From  (G2637) katalalos; to be a traducer, i.e. To slander -- speak against (evil of). see GREEK  (G2637) katalalos
From  (G2637) katalalos; defamation -- backbiting, evil speaking. see GREEK  (G2637) katalalos
From  (G2596) kata and the base of  (G2980) laleo; talkative against, i.e. A slanderer -- backbiter. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G2980) laleo

From  (G2596) kata and  (G2983) lambano; to take eagerly, i.e. Seize, possess, etc. (literally or figuratively) -- apprehend, attain, come upon, comprehend, find, obtain, perceive, (over-)take. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G2983) lambano

column8: to enroll, place on a list
column9: From  (G2596) kata and  (G3004) lego (in its original meaning); to lay down, i.e. (figuratively) to enrol -- take into the number. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G3004) lego
From  (G2641) kataleipo; a remainder, i.e. (by implication) a few -- remnant. see GREEK  (G2641) kataleipo
From  (G2596) kata and  (G3007) leipo; to leave down, i.e. Behind; by implication, to abandon, have remaining -- forsake, leave, reserve. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G3007) leipo
From  (G2596) kata and  (G3034) lithazo; to stone down, i.e. To death -- stone. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G3034) lithazo
From  (G2644) katallasso; exchange (figuratively, adjustment), i.e. Restoration to (the divine) favor -- atonement, reconciliation(-ing). see GREEK  (G2644) katallasso
From  (G2596) kata and  (G236) allasso; to change mutually, i.e. (figuratively) to compound a difference -- reconcile. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G236) allasso
From  (G2596) kata and  (G3062) loipoy; left down (behind), i.e remaining (plural the rest) -- residue. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G3062) loipoy
From  (G2647) kataluo; properly, a dissolution (breaking up of a journey), i.e. (by implication) a lodging-place -- guestchamber, inn. see GREEK  (G2647) kataluo

column8: destroy, dissolve, lodge, come to nought
column9: From  (G2596) kata and  (G3089) luo; to loosen down (disintegrate), i.e. (by implication) to demolish (literally or figuratively); specially (compare  (G2646) kataluma) to halt for the night -- destroy, dissolve, be guest, lodge, come to nought, overthrow, throw down. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G3089) luo see GREEK  (G2646) kataluma
From  (G2596) kata and  (G3129) manthano; to learn thoroughly, i.e. (by implication) to note carefully -- consider. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G3129) manthano

column7: to testify or bear witness against
column9: From  (G2596) kata and  (G3140) martureo; to testify against -- witness against. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G3140) martureo
From  (G2596) kata and  (G3306) meno; to stay fully, i.e. Reside -- abide. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G3306) meno

From  (G2596) kata and accusative case plural feminine of  (G3441) monos (with  (G5561) chora implied); according to sole places, i.e. (adverbially) separately -- alone. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G3441) monos see GREEK  (G5561) chora

From  (G2596) kata and a derivative of  (G4192) ponos; to labor down, i.e. Wear with toil (figuratively, harass) -- oppress, vex. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G4192) ponos

From  (G2596) kata and  (G705) arithmeo; to reckon among -- number with. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G705) arithmeo

From  (G2675) katartizo; thorough equipment (subjectively) -- perfection. see GREEK  (G2675) katartizo
From  (G2675) katartizo; complete furnishing (objectively) -- perfecting. see GREEK  (G2675) katartizo
From  (G2596) kata and  (G4579) seio; to sway downward, i.e. Make a signal -- beckon. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G4579) seio

From  (G2596) kata and  (G4724) stello; to put down, i.e. Quell -- appease, quiet. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G4724) stello

From  (G2596) kata and  (G4762) strepho; to turn upside down, i.e. Upset -- overthrow. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G4762) strepho

From  (G2596) kata and  (G4766) stronnumi; to strew down, i.e. (by implication) to prostrate (slay) -- overthrow. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G4766) stronnumi
From  (G2596) kata and  (G4951) suro; to drag down, i.e. Arrest judicially -- hale. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G4951) suro
From  (G2596) kata and  (G4969) sphazo; to kill down, i.e. Slaughter -- slay. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G4969) sphazo
From  (G2596) kata and  (G4972) sphragizo; to seal closely -- seal. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G4972) sphragizo
From  (G2722) katecho; a holding down, i.e. Occupancy -- possession. see GREEK  (G2722) katecho

From  (G2596) kata and  (G5343) pheugo; to flee down (away) -- flee. see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G5343) pheugo

Probably from kegchros (millet); Cenchreae, a port of Corinth -- Cencrea.

From  (G2795) kineo; a stirring -- moving. see GREEK  (G2795) kineo

column9: Of Hebrew origin ( (H3929) Lemek); Lamech (i.e. Lemek), a patriarch -- Lamech. see HEBREW  (H3929) Lemek
From  (G2989) lampo; a "lamp" or flambeau -- lamp, light, torch. see GREEK  (G2989) lampo
From the same as  (G2985) lampas; radiant; by analogy, limpid; figuratively, magnificent or sumptuous (in appearance) -- bright, clear, gay, goodly, gorgeous, white. see GREEK  (G2985) lampas
From  (G2986) lampros; brilliancy -- brightness. see GREEK  (G2986) lampros
Adverb from  (G2986) lampros; brilliantly, i.e. Figuratively, luxuriously -- sumptuously. see GREEK  (G2986) lampros
A primary verb; to beam, i.e. Radiate brilliancy (literally or figuratively) -- give light, shine.

A prolonged form of a primary verb, which is used only as an alternate in certain tenses; to lie hid (literally or figuratively); often used adverbially, unwittingly -- be hid, be ignorant of, unawares.
From a compound of las (a stone) and the base of  (G3584) xeros (in its original sense of scraping); rock-quarried -- hewn in stone. see GREEK  (G3584) xeros
Apparently a primary word; a people (in general; thus differing from  (G1218) demos, which denotes one's own populace) -- people. see GREEK  (G1218) demos
From a compound of  (G2992) laos and  (G1349) dike; Laodicia, a place in Asia Minor -- Laodicea. see GREEK  (G2992) laos see GREEK  (G1349) dike
From  (G2993) Laodikeia; a Laodicean, i.e. Inhabitant of Laodicia -- Laodicean. see GREEK  (G2993) Laodikeia
Of uncertain derivation; the throat ("larynx") -- throat.
Of uncertain origin; Lasaea, a place in Crete -- Lasea.
A strengthened form of a primary verb, which only occurs in this and another prolonged form as alternate in certain tenses; to crack open (from a fall) -- burst asunder.
From the same as the first part of  (G2991) laxeutos and the base of  (G5114) tomoteros; to quarry -- hew. see GREEK  (G2991) laxeutos see GREEK  (G5114) tomoteros
From  (G3000) latreuo; ministration of God, i.e. Worship -- (divine) service. see GREEK  (G3000) latreuo
From latris (a hired menial); to minister (to God), i.e. Render religious homage -- serve, do the service, worship(-per).
From lachaino (to dig); a vegetable -- herb.
Of uncertain origin; Lebbaeus, a Christian -- Lebbaeus.
Of Latin origin; a "legion", i.e. Roman regiment (figuratively) -- legion.

A primary verb; properly, to "lay" forth, i.e. (figuratively) relate (in words (usually of systematic or set discourse; whereas  (G2036) epo and  (G5346) phemi generally refer to an individual expression or speech respectively; while  (G4483) rheo is properly to break silence merely, and  (G2980) laleo means an extended or random harangue)); by implication, to mean -- ask, bid, boast, call, describe, give out, name, put forth, say(-ing, on), shew, speak, tell, utter. see GREEK  (G2036) epo see GREEK  (G5346) phemi see GREEK  (G4483) rheo see GREEK  (G2980) laleo
From  (G3007) leipo; a remainder -- remnant. see GREEK  (G3007) leipo
Apparently a primary word; smooth, i.e. "level" -- smooth.
A primary verb; to leave, i.e. (intransitively or passively) to fail or be absent -- be destitute (wanting), lack.

column7: to serve the state, by anal. to perform religious service
column9: From  (G3011) leitourgos; to be a public servant, i.e. (by analogy) to perform religious or charitable functions (worship, obey, relieve) -- minister. see GREEK  (G3011) leitourgos
From  (G3008) leitourgeo; public function (as priest ("liturgy") or almsgiver) -- ministration(-try), service. see GREEK  (G3008) leitourgeo
From the same as  (G3008) leitourgeo; functional publicly ("liturgic"); i.e. Beneficient -- ministering. see GREEK  (G3008) leitourgeo

column7: a public servant, a minister, a servant
column9: From a derivative of  (G2992) laos and  (G2041) ergon; a public servant, i.e. A functionary in the Temple or Gospel, or (genitive case) a worshipper (of God) or benefactor (of man) -- minister(-ed). see GREEK  (G2992) laos see GREEK  (G2041) ergon
Of Latin origin; a "linen" cloth, i.e. Apron -- towel.
From lepo (to peel); a flake -- scale.
From the same as  (G3013) lepis; scaliness, i.e. "leprosy" -- leprosy. see GREEK  (G3013) lepis
From the same as  (G3014) lepra; scaly, i.e. Leprous (a leper) -- leper. see GREEK  (G3014) lepra
Neuter of a derivative of the same as  (G3013) lepis; something scaled (light), i.e. A small coin -- mite. see GREEK  (G3013) lepis

column7: Levi, the name of several Israelites
column9: Of Hebrew origin ( (H3878) Leviy); Levi, the name of three Israelites -- Levi. Compare  (G3018) Leuis. see GREEK  (G3018) Leuis see HEBREW  (H3878) Leviy
A form of  (G3017) Leui; Lewis (i.e. Levi), a Christian -- Levi. see GREEK  (G3017) Leui

column7: a Levite, a descendant of Levi
column9: From  (G3017) Leui; a Levite, i.e. Descendant of Levi -- Levite. see GREEK  (G3017) Leui
From  (G3019) Leuites; Levitic, i.e. Relating to the Levites -- Levitical. see GREEK  (G3019) Leuites
From  (G3022) leukos; to whiten -- make white, whiten. see GREEK  (G3022) leukos
From luke ("light"); white -- white.
A primary word; a "lion" -- lion.
From  (G2990) lanthano; forgetfulness -- + forget. see GREEK  (G2990) lanthano
Apparently a primary word; a trough, i.e. Wine-vat -- winepress.
Apparently a primary word; twaddle, i.e. An incredible story -- idle tale.
From leizomai (to plunder); a brigand -- robber, thief.
From  (G2983) lambano; receipt (the act) -- receiving. see GREEK  (G2983) lambano
Of uncertain affinity; much (adverbially) -- exceeding, great(-ly), sore, very (+ chiefest).
Of foreign origin ( (H3828) lbownah); the incense-tree, i.e. (by implication) incense itself -- frankincense. see HEBREW  (H3828) lbownah
From  (G3030) libanos; frankincense, i.e. (by extension) a censer for burning it -- censer. see GREEK  (G3030) libanos

column7: Freedman, the name of a synagogue
column9: Of Latin origin; a Roman freedman -- Libertine.

column7: the west bank of the Nile, Libya, a region in N. Africa
column9: Probably from  (G3047) lips; Libye, a region of Africa -- Libya. see GREEK  (G3047) lips
From  (G3037) lithos; to lapidate -- stone. see GREEK  (G3037) lithos
From  (G3037) lithos; stony, i.e. Made of stone -- of stone. see GREEK  (G3037) lithos

column7: to pelt with stones, to stone
column9: From a compound of  (G3037) lithos and  (G906) ballo; to throw stones, i.e. Lapidate -- stone, cast stones. see GREEK  (G3037) lithos see GREEK  (G906) ballo
Apparently a primary word; a stone (literally or figuratively) -- (mill-, stumbling-)stone.

From  (G3037) lithos and a derivative of  (G4766) stronnumi; stone-strewed, i.e. A tessellated mosaic on which the Roman tribunal was placed -- Pavement. see GREEK  (G3037) lithos see GREEK  (G4766) stronnumi
From likmos, the equivalent of liknon (a winnowing fan or basket); to winnow, i.e. (by analogy), to triturate -- grind to powder.
Apparently a primary word; a harbor -- haven. Compare  (G2568) Kaloi Limenes. see GREEK  (G2568) Kaloi Limenes
Probably from  (G3040) limen (through the idea of nearness of shore); a pond (large or small) -- lake. see GREEK  (G3040) limen
Probably from  (G3007) leipo (through the idea of destitution); a scarcity of food -- dearth, famine, hunger. see GREEK  (G3007) leipo
Probably a primary word; flax, i.e. (by implication) "linen" -- linen.
Perhaps from  (G3043) linon; Linus, a Christian -- Linus. see GREEK  (G3043) linon
From lipos (grease); fat, i.e. (figuratively) sumptuous -- dainty.

column7: a pound (in weight, by Rom. standards)
column9: Of Latin origin (libra); a pound in weight -- pound.
Probably from leibo (to pour a "libation"); the south(- west) wind (as bringing rain, i.e. (by extension) the south quarter) -- southwest.
From  (G3056) logos (in the commercial sense); a contribution -- collection, gathering. see GREEK  (G3056) logos

Middle voice from  (G3056) logos; to take an inventory, i.e. Estimate (literally or figuratively) -- conclude, (ac-)count (of), + despise, esteem, impute, lay, number, reason, reckon, suppose, think (on). see GREEK  (G3056) logos
From  (G3056) logos; rational ("logical") -- reasonable, of the word. see GREEK  (G3056) logos
Neuter of  (G3052) logios; an utterance (of God) -- oracle. see GREEK  (G3052) logios
From  (G3056) logos; fluent, i.e. An orator -- eloquent. see GREEK  (G3056) logos
From  (G3049) logizomai; computation, i.e. (figuratively) reasoning (conscience, conceit) -- imagination, thought. see GREEK  (G3049) logizomai
From a compound of  (G3056) logos and  (G3164) machomai; to be disputatious (on trifles) -- strive about words. see GREEK  (G3056) logos see GREEK  (G3164) machomai
From the same as  (G3054) logomacheo; disputation about trifles ("logomachy") -- strife of words. see GREEK  (G3054) logomacheo

column7: a word (as embodying an idea), a statement, a speech
column9: From  (G3004) lego; something said (including the thought); by implication, a topic (subject of discourse), also reasoning (the mental faculty) or motive; by extension, a computation; specially, (with the article in John) the Divine Expression (i.e. Christ) -- account, cause, communication, X concerning, doctrine, fame, X have to do, intent, matter, mouth, preaching, question, reason, + reckon, remove, say(-ing), shew, X speaker, speech, talk, thing, + none of these things move me, tidings, treatise, utterance, word, work. see GREEK  (G3004) lego
Perhaps a primary word; a "lance" -- spear.
From  (G3060) loidoros; to reproach, i.e. Vilify -- revile. see GREEK  (G3060) loidoros
From  (G3060) loidoros; slander or vituperation -- railing, reproach(-fully). see GREEK  (G3060) loidoros
From loidos (mischief); abusive, i.e. A blackguard -- railer, reviler.
Of uncertain affinity; a plague (literally, the disease, or figuratively, a pest) -- pestilence(-t).
Masculine plural of a derivative of  (G3007) leipo; remaining ones -- other, which remain, remnant, residue, rest. see GREEK  (G3007) leipo
Neuter singular of the same as  (G3062) loipoy; something remaining (adverbially) -- besides, finally, furthermore, (from) henceforth, moreover, now, + it remaineth, then. see GREEK  (G3062) loipoy
Genitive case singular of the same as  (G3062) loipoy; remaining time -- from henceforth. see GREEK  (G3062) loipoy
Contracted from Latin Lucanus; Lucas, a Christian -- Lucas, Luke.

column7: Lucius, the name of two Christians
column9: Of Latin origin; illuminative; Lucius, a Christian -- Lucius.
From  (G3068) louo; a bath, i.e. (figuratively), baptism -- washing. see GREEK  (G3068) louo

A primary verb; to bathe (the whole person; whereas  (G3538) nipto means to wet a part only, and  (G4150) pluno to wash, cleanse garments exclusively) -- wash. see GREEK  (G3538) nipto see GREEK  (G4150) pluno
Of Hebrew origin ( (H3850) Lod); Lydda (i.e. Lod), a place in Palestine -- Lydda. see HEBREW  (H3850) Lod
Properly, feminine of Ludios (of foreign origin) (a Lydian, in Asia Minor); Lydia, a Christian woman: -Lydia.

column7: Lycaonia, a region in Asia Minor
column9: Perhaps remotely from  (G3074) lukos; Lycaonia, a region of Asia Minor -- Lycaonia. see GREEK  (G3074) lukos
Adverb from a derivative of  (G3071) Lukaonia; Lycaonistically, i.e. In the language of the Lycaonians -- in the speech of Lycaonia. see GREEK  (G3071) Lukaonia

column7: Lycia, a region of Asia Minor
column9: Probably remotely from  (G3074) lukos; Lycia, a province of Asia Minor -- Lycia. see GREEK  (G3074) lukos
Perhaps akin to the base of  (G3022) leukos (from the whitish hair); a wolf -- wolf. see GREEK  (G3022) leukos
Middle voice from a probably derivative of  (G3089) luo (meaning filth); properly, to soil, i.e. (figuratively) insult (maltreat) -- make havock of. see GREEK  (G3089) luo
From  (G3077) lupe; to distress; reflexively or passively, to be sad -- cause grief, grieve, be in heaviness, (be) sorrow(-ful), be (make) sorry. see GREEK  (G3077) lupe

column7: pain of body or mind, grief, sorrow
column9: Apparently a primary word; sadness -- grief, grievous, + grudgingly, heaviness, sorrow.

column7: ending sorrow, Lysanias, a governor of Abilene
column9: From  (G3080) lusis and ania (trouble); grief-dispelling; Lysanias, a governor of Abilene -- Lysanias. see GREEK  (G3080) lusis
Of uncertain affinity; Lysias, a Roman -- Lysias.
From  (G3089) luo; a loosening, i.e. (specially), divorce -- to be loosed. see GREEK  (G3089) luo

Third person singular present indicative active of a derivative of a compound of  (G3080) lusis and  (G5056) telos; impersonally, it answers the purpose, i.e. Is advantageous -- it is better. see GREEK  (G3080) lusis see GREEK  (G5056) telos
Of uncertain origin; Lystra, a place in Asia Minor -- Lystra.
From  (G3089) luo; something to loosen with, i.e. A redemption price (figuratively, atonement) -- ransom. see GREEK  (G3089) luo

column7: to release by paying a ransom, to redeem
column9: From  (G3083) lutron; to ransom (literally or figuratively) -- redeem. see GREEK  (G3083) lutron
From  (G3084) lutroo; a ransoming (figuratively) -- + redeemed, redemption. see GREEK  (G3084) lutroo
From  (G3084) lutroo; a redeemer (figuratively) -- deliverer. see GREEK  (G3084) lutroo
From  (G3088) luchnos; a lamp-stand (literally or figuratively) -- candlestick. see GREEK  (G3088) luchnos
From the base of  (G3022) leukos; a portable lamp or other illuminator (literally or figuratively) -- candle, light. see GREEK  (G3022) leukos

column7: to loose, to release, to dissolve
column9: A primary verb; to "loosen" (literally or figuratively) -- break (up), destroy, dissolve, (un-)loose, melt, put off. Compare  (G4486) rhegnumi. see GREEK  (G4486) rhegnumi
Of uncertain origin; Lois, a Christian woman -- Lois.
Of Hebrew origin ( (H3876) Lowt); Lot, a patriarch -- Lot. see HEBREW  (H3876) Lowt
Probably of Hebrew origin; Maath, an Israelite -- Maath.

column7: Magadan, an unidentified place near the Sea of Galilee
column9: Of Chaldee origin (compare  (H4026) migdal); the tower; Magdala (i.e. Migdala), a place in Palestine -- Magdala. see HEBREW  (H4026) migdal

column7: Magdalene, of Magdala, a place on the coast of the Sea of Galilee near Tiberias
column9: Feminine of a derivative of  (G3093) Magdala; a female Magdalene, i.e. Inhabitant of Magdala -- Magdalene. see GREEK  (G3093) Magdala
From  (G3096) mageuo; "magic" -- sorcery. see GREEK  (G3096) mageuo
From  (G3097) magos; to practice magic -- use sorcery. see GREEK  (G3097) magos

column7: a Magian, an (Oriental) astrologer, by implication a magician
column9: Of foreign origin ( (H7248) Rab-Mag); a Magian, i.e. Oriental scientist; by implication, a magician -- sorcerer, wise man. see HEBREW  (H7248) Rab-Mag
Of Hebrew origin ( (H4031) Magowg); Magog, a foreign nation, i.e. (figuratively) an Antichristian party -- Magog. see HEBREW  (H4031) Magowg
Of Hebrew origin ( (H4080) Midyan); Madian (i.e. Midian), a region of Arabia -- Madian. see HEBREW  (H4080) Midyan

column7: to be a disciple, to make a disciple
column9: From  (G3101) mathetes; intransitively, to become a pupil; transitively, to disciple, i.e. Enrol as scholar -- be disciple, instruct, teach. see GREEK  (G3101) mathetes
From  (G3129) manthano; a learner, i.e. Pupil -- disciple. see GREEK  (G3129) manthano
Feminine from  (G3101) mathetes; a female pupil -- disciple. see GREEK  (G3101) mathetes
Of Hebrew origin ( (H4968) Mthuwshelach); Mathusala (i.e. Methushelach), an antediluvian -- Mathusala. see HEBREW  (H4968) Mthuwshelach
Probably of Hebrew origin; Mainan, an Israelite -- Mainan.
Middle voice from a primary mao (to long for; through the idea of insensate craving); to rave as a "maniac" -- be beside self (mad).
From  (G3107) makarios; to beatify, i.e. Pronounce (or esteem) fortunate -- call blessed, count happy. see GREEK  (G3107) makarios
A prolonged form of the poetical makar (meaning the same); supremely blest; by extension, fortunate, well off -- blessed, happy(X -ier).
From  (G3106) makarizo; beatification, i.e. Attribution of good fortune -- blessedness. see GREEK  (G3106) makarizo
From  (G3110) Makedon; Macedonia, a region of Greece -- Macedonia. see GREEK  (G3110) Makedon

column7: a Macedonian, an inhabitant of Macedonia
column9: Of uncertain derivation; a Macedon (Macedonian), i.e. Inhabitant of Macedonia -- of Macedonia, Macedonian.
Of Latin origin (macellum); a butcher's stall, meat market or provision-shop -- shambles.

Feminine accusative case singular of  (G3117) makros ( (G3598) hodos being implied); at a distance (literally or figuratively) -- (a-)far (off), good (great) way off. see GREEK  (G3117) makros see GREEK  (G3598) hodos
Adverb from  (G3117) makros; from a distance or afar -- afar off, from far. see GREEK  (G3117) makros

column8: be longsuffering, have patience, patiently endure.
column9: From the same as  (G3116) makrothumos; to be long-spirited, i.e. (objectively) forbearing or (subjectively) patient -- bear (suffer) long, be longsuffering, have (long) patience, be patient, patiently endure. see GREEK  (G3116) makrothumos
From the same as  (G3116) makrothumos; longanimity, i.e. (objectively) forbearance or (subjectively) fortitude -- longsuffering, patience. see GREEK  (G3116) makrothumos
Adverb of a compound of  (G3117) makros and  (G2372) thumos; with long (enduring) temper, i.e. Leniently -- patiently. see GREEK  (G3117) makros see GREEK  (G2372) thumos
From  (G3372) mekos; long (in place (distant) or time (neuter plural)) -- far, long. see GREEK  (G3372) mekos
From  (G3117) makros and  (G5550) chronos; long-timed, i.e. Long-lived -- live long. see GREEK  (G3117) makros see GREEK  (G5550) chronos
From  (G3120) malakos; softness, i.e. Enervation (debility) -- disease. see GREEK  (G3120) malakos
Of uncertain affinity; soft, i.e. Fine (clothing); figuratively, a catamite -- effeminate, soft.
Of Hebrew origin ( (H4111) Mahalal'el); Maleleel (i.e. Mahalalel), an antediluvian -- Maleleel. see HEBREW  (H4111) Mahalal'el
Neuter plural of the superlative of an apparently primary adverb mala (very); (adverbially) most (in the greatest degree) or particularly -- chiefly, most of all, (e-)specially.

Neuter of the comparative of the same as  (G3122) malista; (adverbially) more (in a greater degree)) or rather -- + better, X far, (the) more (and more), (so) much (the more), rather. see GREEK  (G3122) malista

column7: Malchus, a slave of the high priest
column9: Of Hebrew origin ( (H4429) Melek); Malchus, an Israelite -- Malchus. see HEBREW  (H4429) Melek
Of natural origin ("mammy"); a grandmother -- grandmother.
Of Chaldee origin (confidence, i.e. Wealth, personified); mammonas, i.e. Avarice (deified) -- mammon.
Of uncertain origin; Manaen, a Christian -- Manaen.
Of Hebrew origin ( (H4519) Mnashsheh); Mannasses (i.e. Menashsheh), an Israelite -- Manasses. see HEBREW  (H4519) Mnashsheh
Prolongation from a primary verb, another form of which, matheo, is used as an alternate in certain tenses; to learn (in any way) -- learn, understand.
From  (G3105) mainomai; craziness -- (+ make) X mad. see GREEK  (G3105) mainomai
Of Hebrew origin ( (H4478) man); manna (i.e. Man), an edible gum -- manna. see HEBREW  (H4478) man

From a derivative of  (G3105) mainomai (meaning a prophet, as supposed to rave through inspiration); to divine, i.e. Utter spells (under pretense of foretelling -- by soothsaying. see GREEK  (G3105) mainomai
Of uncertain affinity; to extinguish (as fire), i.e. (figuratively and passively) to pass away -- fade away.
Of Chaldee origin (meaning our Lord has come); maranatha, i.e. An exclamation of the approaching divine judgment -- Maran-atha.
From margaros (a pearl-oyster); a pearl -- pearl.
Probably of Chaldee origin (meaning mistress); Martha, a Christian woman -- Martha.

column7: Mary, the name of several Christian women
column9: Or Mariam (mar-ee-am') of Hebrew origin ( (H4813) Miryam); Maria or Mariam (i.e. Mirjam), the name of six Christian females -- Mary. see HEBREW  (H4813) Miryam
Of Latin origin; Marcus, a Christian -- Marcus, Mark.
From marmairo (to glisten); marble (as sparkling white) -- marble.

From  (G3144) martus; to be a witness, i.e. Testify (literally or figuratively) -- charge, give (evidence), bear record, have (obtain, of) good (honest) report, be well reported of, testify, give (have) testimony, (be, bear, give, obtain) witness. see GREEK  (G3144) martus
From  (G3144) martus; evidence given (judicially or genitive case) -- record, report, testimony, witness. see GREEK  (G3144) martus

Neuter of a presumed derivative of  (G3144) martus; something evidential, i.e. (genitive case) evidence given or (specially), the Decalogue (in the sacred Tabernacle) -- to be testified, testimony, witness. see GREEK  (G3144) martus

column7: to summon as witness, to affirm
column9: Middle voice from  (G3144) martus; to be adduced as a witness, i.e. (figuratively) to obtest (in affirmation or exhortation) -- take to record, testify. see GREEK  (G3144) martus
Of uncertain affinity; a witness (literally (judicially) or figuratively (genitive case)); by analogy, a "martyr" -- martyr, record, witness.
From a primary masso (to handle or squeeze); to chew -- gnaw.
From  (G3148) mastix; to flog (literally or figuratively) -- scourge. see GREEK  (G3148) mastix
From  (G3149) mastos; to whip (literally) -- scourge. see GREEK  (G3149) mastos

Probably from the base of  (G3145) massaomai (through the idea of contact); a whip (literally, the Roman flagellum for criminals; figuratively, a disease) -- plague, scourging. see GREEK  (G3145) massaomai
From the base of  (G3145) massaomai; a (properly, female) breast (as if kneaded up) -- pap. see GREEK  (G3145) massaomai
From  (G3151) mataiologos; random talk, i.e. Babble -- vain jangling. see GREEK  (G3151) mataiologos
From  (G3152) mataios and  (G3004) lego; an idle (i.e. Senseless or mischievous) talker, i.e. A wrangler -- vain talker. see GREEK  (G3152) mataios see GREEK  (G3004) lego
From the base of  (G3155) maten; empty, i.e. (literally) profitless, or (specially), an idol -- vain, vanity. see GREEK  (G3155) maten
From  (G3152) mataios; inutility; figuratively, transientness; morally, depravity -- vanity. see GREEK  (G3152) mataios
From  (G3152) mataios; to render (passively, become) foolish, i.e. (morally) wicked or (specially), idolatrous -- become vain. see GREEK  (G3152) mataios

Accusative case of a derivative of the base of  (G3145) massaomai (through the idea of tentative manipulation, i.e. Unsuccessful search, or else of punishment); folly, i.e. (adverbially) to no purpose -- in vain. see GREEK  (G3145) massaomai
A shorter form of  (G3164) machomai; Matthaeus (i.e. Matthitjah), an Israelite and a Christian -- Matthew. see GREEK  (G3164) machomai
Of Hebrew origin ( (H4977) Mattan); Matthan (i.e. Mattan), an Israelite -- Matthan. see HEBREW  (H4977) Mattan
Probably a shortened form of  (G3161) Mattathias; Matthat (i.e. Mattithjah), the name of two Israelites -- Mathat. see GREEK  (G3161) Mattathias
Apparently a shortened form of  (G3161) Mattathias; Matthias (i.e. Mattithjah), an Israelite -- Matthias. see GREEK  (G3161) Mattathias
Probably a shortened form of  (G3161) Mattathias (compare  (G4992) soterion); Mattatha (i.e. Mattithjah), an Israelite -- Mattatha. see GREEK  (G3161) Mattathias see GREEK  (G4992) soterion
Of Hebrew origin ( (H4993) Mattithyah); Mattathias (i.e. Mattithjah), an Israelite and a Christian -- Mattathias. see HEBREW  (H4993) Mattithyah
Probably feminine of a presumed derivative of  (G3163) mache; a knife, i.e. Dirk; figuratively, war, judicial punishment -- sword. see GREEK  (G3163) mache
From  (G3164) machomai; a battle, i.e. (figuratively) controversy -- fighting, strive, striving. see GREEK  (G3164) machomai
Middle voice of an apparently primary verb; to war, i.e. (figuratively) to quarrel, dispute -- fight, strive.
A shorter (and probably originally) from of  (G1691) eme; me -- I, me, my. see GREEK  (G1691) eme

From a compound of  (G3173) megas and aucheo (to boast; akin to  (G837) auzano and  (G2744) kauchaomai); to talk big, i.e. Be grandiloquent (arrogant, egotistic) -- boast great things. see GREEK  (G3173) megas see GREEK  (G837) auzano see GREEK  (G2744) kauchaomai
From  (G3173) megas; magnificent, i.e. (neuter, plural as noun) a conspicuous favor, or (subjectively) perfection -- great things, wonderful works. see GREEK  (G3173) megas
From  (G3167) megaleios; superbness, i.e. Glory or splendor -- magnificence, majesty, mighty power. see GREEK  (G3167) megaleios
From  (G3173) megas and  (G4241) prepo; befitting greatness or magnificence (majestic) -- excellent. see GREEK  (G3173) megas see GREEK  (G4241) prepo
From  (G3173) megas; to make (or declare) great, i.e. Increase or (figuratively) extol -- enlarge, magnify, shew great. see GREEK  (G3173) megas
Adverb from  (G3173) megas; much -- greatly. see GREEK  (G3173) megas
From  (G3173) megas; greatness, i.e. (figuratively) divinity (often God himself) -- majesty. see GREEK  (G3173) megas

(including the prolonged forms, feminine megale, plural megaloi, etc.; compare also  (G3176) megistos,  (G3187) meizon); big (literally or figuratively, in a very wide application) -- (+ fear) exceedingly, great(-est), high, large, loud, mighty, + (be) sore (afraid), strong, X to years. see GREEK  (G3176) megistos see GREEK  (G3187) meizon
From  (G3173) megas; magnitude (figuratively) -- greatness. see GREEK  (G3173) megas
Plural from  (G3176) megistos; grandees -- great men, lords. see GREEK  (G3176) megistos
Superlative of  (G3173) megas; greatest or very great -- exceeding great. see GREEK  (G3173) megas
From  (G3326) meta and  (G2059) hermeneuo; to explain over, i.e. Translate -- (by) interpret(-ation). see GREEK  (G3326) meta see GREEK  (G2059) hermeneuo
Apparently a primary word; an intoxicant, i.e. (by implication) intoxication -- drunkenness.

Methistano meth-is-tan'-o from  (G3326) meta and  (G2476) histemi; to transfer, i.e. Carry away, depose or (figuratively) exchange, seduce -- put out, remove, translate, turn away. see GREEK  (G3326) meta see GREEK  (G2476) histemi
From a compound of  (G3326) meta and  (G3593) hodeuo (compare "method"); travelling over, i.e. Travesty (trickery) -- wile, lie in wait. see GREEK  (G3326) meta see GREEK  (G3593) hodeuo
From  (G3326) meta and  (G3725) horion; bounded alongside, i.e. Contiguous (neuter plural as noun, frontier) -- border. see GREEK  (G3326) meta see GREEK  (G3725) horion
A prolonged (transitive) form of  (G3184) methuo; to intoxicate -- be drunk(-en). see GREEK  (G3184) methuo
From  (G3184) methuo; tipsy, i.e. (as noun) a sot -- drunkard. see GREEK  (G3184) methuo
From another form of  (G3178) methe; to drink to intoxication, i.e. Get drunk -- drink well, make (be) drunk(-en). see GREEK  (G3178) methe
Neuter of  (G3187) meizon; (adverbially) in greater degree -- the more. see GREEK  (G3187) meizon
Continued comparative of  (G3187) meizon; still larger (figuratively) -- greater. see GREEK  (G3187) meizon
Irregular comparative of  (G3173) megas; larger (literally or figuratively, specially, in age) -- elder, greater(-est), more. see GREEK  (G3173) megas
Neuter of  (G3189) melas as noun; ink -- ink. see GREEK  (G3189) melas
Apparently a primary word; black -- black.
Of uncertain origin; Meleas, an Israelite -- Meleas.
From a presumed derivative of  (G3199) melo; to take care of, i.e. (by implication) revolve in the mind -- imagine, (pre-)meditate. see GREEK  (G3199) melo
Apparently a primary word; honey -- honey.
From  (G3192) meli; relating to honey, i.e. Bee (comb) -- honeycomb. see GREEK  (G3192) meli

column7: Melita (Malta), an island in the Mediterranean
column9: Of uncertain origin; Melita, an island in the Mediterranean -- Melita.

A strengthened form of  (G3199) melo (through the idea of expectation); to intend, i.e. Be about to be, do, or suffer something (of persons or things, especially events; in the sense of purpose, duty, necessity, probability, possibility, or hesitation) -- about, after that, be (almost), (that which is, things, + which was for) to come, intend, was to (be), mean, mind, be at the point, (be) ready, + return, shall (begin), (which, that) should (after, afterwards, hereafter) tarry, which was for, will, would, be yet. see GREEK  (G3199) melo

column7: a member or limb (of the body)
column9: Of uncertain affinity; a limb or part of the body -- member.

column7: Melchi, the name of two Israelites
column9: Of Hebrew origin ( (H4428) melek with pronominal suffix, my king); Melchi (i.e. Malki), the name of two Israelites -- Melchi. see HEBREW  (H4428) melek
Of Hebrew origin ( (H4442) Malkiy-Tsedeq); Melchisedek (i.e. Malkitsedek), a patriarch -- Melchisedec. see HEBREW  (H4442) Malkiy-Tsedeq

column7: to be an object of care
column9: A primary verb; to be of interest to, i.e. To concern (only third person singular present indicative used impersonally, it matters) -- (take) care.
Of Latin origin ("membrane"); a (written) sheep-skin -- parchment.
Middle voice of an apparently primary verb; to blame -- find fault.

From a presumed derivative of  (G3201) memphomai and moira (fate; akin to the base of  (G3313) meros); blaming fate, i.e. Querulous (discontented) -- complainer. see GREEK  (G3201) memphomai see GREEK  (G3313) meros

A primary particle; properly, indicative of affirmation or concession (in fact); usually followed by a contrasted clause with  (G1161) de (this one, the former, etc.) -- even, indeed, so, some, truly, verily. Often compounded with other particles in an intensive or asseverative sense. see GREEK  (G1161) de
From  (G3203) Not Used and  (G3767) oun and  (G1065) ge; so then at least -- nay but, yea doubtless (rather, verily). see GREEK  (G3203) Not Used see GREEK  (G3767) oun see GREEK  (G1065) ge
From  (G3203) Not Used and  (G5104) toi; indeed though, i.e. However -- also, but, howbeit, nevertheless, yet. see GREEK  (G3203) Not Used see GREEK  (G5104) toi
A primary verb; to stay (in a given place, state, relation or expectancy) -- abide, continue, dwell, endure, be present, remain, stand, tarry (for), X thine own.

From  (G3313) meros; to part, i.e. (literally) to apportion, bestow, share, or (figuratively) to disunite, differ -- deal, be difference between, distribute, divide, give participle see GREEK  (G3313) meros
From  (G3307) merizo (through the idea of distraction); solicitude -- care. see GREEK  (G3307) merizo

column7: to be anxious, to care for
column9: From  (G3308) merimna; to be anxious about -- (be, have) care(-ful), take thought. see GREEK  (G3308) merimna
Feminine of  (G3313) meros; a portion, i.e. Province, share or (abstractly) participation -- part (X -akers). see GREEK  (G3313) meros
From  (G3307) merizo; a separation or distribution -- dividing asunder, gift. see GREEK  (G3307) merizo
From  (G3307) merizo; an apportioner (administrator) -- divider. see GREEK  (G3307) merizo

From an obsolete but more primary form of meiromai (to get as a section or allotment); a division or share (literally or figuratively, in a wide application) -- behalf, course, coast, craft, particular (+ -ly), part (+ -ly), piece, portion, respect, side, some sort(-what).
From  (G3319) mesos and  (G2250) hemera; midday; by implication, the south -- noon, south. see GREEK  (G3319) mesos see GREEK  (G2250) hemera
From  (G3316) mesites; to interpose (as arbiter), i.e (by implication) to ratify (as surety) -- confirm. see GREEK  (G3316) mesites
From  (G3319) mesos; a go-between, i.e. (simply) an internunciator, or (by implication) a reconciler (intercessor) -- mediator. see GREEK  (G3319) mesos
Neuter of compound of  (G3319) mesos and  (G3571) nux; midnight (especially as a watch) -- midnight. see GREEK  (G3319) mesos see GREEK  (G3571) nux

column7: Mesopotamia, a region through which the Tigris and Euphrates Rivers flow
column9: From  (G3319) mesos and  (G4215) potamos; Mesopotamia (as lying between the Euphrates and the Tigris; compare  (H763) 'Aram Naharayim), a region of Asia -- Mesopotamia. see GREEK  (G3319) mesos see GREEK  (G4215) potamos see HEBREW  (H763) 'Aram Naharayim
From  (G3326) meta; middle (as an adjective or (neuter) noun) -- among, X before them, between, + forth, mid(-day, -night), midst, way. see GREEK  (G3326) meta
From  (G3319) mesos and  (G5109) toichos; a partition (figuratively) -- middle wall. see GREEK  (G3319) mesos see GREEK  (G5109) toichos
From a presumed compound of  (G3319) mesos and  (G3772) ouranos; mid-sky -- midst of heaven. see GREEK  (G3319) mesos see GREEK  (G3772) ouranos
From  (G3319) mesos; to form the middle, i.e. (in point of time), to be half-way over -- be about the midst. see GREEK  (G3319) mesos

column7: Messiah, the O.T. title corresponding to Christ
column9: Of Hebrew origin ( (H4899) mashiyach); the Messias (i.e. Mashiach), or Christ -- Messias. see HEBREW  (H4899) mashiyach
Of uncertain derivation -- replete (literally or figuratively) -- full.
From  (G3324) mestos; to replenish, i.e. (by implication) to intoxicate -- fill. see GREEK  (G3324) mestos

A primary preposition (often used adverbially); properly, denoting accompaniment; "amid" (local or causal); modified variously according to the case (genitive association, or accusative succession) with which it is joined; occupying an intermediate position between  (G575) apo or  (G1537) ek and  (G1519) eis or  (G4314) pros; less intimate than  (G1722) en and less close than  (G4862) sun) -- after(-ward), X that he again, against, among, X and, + follow, hence, hereafter, in, of, (up-)on, + our, X and setting, since, (un-)to, + together, when, with (+ -out). Often used in composition, in substantially the same relations of participation or proximity, and transfer or sequence. see GREEK  (G4314) pros see GREEK  (G575) apo see GREEK  (G1537) ek see GREEK  (G1519) eis see GREEK  (G1722) en see GREEK  (G4862) sun
From  (G3326) meta and the base of  (G939) basis; to change place -- depart, go, pass, remove. see GREEK  (G3326) meta see GREEK  (G939) basis
From  (G3326) meta and  (G906) ballo; to throw over, i.e. (middle voice figuratively) to turn about in opinion -- change mind. see GREEK  (G3326) meta see GREEK  (G906) ballo
From  (G3326) meta and  (G718) harmozo; to lead over, i.e. Transfer (direct) -- turn about. see GREEK  (G3326) meta see GREEK  (G718) harmozo
From  (G3326) meta and  (G1325) didomi; to give over, i.e. Share -- give, impart. see GREEK  (G3326) meta see GREEK  (G1325) didomi
From  (G3346) metatithemi; transposition, i.e. Transferral (to heaven), disestablishment (of a law) -- change, removing, translation. see GREEK  (G3346) metatithemi
From  (G3326) meta and  (G142) airo; to betake oneself, i.e. Remove (locally) -- depart. see GREEK  (G3326) meta see GREEK  (G142) airo

column7: to call from one place to another
column9: From  (G3326) meta and  (G2564) kaleo; to call elsewhere, i.e. Summon -- call (for, hither). see GREEK  (G3326) meta see GREEK  (G2564) kaleo
From  (G3326) meta and  (G2795) kineo; to stir to a place elsewhere, i.e. Remove (figuratively) -- move away. see GREEK  (G3326) meta see GREEK  (G2795) kineo
From  (G3326) meta and  (G2983) lambano; to participate; genitive case, to accept (and use) -- eat, have, be partaker, receive, take. see GREEK  (G3326) meta see GREEK  (G2983) lambano
From  (G3335) metalambano; participation -- taking. see GREEK  (G3335) metalambano
From  (G3326) meta and  (G236) allasso; to exchange -- change. see GREEK  (G3326) meta see GREEK  (G236) allasso
From  (G3326) meta and the middle voice of  (G3199) melo; to care afterwards, i.e. Regret -- repent (self). see GREEK  (G3326) meta see GREEK  (G3199) melo
From  (G3326) meta and  (G3445) morphoo; to transform (literally or figuratively, "metamorphose") -- change, transfigure, transform. see GREEK  (G3326) meta see GREEK  (G3445) morphoo

column9: From  (G3326) meta and  (G3539) noieo; to think differently or afterwards, i.e. Reconsider (morally, feel compunction) -- repent. see GREEK  (G3326) meta see GREEK  (G3539) noieo
From  (G3340) metanoeo; (subjectively) compunction (for guilt, including reformation); by implication, reversal (of (another's) decision) -- repentance. see GREEK  (G3340) metanoeo

From  (G3326) meta and a form of  (G4862) sun; betwixt (of place or person); (of time) as adjective, intervening, or (by implication) adjoining -- between, mean while, next. see GREEK  (G3326) meta see GREEK  (G4862) sun
From  (G3326) meta and  (G3992) pempo; to send from elsewhere, i.e. (middle voice) to summon or invite -- call (send) foreign see GREEK  (G3326) meta see GREEK  (G3992) pempo
From  (G3326) meta and  (G4762) strepho; to turn across, i.e. Transmute or (figuratively) corrupt -- pervert, turn. see GREEK  (G3326) meta see GREEK  (G4762) strepho

column9: From  (G3326) meta and a derivative of  (G4976) schema; to transfigure or disguise; figuratively, to apply (by accommodation) -- transfer, transform (self). see GREEK  (G3326) meta see GREEK  (G4976) schema

From  (G3326) meta and  (G1899) epeita; thereafter -- afterward. see GREEK  (G3326) meta see GREEK  (G1899) epeita
From  (G3326) meta and  (G2192) echo; to share or participate; by implication, belong to, eat (or drink) -- be partaker, pertain, take part, use. see GREEK  (G3326) meta see GREEK  (G2192) echo

column9: From a compound of  (G3326) meta and a collateral form of  (G142) airo or perhaps rather  (G109) aer (compare "meteor"); to raise in mid-air, i.e. (figuratively) suspend (passively, fluctuate or be anxious) -- be of doubtful mind. see GREEK  (G3326) meta see GREEK  (G142) airo see GREEK  (G109) aer

From a derivative of a compound of  (G3326) meta and  (G3624) oikos; a change of abode, i.e. (specially), expatriation -- X brought, carried(-ying) away (in-)to. see GREEK  (G3326) meta see GREEK  (G3624) oikos
From the same as  (G3350) metoikesia; to transfer as a settler or captive, i.e colonize or exile -- carry away, remove into. see GREEK  (G3350) metoikesia
From  (G3348) metecho; participation, i.e. Intercourse -- fellowship. see GREEK  (G3348) metecho
From  (G3348) metecho; participant, i.e. (as noun) a sharer; by implication, an associate -- fellow, partaker, partner. see GREEK  (G3348) metecho

From  (G3358) metron; to measure (i.e. Ascertain in size by a fixed standard); by implication, to admeasure (i.e. Allot by rule) -- figuratively, to estimate -- measure, mete. see GREEK  (G3358) metron
From  (G3354) metreo; a measurer, i.e. (specially), a certain standard measure of capacity for liquids -- firkin. see GREEK  (G3354) metreo
