From a presumed derivative of  (G4429) ptuo (and thus akin to  (G4422) ptoeo); to frighten -- terrify. see GREEK  (G4429) ptuo see GREEK  (G4422) ptoeo
From  (G4429) ptuo; saliva -- spittle. see GREEK  (G4429) ptuo

Probably akin to petannumi (to spread; and thus apparently allied to  (G4072) petomai through the idea of expansion, and to  (G4429) ptuo through that of flattening; compare  (G3961) pateo); to fold, i.e. Furl a scroll -- close. see GREEK  (G4072) petomai see GREEK  (G3961) pateo
A primary verb (compare  (G4428) ptusso); to spit -- spit. see GREEK  (G4428) ptusso
From the alternate of  (G4098) pipto; a ruin, i.e. (specially), lifeless body (corpse, carrion) -- dead body, carcase, corpse. see GREEK  (G4098) pipto
From the alternate of  (G4098) pipto; a crash, i.e. Downfall (literally or figuratively) -- fall. see GREEK  (G4098) pipto
From  (G4433) ptocheuo; beggary, i.e. Indigence (literally or figuratively) -- poverty. see GREEK  (G4433) ptocheuo

column7: to be a beggar, be destitute
column9: From  (G4434) ptochos; to be a beggar, i.e. (by implication) to become indigent (figuratively) -- become poor. see GREEK  (G4434) ptochos

column7: (of one who crouches and cowers, hence) beggarly, poor
column9: From ptosso (to crouch); akin to  (G4422) ptoeo and the alternate of  (G4098) pipto); a beggar (as cringing), i.e. Pauper (strictly denoting absolute or public mendicancy, although also used in a qualified or relative sense; whereas  (G3993) penes properly means only straitened circumstances in private), literally (often as noun) or figuratively (distressed) -- beggar(-ly), poor. see GREEK  (G4422) ptoeo see GREEK  (G4098) pipto see GREEK  (G3993) penes
From a primary pux (the fist as a weapon); the clenched hand, i.e. (only in dative case as adverb) with the fist (hard scrubbing) -- oft.

column7: Python, a mythical serpent slain by Apollo, divination
column9: From Putho (the name of the region where Delphi, the seat of the famous oracle, was located); a Python, i.e. (by analogy, with the supposed diviner there) inspiration (soothsaying) -- divination.
From the same as  (G4635) skenopoios; clasped (thick), i.e. (figuratively) frequent; neuter plural (as adverb) frequently -- often(-er). see GREEK  (G4635) skenopoios
From a derivative of the same as  (G4435) pugme; to box (with the fist), i.e. Contend (as a boxer) at the games (figuratively) -- fight. see GREEK  (G4435) pugme
Apparently a primary word; a gate, i.e. The leaf or wing of a folding entrance (literally or figuratively) -- gate.
From  (G4439) pule; a gate-way, door-way of a building or city; by implication, a portal or vestibule -- gate, porch. see GREEK  (G4439) pule

column7: to inquire, by implication to learn
column9: Middle voice prolonged from a primary putho (which occurs only as an alternate in certain tenses); to question, i.e. Ascertain by inquiry (as a matter of information merely; and thus differing from  (G2065) erotao, which properly means a request as a favor; and from  (G154) aiteo, which is strictly a demand for something due; as well as from  (G2212) zeteo, which implies a search for something hidden; and from  (G1189) deomai, which involves the idea of urgent need); by implication, to learn (by casual intelligence) -- ask, demand, enquire, understand. see GREEK  (G2065) erotao see GREEK  (G154) aiteo see GREEK  (G2212) zeteo see GREEK  (G1189) deomai
A primary word; "fire" (literally or figuratively, specially, lightning) -- fiery, fire.
From  (G4442) pur; a fire (concretely) -- fire. see GREEK  (G4442) pur
Apparently a primary word ("burgh"); a tower or castle -- tower.

column7: to be on fire, to be ill of a fever
column9: From  (G4443) pura; to be on fire, i.e. (specially), to have a fever -- be sick of a fever. see GREEK  (G4443) pura
From  (G4445) puresso; inflamed, i.e. (by implication) feverish (as noun, fever) -- fever. see GREEK  (G4445) puresso
From  (G4443) pura; fiery, i.e. (by implication) flaming -- of fire. see GREEK  (G4443) pura

column7: to set on fire, to burn (pass.)
column9: From  (G4442) pur; to kindle, i.e. (passively) to be ignited, glow (literally), be refined (by implication), or (figuratively) to be inflamed (with anger, grief, lust) -- burn, fiery, be on fire, try. see GREEK  (G4442) pur
From  (G4450) purrhos; to redden (intransitively) -- be red. see GREEK  (G4450) purrhos
From  (G4442) pur; fire-like, i.e. (specially), flame- colored -- red. see GREEK  (G4442) pur
From  (G4448) puroo; ignition, i.e. (specially), smelting (figuratively, conflagration, calamity as a test) -- burning, trial. see GREEK  (G4448) puroo

Another form of the base of  (G4458) pos; an enclitic particle of indefiniteness; yet, even; used only in the comparative. See  (G3369) medepo,  (G3380) mepo,  (G3764) oudepo,  (G3768) oupo,  (G4455) popote. see GREEK  (G4458) pos see GREEK  (G3369) medepo see GREEK  (G3380) mepo see GREEK  (G3764) oudepo see GREEK  (G3768) oupo see GREEK  (G4455) popote

column7: to exchange or barter, to sell
column9: Probably ultimately from pelomai (to be busy, to trade); to barter (as a pedlar), i.e. To sell -- sell, whatever is sold.
Apparently a primary word; a "foal" or "filly", i.e. (specially), a young ass -- colt.
From  (G4452) po and  (G4218) pote; at any time, i.e. (with negative particle) at no time -- at any time, + never (...to any man), + yet, never man. see GREEK  (G4452) po see GREEK  (G4218) pote
Apparently from poros (a kind of stone); to petrify, i.e. (figuratively) to indurate (render stupid or callous) -- blind, harden.

column7: a covering with a callous, blindness
column9: From  (G4456) poroo; stupidity or callousness -- blindness, hardness. see GREEK  (G4456) poroo

Adverb from the base of  (G4225) pou; an enclitic particle of indefiniteness of manner; somehow or anyhow; used only in composition -- haply, by any (some) means, perhaps. See  (G1513) ei pos,  (G3381) mepos. Compare  (G4459) pos. see GREEK  (G4225) pou see GREEK  (G4459) pos see GREEK  (G1513) ei pos see GREEK  (G3381) mepos

Adverb from the base of  (G4226) pou; an interrogative particle of manner; in what way? (sometimes the question is indirect, how?); also as exclamation, how much! -- how, after (by) what manner (means), that. (Occasionally unexpressed in English). see GREEK  (G4226) pou

column7: Rahab, a Canaanitess and an ancestor of Christ
column9: Of Hebrew origin ( (H7343) Rachab); Raab (i.e. Rachab), a Canaanitess -- Rahab. See also  (G4477) Rhachab. see HEBREW  (H7343) Rachab see GREEK  (G4477) Rhachab
Of Hebrew origin ( (H7227) rab with pronominal suffix); my master, i.e Rabbi, as an official title of honor -- Master, Rabbi. see HEBREW  (H7227) rab
Or rhabbouni (hrab-boo-nee') of Chaldee origin; corresponding to  (G4461) rhabbi -- Lord, Rabboni. see GREEK  (G4461) rhabbi
From  (G4464) rhabdos; to strike with a stick, i.e. Bastinado -- beat (with rods). see GREEK  (G4464) rhabdos
From the base of  (G4474) rhapizo; a stick or wand (as a cudgel, a cane or a baton of royalty) -- rod, sceptre, staff. see GREEK  (G4474) rhapizo

column7: a rod holder, (a Roman) lictor (one holding the rod of office)
column9: From  (G4464) rhabdos and  (G2192) echo; a rod- (the Latin fasces) holder, i.e. A Roman lictor (constable or executioner) -- serjeant. see GREEK  (G4464) rhabdos see GREEK  (G2192) echo
Of Hebrew origin ( (H7466) r'uw); Ragau (i.e. Reu), a patriarch -- Ragau. see HEBREW  (H7466) r'uw
From a comparative of rhaidios (easy, i.e. Reckless) and  (G2041) ergon; easy-going behavior, i.e. (by extension) a crime -- lewdness. see GREEK  (G2041) ergon

column7: ease in doing, laziness, recklessness, wickedness
column9: From the same as  (G4467) rhaidiourgema; recklessness, i.e. (by extension) malignity -- mischief. see GREEK  (G4467) rhaidiourgema
Of Chaldee origin (compare  (H7386) reyq); O empty one, i.e. Thou worthless (as a term of utter vilification) -- Raca. see HEBREW  (H7386) reyq
From  (G4486) rhegnumi; a "rag," i.e. Piece of cloth -- cloth. see GREEK  (G4486) rhegnumi

column7: Ramah, a city North of Jer
column9: Of Hebrew origin ( (H7414) Ramah); Rama (i.e. Ramah), a place in Palestine -- Rama. see HEBREW  (H7414) Ramah
From a derivative of rhaino (to sprinkle); to render besprinkled, i.e. Asperse (ceremonially or figuratively) -- sprinkle.
From  (G4472) rhantizo; aspersion (ceremonially or figuratively) -- sprinkling. see GREEK  (G4472) rhantizo

column7: to strike with a rod, to strike with the palm of the hand
column8: slap, smite with the palm of the hand.
column9: From a derivative of a primary rhepo (to let fall, "rap"); to slap -- smite (with the palm of the hand). Compare  (G5180) tupto. see GREEK  (G5180) tupto

column7: a blow (with a stick or the palm of the hand)
column8: a blow, slap in the face
column9: From  (G4474) rhapizo; a slap -- (+ strike with the) palm of the hand, smite with the hand. see GREEK  (G4474) rhapizo
From a primary rhapto (to sew; perhaps rather akin to the base of  (G4474) rhapizo through the idea of puncturing); a needle -- needle. see GREEK  (G4474) rhapizo
From the same as  (G4460) Rhaab; Rachab, a Canaanitess -- Rachab. see GREEK  (G4460) Rhaab
Of Hebrew origin ( (H7354) Rachel); Rachel, the wife of Jacob -- Rachel. see HEBREW  (H7354) Rachel
Of Hebrew origin ( (H7259) Ribqah); Rebecca (i.e. Ribkah), the wife of Isaac -- Rebecca. see HEBREW  (H7259) Ribqah
Of Latin origin; a rheda, i.e. Four-wheeled carriage (wagon for riding) -- chariot.
By incorrect transliteration for a word of Hebrew origin ( (H3594) Kiyuwn); Remphan (i.e. Kijun), an Egyptian idol -- Remphan. see HEBREW  (H3594) Kiyuwn
A primary verb; for some tenses of which a prolonged form rheuo (hryoo'-o) is used to flow ("run"; as water) -- flow.

For certain tenses of which a prolonged form ereo (er-eh'-o) is used; and both as alternate for  (G2036) epo; perhaps akin (or identical) with  (G4482) rheo (through the idea of pouring forth); to utter, i.e. Speak or say -- command, make, say, speak (of). Compare  (G3004) lego. see GREEK  (G2036) epo see GREEK  (G4482) rheo see GREEK  (G3004) lego

column7: Rhegium, a city in southern Italy
column9: Of Latin origin; Rhegium, a place in Italy -- Rhegium.
From  (G4486) rhegnumi; something torn, i.e. A fragment (by implication and abstractly, a fall) -- ruin. see GREEK  (G4486) rhegnumi

column7: to break apart,  to throw down
column9: Or rhesso (hrace'-so) both prolonged forms of rheko (which appears only in certain forms, and is itself probably a strengthened form of agnumi (see in  (G2608) katagnumi)) to "break," "wreck" or "crack", i.e. (especially) to sunder (by separation of the parts;  (G2608) katagnumi being its intensive (with the preposition in composition), and  (G2352) thrauo a shattering to minute fragments; but not a reduction to the constituent particles, like  (G3089) luo) or disrupt, lacerate; by implication, to convulse (with spasms); figuratively, to give vent to joyful emotions -- break (forth), burst, rend, tear. see GREEK  (G2608) katagnumi see GREEK  (G2608) katagnumi see GREEK  (G2352) thrauo see GREEK  (G3089) luo

column7: a word, by implication a matter
column9: From  (G4483) rheo; an utterance (individually, collectively or specially),; by implication, a matter or topic (especially of narration, command or dispute); with a negative naught whatever -- + evil, + nothing, saying, word. see GREEK  (G4483) rheo
Probably of Hebrew origin (apparently for  (H7509) Rphayah); Resa (i.e. Rephajah), an Israelite -- Rhesa. see HEBREW  (H7509) Rphayah
From  (G4483) rheo; a speaker, i.e. (by implication) a forensic advocate -- orator. see GREEK  (G4483) rheo
Adverb from a derivative of  (G4483) rheo; out-spokenly, i.e. Distinctly -- expressly. see GREEK  (G4483) rheo
Apparently a primary word; a "root" (literally or figuratively) -- root.
From  (G4491) rhiza; to root (figuratively, become stable) -- root. see GREEK  (G4491) rhiza

column7: any rapid movement, a twinkling (of lights or the eye)
column9: From  (G4496) rhipto; a jerk (of the eye, i.e. (by analogy) an instant) -- twinkling. see GREEK  (G4496) rhipto

column7: to fan, generally to make a breeze
column9: From a derivative of  (G4496) rhipto (meaning a fan or bellows); to breeze up, i.e. (by analogy) to agitate (into waves) -- toss. see GREEK  (G4496) rhipto
From a derivative of  (G4496) rhipto; to toss up -- cast off. see GREEK  (G4496) rhipto

column7: to throw, cast, to throw off, toss
column9: A primary verb (perhaps rather akin to the base of  (G4474) rhapizo, through the idea of sudden motion); to fling (properly, with a quick toss, thus differing from  (G906) ballo, which denotes a deliberate hurl; and from teino (see in  (G1614) ekteino), which indicates an extended projection); by qualification, to deposit (as if a load); by extension, to disperse -- cast (down, out), scatter abroad, throw. see GREEK  (G4474) rhapizo see GREEK  (G906) ballo see GREEK  (G1614) ekteino
Of Hebrew origin ( (H7346) Rchab'am); Roboam (i.e. Rechobam), an Israelite -- Roboam. see HEBREW  (H7346) Rchab'am
Probably for rhode (a rose); Rode, a servant girl -- Rhoda.

column7: Rhodes, an island in the Mediterranean
column9: Probably from rhodon (a rose); Rhodus, an island of the Mediterranean -- Rhodes.
Adverb from a derivative of rhoizos (a whir); whizzingly, i.e. With a crash -- with a great noise.

column7: Rompha, Rephan, the name of an Eg. god
column9: Probably of foreign origin; a sabre, i.e. A long and broad cutlass (any weapon of the kind, literally or figuratively) -- sword.

column7: Reuben, a son of Jacob, also a tribe of Isr
column9: Of Hebrew origin ( (H7205) r'uwben); Ruben (i.e. Reuben), an Israelite -- Reuben. see HEBREW  (H7205) r'uwben

column7: Ruth, a Moabitess and an ancestor of Christ
column9: Of Hebrew origin ( (H7327) Ruwth); Ruth, a Moabitess -- Ruth. see HEBREW  (H7327) Ruwth

column7: red, Rufus, a Christian at Rome
column9: Of Latin origin; red; Rufus, a Christian -- Rufus.

column7: the rush (of a moving body), a (crowded) street
column9: Prolongation from  (G4506) rhoumai in its original sense; an alley or avenue (as crowded) -- lane, street. see GREEK  (G4506) rhoumai

Middle voice of an obsolete verb, akin to  (G4482) rheo (through the idea of a current; compare  (G4511) rhusis); to rush or draw (for oneself), i.e. Rescue -- deliver(-er). see GREEK  (G4482) rheo see GREEK  (G4511) rhusis
From  (G4508) rhuparos; dirtiness (morally) -- turpitude. see GREEK  (G4508) rhuparos
From  (G4509) rhupos; dirty, i.e. (relatively) cheap or shabby; morally, wicked -- vile. see GREEK  (G4509) rhupos
Of uncertain affinity; dirt, i.e. (morally) depravity -- filth.
From  (G4509) rhupos; to soil, i.e. (intransitively) to become dirty (morally) -- be filthy. see GREEK  (G4509) rhupos
From  (G4506) rhoumai in the sense of its congener  (G4482) rheo; a flux (of blood) -- issue. see GREEK  (G4506) rhoumai see GREEK  (G4482) rheo
From  (G4506) rhoumai; a fold (as drawing together), i.e. A wrinkle (especially on the face) -- wrinkle. see GREEK  (G4506) rhoumai
From  (G4514) Rhomaios; Romaic, i.e. Latin -- Latin. see GREEK  (G4514) Rhomaios
From  (G4516) Rhome; Romaean, i.e. Roman (as noun) -- Roman, of Rome. see GREEK  (G4516) Rhome
Adverb from a presumed derivative of  (G4516) Rhome; Romaistically, i.e. In the Latin language -- Latin. see GREEK  (G4516) Rhome

column7: Rome, the capital of Italy and the Rom. Empire (named after Romulus, the legendary founder)
column9: From the base of  (G4517) rhonnumi; strength; Roma, the capital of Italy -- Rome. see GREEK  (G4517) rhonnumi

Prolongation from rhoomai (to dart; probably akin to  (G4506) rhoumai); to strengthen, i.e. (impersonal passive) have health (as a parting exclamation, good-bye) -- farewell. see GREEK  (G4506) rhoumai
Of Chaldee or ( (H7662) shbaq with pronominal suffix); thou hast left me; sabachthani (i.e. Shebakthani), a cry of distress -- sabachthani. see HEBREW  (H7662) shbaq
Of Hebrew origin ( (H6635) tsaba' in feminine plural); armies; sabaoth (i.e. Tsebaoth), a military epithet of God -- sabaoth. see HEBREW  (H6635) tsaba'
From a derivative of  (G4521) sabbaton; a "sabbatism", i.e. (figuratively) the repose of Christianity (as a type of heaven) -- rest. see GREEK  (G4521) sabbaton

column7: the Sabbath, the seventh day (of the week)
column9: Of Hebrew origin ( (H7676) shabbath); the Sabbath (i.e. Shabbath), or day of weekly repose from secular avocations (also the observance or institution itself); by extension, a se'nnight, i.e. The interval between two Sabbaths; likewise the plural in all the above applications -- sabbath (day), week. see HEBREW  (H7676) shabbath
From a derivative of satto (to equip) meaning furniture, especially a pack-saddle (which in the East is merely a bag of netted rope); a "seine" for fishing -- net.

column7: a Sadducee, a member of a Jewish religious sect
column9: Probably from  (G4524) Sadok; a Sadducaean (i.e. Tsadokian), or follower of a certain heretical Israelite -- Sadducee. see GREEK  (G4524) Sadok
Of Hebrew origin ( (H6659) Tsadowq); Sadoc (i.e. Tsadok), an Israelite -- Sadoc. see HEBREW  (H6659) Tsadowq

column7: to wag the tail, to greet, flatter, disturb
column9: Akin to  (G4579) seio; to wag (as a dog its tail fawningly), i.e. (generally) to shake (figuratively, disturb) -- move. see GREEK  (G4579) seio
Of Hebrew origin ( (H8242) saq); "sack"-cloth, i.e. Mohair (the material or garments made of it, worn as a sign of grief) -- sackcloth. see HEBREW  (H8242) saq

column7: Shelah, an ancestor of Christ, also Salmon, an ancestor of Christ
column9: Of Hebrew origin ( (H7974) Shelach); Sala (i.e. Shelach), a patriarch -- Sala. see HEBREW  (H7974) Shelach
Of Hebrew origin ( (H7597) Sh'altiy'el); Salathiel (i.e. Shealtiel), an Israelite -- Salathiel. see HEBREW  (H7597) Sh'altiy'el

column7: Salamis, the chief city of Cyprus
column9: Probably from  (G4535) salos (from the surge on the shore); Salamis, a place in Cyprus -- Salamis. see GREEK  (G4535) salos
Probably from the same as  (G4531) saleuo; Salim, a place in Palestine -- Salim. see GREEK  (G4531) saleuo

column7: to agitate, shake,  to cast down
column9: From  (G4535) salos; to waver, i.e. Agitate, rock, topple or (by implication) destroy; figuratively, to disturb, incite -- move, shake (together), which can(-not) be shaken, stir up. see GREEK  (G4535) salos
Of Hebrew origin ( (H8004) Shalem); Salem (i.e. Shalem), a place in Palestine -- Salem. see HEBREW  (H8004) Shalem
Of Hebrew origin ( (H8012) Salmown); Salmon, an Israelite -- Salmon. see HEBREW  (H8012) Salmown
Perhaps of similar origin to  (G4529) Salamis; Salmone, a place in Crete -- Salmone. see GREEK  (G4529) Salamis

column7: a tossing, the swell (of the sea)
column9: Probably from the base of  (G4525) saino; a vibration, i.e. (specially), billow -- wave. see GREEK  (G4525) saino
Perhaps from  (G4535) salos (through the idea of quavering or reverberation); a trumpet -- trump(-et). see GREEK  (G4535) salos
From  (G4536) salpigx; to trumpet, i.e. Sound a blast (literally or figuratively) -- (which are yet to) sound (a trumpet). see GREEK  (G4536) salpigx
From  (G4537) salpizo; a trumpeter -- trumpeter. see GREEK  (G4537) salpizo

column7: Salome, the mother of the apostles James and John
column9: Probably of Hebrew origin; Salome (i.e. Shelomah), an Israelitess -- Salome. see HEBREW  (H7965) shalowm

column7: Samaria, the name of both a city and a region in Palestine
column9: Of Hebrew origin ( (H8111) Shomrown); Samaria (i.e. Shomeron), a city and region of Palestine -- Samaria. see HEBREW  (H8111) Shomrown

column7: a Samaritan, an inhabitant of the region of Samaria
column9: From  (G4540) Samareia; a Samarite, i.e. Inhabitant of Samaria -- Samaritan. see GREEK  (G4540) Samareia

column7: (the region of) Samaria, a Samaritan woman
column9: Feminine of  (G4541) Samareites; a Samaritess, i.e. Woman of Samaria -- of Samaria. see GREEK  (G4541) Samareites

column7: Samos of Thrace, Samothrace, an island in the Aegean
column9: From  (G4544) Samos and Thraike (Thrace); Samo-thrace (Samos of Thrace), an island in the Mediterranean -- Samothracia. see GREEK  (G4544) Samos

column7: Samos, an island in the Aegean
column9: Of uncertain affinity; Samus, an island of the Mediterranean -- Samos.

column7: Samuel, a prophet and judge in Isr
column9: Of Hebrew origin ( (H8050) Shmuw'el); Samuel (i.e. Shemuel), an Israelite -- Samuel. see HEBREW  (H8050) Shmuw'el
Of Hebrew origin ( (H8123) Shimshown); Sampson (i.e. Shimshon), an Israelite -- Samson. see HEBREW  (H8123) Shimshown
Neuter of a derivative of sandalon (a "sandal"; of uncertain origin); a slipper or sole-pad -- sandal.
Of uncertain affinity; a plank -- board.

column7: Saul, the first Israelite king, also the Jewish name of Paul
column9: Of Hebrew origin ( (H7586) Sha'uwl); Saul (i.e. Shaul), the Jewish name of Paul -- Saul. Compare  (G4569) Saulos. see GREEK  (G4569) Saulos see HEBREW  (H7586) Sha'uwl
From  (G4595) sepo; rotten, i.e. Worthless (literally or morally) -- bad, corrupt. Compare  (G4190) poneros. see GREEK  (G4595) sepo see GREEK  (G4190) poneros
Feminine of  (G4552) sappheiros; Sapphire, an Israelitess -- Sapphira. see GREEK  (G4552) sappheiros
Of Hebrew origin ( (H5601) cappiyr); a "sapphire" or lapis-lazuli gem -- sapphire. see HEBREW  (H5601) cappiyr

column7: a plaited rope, a hamper, basket
column9: Apparently of Hebrew origin ( (H8276) sarag); a basket (as interwoven or wicker-work -- basket. see HEBREW  (H8276) sarag

column7: Sardis, the chief city of Lydia
column9: Plural of uncertain derivation; Sardis, a place in Asia Minor -- Sardis.
From the same as  (G4556) sardios; sardine ( (G3037) lithos being implied), i.e. A gem, so called -- sardine. see GREEK  (G4556) sardios see GREEK  (G3037) lithos
Properly, an adjective from an uncertain base; sardian ( (G3037) lithos being implied), i.e. (as noun) the gem so called -- sardius.
From the base of  (G4556) sardios and onux (the nail of a finger; hence the "onyx" stone); a "sardonyx", i.e. The gem so called -- sardonyx. see GREEK  (G4556) sardios
Of Hebrew origin ( (H6886) Tsarphath); Sarepta (i.e. Tsarephath), a place in Palestine -- Sarepta. see HEBREW  (H6886) Tsarphath
From  (G4561) sarx; pertaining to flesh, i.e. (by extension) bodily, temporal, or (by implication) animal, unregenerate -- carnal, fleshly. see GREEK  (G4561) sarx
From  (G4561) sarx; similar to flesh, i.e. (by analogy) soft -- fleshly. see GREEK  (G4561) sarx

Probably from the base of  (G4563) saroo; flesh (as stripped of the skin), i.e. (strictly) the meat of an animal (as food), or (by extension) the body (as opposed to the soul (or spirit), or as the symbol of what is external, or as the means of kindred), or (by implication) human nature (with its frailties (physically or morally) and passions), or (specially), a human being (as such) -- carnal(-ly, + -ly minded), flesh(-ly). see GREEK  (G4563) saroo
Of Hebrew origin ( (H8286) Sruwg); Saruch (i.e. Serug), a patriarch -- Saruch. see HEBREW  (H8286) Sruwg
From a derivative of sairo (to brush off; akin to  (G4951) suro); meaning a broom; to sweep -- sweep. see GREEK  (G4951) suro
Of Hebrew origin ( (H8283) Sarah); Sarra (i.e. Sarah), the wife of Abraham -- Sara, Sarah. see HEBREW  (H8283) Sarah
Of Hebrew origin ( (H8289) Sharown); Saron (i.e. Sharon), a district of Palestine -- Saron. see HEBREW  (H8289) Sharown
Of Hebrew origin ( (H7854) satan); Satan, i.e. The devil -- Satan. Compare  (G4567) Satanas. see GREEK  (G4567) Satanas see HEBREW  (H7854) satan
Of Chaldee origin corresponding to  (H4566) ma'bad (with the definite affix); the accuser, i.e. The devil -- Satan. see HEBREW  (H4566) ma'bad

column7: seah, a (Hebrew) measure (equiv. to about one and a half pecks)
column9: Of Hebrew origin ( (H5429) c'ah); a certain measure for things dry -- measure. see HEBREW  (H5429) c'ah

column7: Saul, the Jewish name of the apostle Paul
column9: Of Hebrew origin, the same as  (G4549) Saoul; Saulus (i.e. Shaul), the Jewish name of Paul -- Saul. see GREEK  (G4549) Saoul
A prolonged form of an apparently primary verb; to extinguish (literally or figuratively) -- go out, quench.
Accusative case singular of  (G4771) su; thee -- thee, thou, X thy house. see GREEK  (G4771) su

Genitive case from  (G4571) se and  (G846) autos, also dative case of the same, seautoi seh-ow-to', and accusative case seauton seh-ow-ton', likewise contracted sautou (sow-too'), sautoi (sow-to'), and sauton (sow-ton'), respectively of (with, to) thyself -- thee, thine own self, (thou) thy(-self). see GREEK  (G4571) se see GREEK  (G846) autos

column7: to fear, to have reverential awe
column9: Middle voice from a derivative of  (G4576) sebomai; to venerate, i.e. Adore -- worship. see GREEK  (G4576) sebomai
From  (G4573) sebazomai; something adored, i.e. An object of worship (god, altar, etc) -- devotion, that is worshipped. see GREEK  (G4573) sebazomai

column7: reverend, august, Augustus, a Roman emperor
column9: From  (G4573) sebazomai; venerable (august), i.e. (as noun) a title of the Roman Emperor, or (as adjective) imperial -- Augustus(-'). see GREEK  (G4573) sebazomai
Middle voice of an apparently primary verb; to revere, i.e. Adore -- devout, religious, worship.
Probably from  (G4951) suro through its congener eiro (to fasten; akin to  (G138) haireomai); a chain (as binding or drawing) -- chain. see GREEK  (G4951) suro see GREEK  (G138) haireomai
From  (G4579) seio; a commotion, i.e. (of the air) a gale, (of the ground) an earthquake -- earthquake, tempest. see GREEK  (G4579) seio

Apparently a primary verb; to rock (vibrate, properly, sideways or to and fro), i.e. (generally) to agitate (in any direction; cause to tremble); figuratively, to throw into a tremor (of fear or concern) -- move, quake, shake.

column7: second, Secundus, a Christian of Thessalonica
column9: Of Latin origin; "second"; Secundus, a Christian -- Secundus.
From Seleukos (Seleucus, a Syrian king); Seleuceia, a place in Syria -- Seleucia.
From selas (brilliancy; probably akin to the alternate of  (G138) haireomai, through the idea of attractiveness); the moon -- moon. see GREEK  (G138) haireomai

column7: to be moonstruck, be epileptic (supposedly influenced by the moon)
column9: Middle voice or passive from a presumed derivative of  (G4582) selene; to be moon-struck, i.e. Crazy -- be a lunatic. see GREEK  (G4582) selene
Of Hebrew origin ( (H8096) Shim'iy); Semei (i.e. Shimi), an Israelite -- Semei. see HEBREW  (H8096) Shim'iy
Probably of foreign origin; fine wheaten flour -- fine flour.
From  (G4576) sebomai; venerable, i.e. Honorable -- grave, honest. see GREEK  (G4576) sebomai
From  (G4586) semnos; venerableness, i.e. Probity -- gravity, honesty. see GREEK  (G4586) semnos

column7: Sergius, a Roman proconsul of Cyprus
column9: Of Latin origin; Sergius, a Roman -- Sergius.
Of Hebrew origin ( (H8352) Sheth); Seth (i.e. Sheth), a patriarch -- Seth. see HEBREW  (H8352) Sheth
Of Hebrew origin ( (H8035) Shem); Sem (i.e. Shem), a patriarch -- Sem. see HEBREW  (H8035) Shem
From sema (a mark; of uncertain derivation); to indicate -- signify.
Neuter of a presumed derivative of the base of  (G4591) semaino; an indication, especially ceremonially or supernaturally -- miracle, sign, token, wonder. see GREEK  (G4591) semaino
From  (G4592) semeion; to distinguish, i.e. Mark (for avoidance) -- note. see GREEK  (G4592) semeion

Neuter (as adverb) of a presumed compound of the article  (G3588) ho (t changed to s) and  (G2250) hemera; on the (i.e. This) day (or night current or just passed); generally, now (i.e. At present, hitherto) -- this (to-)day. see GREEK  (G3588) ho see GREEK  (G2250) hemera

column7: to make corrupt, pass. become corrupt
column9: Apparently a primary verb; to putrefy, i.e. (figuratively) perish -- be corrupted.
From Ser (an Indian tribe from whom silk was procured; hence the name of the silk-worm); Seric, i.e. Silken (neuter as noun, a silky fabric) -- silk.
Apparently of Hebrew origin ( (H5580) cac); a moth -- moth. see HEBREW  (H5580) cac
From  (G4597) ses and a derivative of  (G977) bibrosko; moth-eaten -- motheaten. see GREEK  (G4597) ses see GREEK  (G977) bibrosko
From sthenos (bodily vigor; probably akin to the base of  (G2476) histemi); to strengthen, i.e. (figuratively) confirm (in spiritual knowledge and power) -- strengthen. see GREEK  (G2476) histemi
Of uncertain derivation; the jaw-bone, i.e. (by implication) the cheek or side of the face -- cheek.

column7: to keep silent, to keep secret
column9: From  (G4602) sige; to keep silent (transitively or intransitively) -- keep close (secret, silence), hold peace. see GREEK  (G4602) sige
Apparently from sizo (to hiss, i.e. Hist or hush); silence -- silence. Compare  (G4623) siopao. see GREEK  (G4623) siopao
From  (G4604) sideros; made of iron -- (of) iron. see GREEK  (G4604) sideros
Of uncertain derivation; iron -- iron.

column7: Sidon, a maritime city of Phoenicia
column9: Of Hebrew origin ( (H6721) Tsiydown); Sidon (i.e. Tsidon), a place in Palestine -- Sidon. see HEBREW  (H6721) Tsiydown
From  (G4605) Sidon; a Sidonian, i.e. Inhabitant of Sidon -- of Sidon. see GREEK  (G4605) Sidon
Of Latin origin; a dagger-man or assassin; a freebooter (Jewish fanatic outlawed by the Romans) -- murderer. Compare  (G5406) phoneus. see GREEK  (G5406) phoneus
Of Hebrew origin ( (H7941) shekar); an intoxicant, i.e. Intensely fermented liquor -- strong drink. see HEBREW  (H7941) shekar

column7: Silas, a fellow missionary of Paul
column9: Contraction for  (G4610) Silouanos; Silas, a Christian -- Silas. see GREEK  (G4610) Silouanos

column7: sylvan, Silvanus, alt. form of the name Silas
column9: Of Latin origin; "silvan"; Silvanus, a Christian -- Silvanus. Compare  (G4609) Silas. see GREEK  (G4609) Silas
Of Hebrew origin ( (H7975) Shiloach); Siloam (i.e. Shiloach), a pool of Jerusalem -- Siloam. see HEBREW  (H7975) Shiloach
Of Latin origin; a semicinctium or half-girding, i.e. Narrow covering (apron) -- apron.

column7: Simon, the name of several Israelites
column9: Of Hebrew origin ( (H8095) Shim'own); Simon (i.e. Shimon), the name of nine Israelites -- Simon. Compare  (G4826) Sumeon. see GREEK  (G4826) Sumeon see HEBREW  (H8095) Shim'own

column7: Sinai, a mountain probably on the Sinai Peninsula
column9: Of Hebrew origin ( (H5514) Ciynay); Sina (i.e. Sinai), a mountain in Arabia -- Sina. see HEBREW  (H5514) Ciynay
Perhaps from sinomai (to hurt, i.e. Sting); mustard (the plant) -- mustard.
Of uncertain (perhaps foreign) origin; byssos, i.e. Bleached linen (the cloth or a garment of it) -- (fine) linen (cloth).
From sinion (a sieve); to riddle (figuratively) -- sift.
From a derivative of  (G4621) sitos; grain-fed, i.e. Fattened -- fatted. see GREEK  (G4621) sitos
From a derivative of  (G4621) sitos; grained, i.e. Fatted -- fatling. see GREEK  (G4621) sitos
From  (G4621) sitos and  (G3358) metron; a grain-measure, i.e. (by implication) ration (allowance of food) -- portion of meat. see GREEK  (G4621) sitos see GREEK  (G3358) metron
Also plural irregular neuter sita (see'-tah) of uncertain derivation; grain, especially wheat -- corn, wheat.

column7: Zion, a mountain of Jerusalem or the city of Jer
column9: Of Hebrew origin ( (H6726) Tsiyown); Sion (i.e. Tsijon), a hill of Jerusalem; figuratively, the Church (militant or triumphant) -- Sion. see HEBREW  (H6726) Tsiyown

From siope (silence, i.e. A hush; properly, muteness, i.e. Involuntary stillness, or inability to speak; and thus differing from  (G4602) sige, which is rather a voluntary refusal or indisposition to speak, although the terms are often used synonymously); to be dumb (but not deaf also, like  (G2974) kophos properly); figuratively, to be calm (as quiet water) -- dumb, (hold) peace. see GREEK  (G4602) sige

column7: to put a snare (in the way), to cause to stumble, to give offense
column9: From  (G4625) skandalon; to entrap, i.e. Trip up (figuratively, stumble (transitively) or entice to sin, apostasy or displeasure) -- (make to) offend. see GREEK  (G4625) skandalon

column7: a stick for bait (of a trap), generally a snare, a stumbling block, an offense
column9: Scandal; probably from a derivative of  (G2578) kampto; a trap-stick (bent sapling), i.e. Snare (figuratively, cause of displeasure or sin) -- occasion to fall (of stumbling), offence, thing that offends, stumblingblock. see GREEK  (G2578) kampto
Apparently a primary verb; to dig -- dig.

column7: anything scooped out, a light boat
column9: A "skiff" (as if dug out), or yawl (carried aboard a large vessel for landing) -- boat.
Apparently from skello (to parch; through the idea of leanness); the leg (as lank) -- leg.
From a derivative of skepas (a covering; perhaps akin to the base of  (G4649) skopos through the idea of noticeableness); clothing -- raiment. see GREEK  (G4649) skopos
Apparently of Latin origin; left-handed; Scevas (i.e. Scoevus), an Israelite -- Sceva.
From  (G4632) skeuos; furniture, i.e. Spare tackle -- tackling. see GREEK  (G4632) skeuos
Of uncertain affinity; a vessel, implement, equipment or apparatus (literally or figuratively (specially, a wife as contributing to the usefulness of the husband)) -- goods, sail, stuff, vessel.
Apparently akin to  (G4632) skeuos and  (G4639) skia; a tent or cloth hut (literally or figuratively) -- habitation, tabernacle. see GREEK  (G4639) skia see GREEK  (G4632) skeuos

From  (G4636) skenos and  (G4078) pegnumi; the Festival of Tabernacles (so called from the custom of erecting booths for temporary homes) -- tabernacles. see GREEK  (G4636) skenos see GREEK  (G4078) pegnumi
From  (G4633) skene and  (G4160) poieo; a manufacturer of tents -- tent-maker. see GREEK  (G4633) skene see GREEK  (G4160) poieo
From  (G4633) skene; a hut or temporary residence, i.e. (figuratively) the human body (as the abode of the spirit) -- tabernacle. see GREEK  (G4633) skene

From  (G4636) skenos; to tent or encamp, i.e. (figuratively) to occupy (as a mansion) or (specially), to reside (as God did in the Tabernacle of old, a symbol of protection and communion) -- dwell. see GREEK  (G4636) skenos
From  (G4637) skenoo; an encampment, i.e. (figuratively) the Temple (as God's residence), the body (as a tenement for the soul) -- tabernacle. see GREEK  (G4637) skenoo
Apparently a primary word; "shade" or a shadow (literally or figuratively (darkness of error or an adumbration)) -- shadow.
Akin to skairo (to skip); to jump, i.e. Sympathetically move (as the quickening of a fetus) -- leap (for joy).

Feminine of a compound of  (G4642) skleros and  (G2588) kardia; hard-heartedness, i.e. (specially), destitution of (spiritual) perception -- hardness of heart. see GREEK  (G4642) skleros see GREEK  (G2588) kardia
From the base of  (G4628) skelos; dry, i.e. Hard or tough (figuratively, harsh, severe) -- fierce, hard. see GREEK  (G4628) skelos
From  (G4642) skleros; callousness, i.e. (figuratively) stubbornness -- hardness. see GREEK  (G4642) skleros
From  (G4642) skleros and  (G5137) trachelos; hardnaped, i.e. (figuratively) obstinate -- stiffnecked. see GREEK  (G4642) skleros see GREEK  (G5137) trachelos
From  (G4642) skleros; to indurate, i.e. (figuratively) render stubborn -- harden. see GREEK  (G4642) skleros
From the base of  (G4628) skelos; warped, i.e. Winding; figuratively, perverse -- crooked, froward, untoward. see GREEK  (G4628) skelos

Perhaps from the base of  (G4628) skelos and  (G3700) optanomai; withered at the front, i.e. A point or prickle (figuratively, a bodily annoyance or disability) -- thorn. see GREEK  (G4628) skelos see GREEK  (G3700) optanomai
From  (G4649) skopos; to take aim at (spy), i.e. (figuratively) regard -- consider, take heed, look at (on), mark. Compare  (G3700) optanomai. see GREEK  (G4649) skopos see GREEK  (G3700) optanomai

column7: a watchman, a mark (on which to fix the eye)
column9: From skeptomai (to peer about ("skeptic"); perhaps akin to  (G4626) skapto through the idea of concealment; compare  (G4629) skepasma); a watch (sentry or scout), i.e. (by implication) a goal -- mark. see GREEK  (G4626) skapto see GREEK  (G4629) skepasma

Apparently from the same as  (G4651) skorpios (through the idea of penetrating); to dissipate, i.e. (figuratively) put to flight, waste, be liberal -- disperse abroad, scatter (abroad). see GREEK  (G4651) skorpios
Probably from an obsolete skerpo (perhaps strengthened from the base of  (G4649) skopos and meaning to pierce); a "scorpion" (from its sting) -- scorpion. see GREEK  (G4649) skopos
From  (G4655) skotos; opaque, i.e. (figuratively) benighted -- dark, full of darkness. see GREEK  (G4655) skotos
From  (G4655) skotos; dimness, obscurity (literally or figuratively) -- dark(-ness). see GREEK  (G4655) skotos
From  (G4655) skotos; to obscure (literally or figuratively) -- darken. see GREEK  (G4655) skotos
From the base of  (G4639) skia; shadiness, i.e. Obscurity (literally or figuratively) -- darkness. see GREEK  (G4639) skia
From  (G4655) skotos; to obscure or blind (literally or figuratively) -- be full of darkness. see GREEK  (G4655) skotos

Neuter of a presumed derivative of  (G1519) eis and  (G2965) kuon and  (G906) ballo; what is thrown to the dogs, i.e. Refuse (ordure) -- dung. see GREEK  (G1519) eis see GREEK  (G2965) kuon see GREEK  (G906) ballo

column7: a Scythian, an inhabitant of Scythia (considered the wildest of barbarians)
column9: Probably of foreign origin; a Scythene or Scythian, i.e. (by implication) a savage -- Scythian.
From skuthros (sullen) and a derivative of  (G3700) optanomai; angry-visaged, i.e. Gloomy or affecting a mournful appearance -- of a sad countenance. see GREEK  (G3700) optanomai
Apparently a primary verb; to flay, i.e. (figuratively) to harass -- trouble(self).

column7: arms stripped from a foe, spoils
column9: Neuter from  (G4660) skullo; something stripped (as a hide), i.e. Booty -- spoil. see GREEK  (G4660) skullo
From  (G4663) skolex and a derivative of  (G977) bibrosko; worm-eaten, i.e. Diseased with maggots -- eaten of worms. see GREEK  (G4663) skolex see GREEK  (G977) bibrosko
Of uncertain derivation; a grub, maggot or earth-worm -- worm.
From  (G4665) smaragdos; consisting of emerald -- emerald. see GREEK  (G4665) smaragdos
Of uncertain derivation; the emerald or green gem so called -- emerald.

column7: myrrh (used as an ointment and for embalming)
column9: Apparently strengthened for  (G3464) muron; myrrh -- myrrh. see GREEK  (G3464) muron

column7: myrrh, Smyrna, an Ionian city in Asia Minor
column9: The same as  (G4666) smurna; Smyrna, a place in Asia Minor -- Smyrna. see GREEK  (G4666) smurna
From  (G4667) Smurna; a Smyrnoean -- in Smyrna. see GREEK  (G4667) Smurna

column7: to be like myrrh, to mingle with myrrh
column9: From  (G4667) Smurna; to tincture with myrrh, i.e. Embitter (as a narcotic) -- mingle with myrrh. see GREEK  (G4667) Smurna

column7: Sodom, an unidentified city in the Jordan Valley
column9: Plural of Hebrew origin ( (H5467) Cdom); Sodoma (i.e. Sedom), a place in Palestine -- Sodom. see HEBREW  (H5467) Cdom
Dative case of  (G4771) su; to thee -- thee, thine own, thou, thy. see GREEK  (G4771) su

column7: Solomon, a son of David and king of Isr
column9: Of Hebrew origin ( (H8010) Shlomoh); Solomon (i.e. Shelomoh), the son of David -- Solomon. see HEBREW  (H8010) Shlomoh

column7: a cinerary urn, by anal. a coffin
column9: Probably akin to the base of  (G4987) soreuo; a funereal receptacle (urn, coffin), i.e. (by analogy) a bier -- bier. see GREEK  (G4987) soreuo
From  (G4771) su; thine -- thine (own), thy (friend). see GREEK  (G4771) su
Genitive case of  (G4771) su; of thee, thy -- X home, thee, thine (own), thou, thy. see GREEK  (G4771) su

column7: a handkerchief, a head cloth (for the dead)
column9: Of Latin origin; a sudarium (sweat-cloth), i.e. Towel (for wiping the perspiration from the face, or binding the face of a corpse) -- handkerchief, napkin.

column7: lily, Susanna, one of the women accompanying Jesus on His journeys
column9: Of Hebrew origin ( (H7799) shuwshan feminine); lily; Susannah (i.e. Shoshannah), an Israelitess -- Susanna. see HEBREW  (H7799) shuwshan
From  (G4680) sophos; wisdom (higher or lower, worldly or spiritual) -- wisdom. see GREEK  (G4680) sophos
From  (G4680) sophos; to render wise; in a sinister acceptation, to form "sophisms", i.e. Continue plausible error -- cunningly devised, make wise. see GREEK  (G4680) sophos
Akin to saphes (clear); wise (in a most general application) -- wise. Compare  (G5429) phronimos. see GREEK  (G5429) phronimos

column7: Spain, a peninsula of S.W. Europe
column9: Probably of foreign origin; Spania, a region of Europe -- Spain.

column8: to convulse, shake to and fro
column9: Prolongation from spairo (to grasp; apparently strengthened from  (G4685) spao through the idea of spasmodic contraction); to mangle, i.e. Convluse with epilepsy -- rend, tear. see GREEK  (G4685) spao

From sparganon (a strip; from a derivative of the base of  (G4682) sparasso meaning to strap or wrap with strips); to swathe (an infant after the Oriental custom) -- wrap in swaddling clothes. see GREEK  (G4682) sparasso
From spatale (luxury); to be voluptuous -- live in pleasure, be wanton.
A primary verb; to draw -- draw (out).

column7: anything wound up or coiled,  a body (of soldiers), a cohort
column9: Of immediate Latin origin, but ultimately a derivative of  (G138) haireomai in the sense of its cognate  (G1507) heilisso; a coil (spira, "spire"), i.e. (figuratively) a mass of men (a Roman military cohort; also (by analogy) a squad of Levitical janitors) -- band. see GREEK  (G1507) heilisso see GREEK  (G138) haireomai
Probably strengthened from  (G4685) spao (through the idea of extending); to scatter, i.e. Sow (literally or figuratively) -- sow(- er), receive seed. see GREEK  (G4685) spao
Of Latin origin; a speculator, i.e. Military scout (spy or (by extension) life-guardsman) -- executioner.

column7: to pour out (as a drink offering), to make a libation
column8: to pour out as a drink offering
column9: Apparently a primary verb; to pour out as a libation, i.e. (figuratively) to devote (one's life or blood, as a sacrifice) ("spend") -- (be ready to) be offered.

From  (G4687) speiro; something sown, i.e. Seed (including the male "sperm"); by implication, offspring; specially, a remnant (figuratively, as if kept over for planting) -- issue, seed. see GREEK  (G4687) speiro

column7: a seed picker, one who picks up scraps of knowledge
column9: From  (G4690) sperma and  (G3004) lego; a seed-picker (as the crow), i.e. (figuratively) a sponger, loafer (specially, a gossip or trifler in talk) -- babbler. see GREEK  (G4690) sperma see GREEK  (G3004) lego
Probably strengthened from  (G4228) pous; to "speed" ("study"), i.e. Urge on (diligently or earnestly); by implication, to await eagerly -- (make, with) haste unto. see GREEK  (G4228) pous
Neuter of a presumed derivative of speos (a grotto); a cavern; by implication, a hiding-place or resort -- cave, den.

column7: a ledge of rock (over which the sea dashes), a reef
column9: Of uncertain derivation; a ledge or reef of rock in the sea -- spot (by confusion with  (G4696) spilos). see GREEK  (G4696) spilos
From  (G4696) spilos; to stain or soil (literally or figuratively) -- defile, spot. see GREEK  (G4696) spilos
Of uncertain derivation; a stain or blemish, i.e. (figuratively) defect, disgrace -- spot.

column7: to be moved in the inward parts, to feel compassion
column9: Middle voice from  (G4698) splagchnon; to have the bowels yearn, i.e. (figuratively) feel sympathy, to pity -- have (be moved with) compassion. see GREEK  (G4698) splagchnon

column7: the inward parts (heart, liver, lungs, etc.), the emotions
column9: Probably strengthened from splen (the "spleen"); an intestine (plural); figuratively, pity or sympathy -- bowels, inward affection, + tender mercy.
Perhaps of foreign origin; a "sponge" -- spunge.
Of uncertain derivation; ashes -- ashes.
From  (G4687) speiro; a sowing, i.e. (by implication) parentage -- seed. see GREEK  (G4687) speiro
From  (G4703) sporos; sown, i.e. (neuter plural) a planted field -- corn(-field). see GREEK  (G4703) sporos
From  (G4687) speiro; a scattering (of seed), i.e. (concretely) seed (as sown) -- seed (X sown). see GREEK  (G4687) speiro

column7: to make haste, to give diligence
column9: From  (G4710) spoude; to use speed, i.e. To make effort, be prompt or earnest -- do (give) diligence, be diligent (forward), endeavour, labour, study. see GREEK  (G4710) spoude
From  (G4710) spoude; prompt, energetic, earnest -- diligent. see GREEK  (G4710) spoude
Neuter of  (G4707) spoudaioteros as adverb; more earnestly than others), i.e. Very promptly -- very diligently. see GREEK  (G4707) spoudaioteros
Comparative of  (G4705) spoudaios; more prompt, more earnest -- more diligent (forward). see GREEK  (G4705) spoudaios
Adverb from  (G4707) spoudaioteros; more speedily, i.e. Sooner than otherwise -- more carefully. see GREEK  (G4707) spoudaioteros
Adverb from  (G4705) spoudaios; earnestly, promptly -- diligently, instantly. see GREEK  (G4705) spoudaios
From  (G4692) speudo; "speed", i.e. (by implication) despatch, eagerness, earnestness -- business, (earnest) care(-fulness), diligence, forwardness, haste. see GREEK  (G4692) speudo
From  (G4687) speiro (as woven); a hamper or lunch-receptacle -- basket. see GREEK  (G4687) speiro

column7: a stadium (a Greek  measure of length), by implication a racecourse
column9: Or masculine (in plural) stadios (stad'-ee-os) from the base of  (G2476) histemi (as fixed); a stade or certain measure of distance; by implication, a stadium or race-course -- furlong, race. see GREEK  (G2476) histemi

column7: an earthen jar (for racking off wine)
column9: From the base of  (G2476) histemi (as stationary); a jar or earthen tank -- pot. see GREEK  (G2476) histemi

From the base of  (G2476) histemi; a standing (properly, the act), i.e. (by analogy) position (existence); by implication, a popular uprising; figuratively, controversy -- dissension, insurrection, X standing, uproar. see GREEK  (G2476) histemi
From the base of  (G2746) kauchesis; a stander (standard of value), i.e. (specially), a stater or certain coin -- piece of money. see GREEK  (G2746) kauchesis

column7: an upright stake, a cross (the Rom. instrument of crucifixion)
column9: From the base of  (G2476) histemi; a stake or post (as set upright), i.e. (specially), a pole or cross (as an instrument of capital punishment); figuratively, exposure to death, i.e. Self-denial; by implication, the atonement of Christ -- cross. see GREEK  (G2476) histemi

column7: to fence with stakes, to crucify
column9: From  (G4716) stauros; to impale on the cross; figuratively, to extinguish (subdue) passion or selfishness -- crucify. see GREEK  (G4716) stauros
Probably from the base of  (G4735) stephanos; a cluster of grapes (as if intertwined) -- grapes. see GREEK  (G4735) stephanos
From the base of  (G2476) histemi; a head of grain (as standing out from the stalk) -- ear (of corn). see GREEK  (G2476) histemi
The same as  (G4719) stachus; Stachys, a Christian -- Stachys. see GREEK  (G4719) stachus
Strengthened from a primary tegos (a "thatch" or "deck" of a building); a roof -- roof.

column7: to cover closely (so as to keep water out), generally to bear up under
column9: From  (G4721) stege; to roof over, i.e. (figuratively) to cover with silence (endure patiently) -- (for-)bear, suffer. see GREEK  (G4721) stege
A contraction from  (G4731) stereos (as stiff and unnatural); "sterile" -- barren. see GREEK  (G4731) stereos

column7: to arrange, prepare, gather up, to restrain
column9: Probably strengthened from the base of  (G2476) histemi; properly, to set fast ("stall"), i.e. (figuratively) to repress (reflexively, abstain from associating with) -- avoid, withdraw self. see GREEK  (G2476) histemi
From the base of  (G4735) stephanos; a wreath for show -- garland. see GREEK  (G4735) stephanos
From  (G4727) stenazo; a sigh -- groaning. see GREEK  (G4727) stenazo
From  (G4728) stenos; to make (intransitively, be) in straits, i.e. (by implication) to sigh, murmur, pray inaudibly -- with grief, groan, grudge, sigh. see GREEK  (G4728) stenos
Probably from the base of  (G2476) histemi; narrow (from obstacles standing close about) -- strait. see GREEK  (G2476) histemi

column7: to be made narrow, to compress
column9: From the same as  (G4730) stenochoria; to hem in closely, i.e. (figuratively) cramp -- distress, straiten. see GREEK  (G4730) stenochoria
From a compound of  (G4728) stenos and  (G5561) chora; narrowness of room, i.e. (figuratively) calamity -- anguish, distress. see GREEK  (G4728) stenos see GREEK  (G5561) chora
From  (G2476) histemi; stiff, i.e. Solid, stable (literally or figuratively) -- stedfast, strong, sure. see GREEK  (G2476) histemi
From  (G4731) stereos; to solidify, i.e. Confirm (literally or figuratively) -- establish, receive strength, make strong. see GREEK  (G4731) stereos

column7: a solid body, a support, strength, firmness
column9: From  (G4732) stereoo; something established, i.e. (abstractly) confirmation (stability) -- stedfastness. see GREEK  (G4732) stereoo

column7: crowned, Stephanas, a Christian at Corinth
column9: Probably contraction for stephanotos (crowned; from  (G4737) stephanoo); Stephanas, a Christian -- Stephanas. see GREEK  (G4737) stephanoo

From an apparently primary stepho (to twine or wreathe); a chaplet (as a badge of royalty, a prize in the public games or a symbol of honor generally; but more conspicuous and elaborate than the simple fillet,  (G1238) diadema), literally or figuratively -- crown. see GREEK  (G1238) diadema

column7: crown, Stephen, the first Christian martyr
column9: The same as  (G4735) stephanos; Stephanus, a Christian -- Stephen. see GREEK  (G4735) stephanos
From  (G4735) stephanos; to adorn with an honorary wreath (literally or figuratively) -- crown. see GREEK  (G4735) stephanos
From  (G2476) histemi (as standing prominently); the (entire external) bosom, i.e. Chest -- breast. see GREEK  (G2476) histemi
From the perfect tense of  (G2476) histemi; to be stationary, i.e. (figuratively) to persevere -- stand (fast). see GREEK  (G2476) histemi
From  (G4741) sterizo; stability (figuratively) -- stedfastness. see GREEK  (G4741) sterizo

From a presumed derivative of  (G2476) histemi (like  (G4731) stereos); to set fast, i.e. (literally) to turn resolutely in a certain direction, or (figuratively) to confirm -- fix, (e-)stablish, stedfastly set, strengthen. see GREEK  (G2476) histemi see GREEK  (G4731) stereos

column7: a bed of leaves or rushes
column9: From a primary stizo (to "stick", i.e. Prick); a mark incised or punched (for recognition of ownership), i.e. (figuratively) scar of service -- mark.
Feminine of  (G4742) stigma; a point of time, i.e. An instant -- moment. see GREEK  (G4742) stigma
Apparently a primary verb; to gleam, i.e. Flash intensely -- shining.
Probably from  (G2476) histemi; a colonnade or interior piazza -- porch. see GREEK  (G2476) histemi
From a primary steibo (to "step" or "stamp"); a spread (as if tramped flat) of loose materials for a couch, i.e. (by implication) a bough of a tree so employed -- branch.

column7: one of a row, a letter (of the alphabet),  the elements (of knowledge)
column9: Neuter of a presumed derivative of the base of  (G4748) stoicheo; something orderly in arrangement, i.e. (by implication) a serial (basal, fundamental, initial) constituent (literally), proposition (figuratively) -- element, principle, rudiment. see GREEK  (G4748) stoicheo

column7: to be in rows, to walk by rule
column9: From a derivative of steicho (to range in regular line); to march in (military) rank (keep step), i.e. (figuratively) to conform to virtue and piety -- walk (orderly).
From  (G4724) stello; equipment, i.e. (specially), a "stole" or long-fitting gown (as a mark of dignity) -- long clothing (garment), (long) robe. see GREEK  (G4724) stello

Probably strengthened from a presumed derivative of the base of  (G5114) tomoteros; the mouth (as if a gash in the face); by implication, language (and its relations); figuratively, an opening (in the earth); specially, the front or edge (of a weapon) -- edge, face, mouth. see GREEK  (G5114) tomoteros
From  (G4750) stoma; an orifice (the gullet), i.e. (specially), the "stomach" -- stomach. see GREEK  (G4750) stoma
From  (G4754) strateuomai; military service, i.e. (figuratively) the apostolic career (as one of hardship and danger) -- warfare. see GREEK  (G4754) strateuomai

column7: an expedition, an army, a company of soldiers
column9: From  (G4754) strateuomai; an armament, i.e. (by implication) a body of troops (more or less extensive or systematic) -- army, soldier, man of war. see GREEK  (G4754) strateuomai

column7: to make war, to serve as a soldier
column9: Middle voice from the base of  (G4756) stratia; to serve in a military campaign; figuratively, to execute the apostolate (with its arduous duties and functions), to contend with carnal inclinations -- soldier, (go to) war(-fare). see GREEK  (G4756) stratia

From the base of  (G4756) stratia and  (G71) ago or  (G2233) hegeomai; a general, i.e. (by implication or analogy) a (military) governor (praetor), the chief (praefect) of the (Levitical) temple-wardens -- captain, magistrate. see GREEK  (G4756) stratia see GREEK  (G71) ago see GREEK  (G2233) hegeomai

Feminine of a derivative of stratos (an army; from the base of  (G4766) stronnumi, as encamped); camp-likeness, i.e. An army, i.e. (figuratively) the angels, the celestial luminaries -- host. see GREEK  (G4766) stronnumi
From a presumed derivative of the same as  (G4756) stratia; a camper-out, i.e. A (common) warrior (literally or figuratively) -- soldier. see GREEK  (G4756) stratia

From a compound of the base of  (G4756) stratia and  (G3004) lego (in its original sense); to gather (or select) as a warrior, i.e. Enlist in the army -- choose to be a soldier. see GREEK  (G4756) stratia see GREEK  (G3004) lego

column4: Noun, MasculinePhonetic Spelling: (strat-op-ed-ar\'-khace)Definition: captain of the guardUsage: commander of the Roman emperor\'s body-guard.Thayer\'s Greek LexiconSTRONGS NT 4759: \xcf\x83\xcf\x84\xcf\x81\xce\xb1\xcf\x84\xce\xbf\xcf\x80\xce\xb5\xce\xb4\xce\xac\xcf\x81\xcf\x87\xce\xb7\xcf\x82\xcf\x83\xcf\x84\xcf\x81\xce\xb1\xcf\x84\xce\xbf\xcf\x80\xce\xb5\xce\xb4\xce\xac\xcf\x81\xcf\x87\xce\xb7\xcf\x82, \xcf\x83\xcf\x84\xcf\x81\xce\xb1\xcf\x84\xce\xbf\xcf\x80\xce\xb5\xce\xb4\xce\xb1\xcf\x81\xcf\x87\xce\xbf\xcf\x85, \xe1\xbd\x81 (\xcf\x83\xcf\x84\xcf\x81\xce\xb1\xcf\x84\xcf\x8c\xcf\x80\xce\xb5\xce\xb4\xce\xbf\xce\xbd and \xe1\xbc\x84\xcf\x81\xcf\x87\xcf\x89) (cf. Buttmann, 73 (64)); a. the commander of a camp and army, a military tribune: Dionysius Halicarnassus 10, 36; Lucian, hist. conscr. 22; (Josephus, b. j. 2, 19, 4). b. Praetorian prefect, commander of the praetorian cohorts, i. e. captain of the Roman emperor\'s bodyguard: Acts 28:16 (L T Tr WH omit the clause, see Abbot in B. D., American edition, under the word, Captain of the Guard). There were two praetorian prefects, to whose custody prisoners sent bound to the emperor were consigned: Josephus, Antiquities 18, 6, 6; Pliny, epistles 10, 65 (57). (See B. D. American edition as above; Lightfoot on Philippi, p. 7f.)   STRONGS NT 4759a: \xcf\x83\xcf\x84\xcf\x81\xce\xb1\xcf\x84\xce\xbf\xcf\x80\xce\xb5\xce\xb4\xce\xb1\xcf\x81\xcf\x87\xce\xbf\xcf\x82 [\xcf\x83\xcf\x84\xcf\x81\xce\xb1\xcf\x84\xce\xbf\xcf\x80\xce\xb5\xce\xb4\xce\xb1\xcf\x81\xcf\x87\xce\xbf\xcf\x82, \xcf\x83\xcf\x84\xcf\x81\xce\xb1\xcf\x84\xce\xbf\xcf\x80\xce\xb5\xce\xb4\xce\xb1\xcf\x81\xcf\x87\xce\xbf\xcf\x85, \xe1\xbd\x81: see the preceding word. The dative \xcf\x83\xcf\x84\xcf\x81\xce\xb1\xcf\x84\xce\xbf\xcf\x80\xce\xb5\xce\xb4\xce\xac\xcf\x81\xcf\x87\xe1\xbf\xb3 is the reading of some manuscripts (cf. WH rejected marginal reading) in Acts 28:16; cf.  \xe1\xbc\x91\xce\xba\xce\xb1\xcf\x84\xce\xbf\xce\xbd\xcf\x84\xce\xac\xcf\x81\xcf\x87\xce\xb7\xcf\x82, at the beginning]   Strong\'s Exhaustive Concordancecaptain of the guard. From stratopedon and archo; a ruler of an army, i.e. (specially), a Praetorian praefect -- captain of the guard. see GREEK stratopedon see GREEK archo g,4760,στρατόπεδον
column9: (strat-op'-ed-on)
column12: From the base of  (G4756) stratia and the same as  (G3977) pedinos; a camping-ground, i.e. (by implication) a body of troops -- army. see GREEK  (G4756) stratia see GREEK  (G3977) pedinos

column9: From a derivative of  (G4762) strepho; to wrench, i.e. (specially), to torture (by the rack), but only figuratively, to pervert -- wrest. see GREEK  (G4762) strepho
Strengthened from the base of  (G5157) trope; to twist, i.e. Turn quite around or reverse (literally or figuratively) -- convert, turn (again, back again, self, self about). see GREEK  (G5157) trope
From a presumed derivative of  (G4764) strenos; to be luxurious -- live deliciously. see GREEK  (G4764) strenos
Akin to  (G4731) stereos; a "straining", "strenuousness" or "strength", i.e. (figuratively) luxury (voluptuousness) -- delicacy. see GREEK  (G4731) stereos
Diminutive of strouthos (a sparrow); a little sparrow -- sparrow.

Or simpler stronnuo (strone-noo'-o), prolongation from a still simpler stroo (stro'-o), (used only as an alternate in certain tenses) (probably akin to  (G4731) stereos through the idea of positing); to "strew," i.e. Spread (as a carpet or couch) -- make bed, furnish, spread, strew. see GREEK  (G4731) stereos
From a derivative of an obsolete apparently primary stugo (to hate); hated, i.e. Odious -- hateful.
From the same as  (G4767) stugnetos; to render gloomy, i.e. (by implication) glower (be overcast with clouds, or sombreness of speech) -- lower, be sad. see GREEK  (G4767) stugnetos
From stuo (to stiffen; properly akin to the base of  (G2476) histemi); a post ("style"), i.e. (figuratively) support -- pillar. see GREEK  (G2476) histemi
From  (G4745) stoa; a "Stoic" (as occupying a particular porch in Athens), i.e. Adherent of a certin philosophy -- Stoick. see GREEK  (G4745) stoa

The person pronoun of the second person singular; thou -- thou. See also  (G4571) se,  (G4671) soi,  (G4675) sou; and for the plural  (G5209) humas,  (G5210) humeis,  (G5213) humin,  (G5216) humon. see GREEK  (G4675) sou see GREEK  (G4571) se see GREEK  (G4671) soi see GREEK  (G5209) humas see GREEK  (G5210) humeis see GREEK  (G5213) humin see GREEK  (G5216) humon
From  (G4773) suggenes; relationship, i.e. (concretely) relatives -- kindred. see GREEK  (G4773) suggenes

column7: congenital, akin to, subst. a kinsman, relative
column9: From  (G4862) sun and  (G1085) genos; a relative (by blood); by extension, a fellow countryman -- cousin, kin(-sfolk, -sman). see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G1085) genos
From a compound of  (G4862) sun and  (G1097) ginosko; fellow knowledge, i.e. Concession -- permission. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G1097) ginosko
From  (G4862) sun and  (G2521) kathemai; to seat oneself in company with -- sit with. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G2521) kathemai

column7: to make to sit together, to sit together
column9: From  (G4862) sun and  (G2523) kathizo; to give (or take) a seat in company with -- (make) sit (down) together. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G2523) kathizo

column7: to bear evil treatment along with
column9: From  (G4862) sun and  (G2553) kakopatheo; to suffer hardship in company with -- be partaker of afflictions. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G2553) kakopatheo
From  (G4862) sun and  (G2558) kakoucheo; to maltreat in company with, i.e. (passively) endure persecution together -- suffer affliction with. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G2558) kakoucheo
From  (G4862) sun and  (G2564) kaleo; to convoke -- call together. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G2564) kaleo
From  (G4862) sun and  (G2572) kalupto; to conceal altogether -- cover. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G2572) kalupto
From  (G4862) sun and  (G2578) kampto; to bend together, i.e. (figuratively) to afflict -- bow down. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G2578) kampto
From  (G4862) sun and  (G2597) katabaino; to descend in company with -- go down with. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G2597) katabaino
From  (G4784) sugkatatithemai; a deposition (of sentiment) in company with, i.e. (figuratively) accord with -- agreement. see GREEK  (G4784) sugkatatithemai

column7: to deposit together, to agree with
column9: Mid from  (G4862) sun and  (G2698) katatithemi; to deposit (one's vote or opinion) in company with, i.e. (figuratively) to accord with -- consent. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G2698) katatithemi

column7: to condemn with, to vote (one) a place among
column9: From  (G4862) sun and a compound of  (G2596) kata and  (G5585) psephizo; to count down in company with, i.e. Enroll among -- number with. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G2596) kata see GREEK  (G5585) psephizo

column7: to mix together, to agree with
column9: From  (G4862) sun and  (G2767) kerannumi; to commingle, i.e. (figuratively) to combine or assimilate -- mix with, temper together. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G2767) kerannumi

column7: to move together, to stir up
column9: From  (G4682) sparasso and  (G2795) kineo; to move together, i.e. (specially), to excite as a mass (to sedition) -- stir up. see GREEK  (G4682) sparasso see GREEK  (G2795) kineo
From  (G4862) sun and  (G2808) kleio; to shut together, i.e. Include or (figuratively) embrace in a common subjection to -- conclude, inclose, shut up. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G2808) kleio
From  (G4862) sun and  (G2818) kleronomos; a co-heir, i.e. (by analogy) participant in common -- fellow (joint)-heir, heir together, heir with. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G2818) kleronomos

column8: fellowship, communicate with, be partaker of.
column9: From  (G4862) sun and  (G2841) koinoneo; to share in company with, i.e. Co-participate in -- communicate (have fellowship) with, be partaker of. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G2841) koinoneo
From  (G4862) sun and  (G2844) koinonos; a co-participant -- companion, partake(-r, -r with). see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G2844) koinonos

column7: to bring together, to take up (a body for burial)
column9: From  (G4862) sun and  (G2865) komizo; to convey together, i.e. Collect or bear away in company with others -- carry. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G2865) komizo

From  (G4862) sun and  (G2919) krino; to judge of one thing in connection with another, i.e. Combine (spiritual ideas with appropriate expressions) or collate (one person with another by way of contrast or resemblance) -- compare among (with). see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G2919) krino
From  (G4862) sun and  (G2955) kupto; to stoop altogether, i.e. Be completely overcome by -- bow together. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G2955) kupto
From a comparative of  (G4862) sun and kureo (to light or happen; from the base of  (G2962) kurios); concurrence, i.e. Accident -- chance. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G2962) kurios
From  (G4862) sun and  (G5463) chairo; to sympathize in gladness, congratulate -- rejoice in (with). see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G5463) chairo

column7: to pour together, to confuse, throw into confusion
column8: confound, confuse, stir up, be in an uproar.
column9: Or sugchuno (soong-khoo'-no) from  (G4862) sun and cheo (to pour) or its alternate; to commingle promiscuously, i.e. (figuratively) to throw (an assembly) into disorder, to perplex (the mind) -- confound, confuse, stir up, be in an uproar. see GREEK  (G4862) sun

column7: to use together with, to associate with
column9: From  (G4862) sun and  (G5530) chraomai; to use jointly, i.e. (by implication) to hold intercourse in common -- have dealings with. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G5530) chraomai
From  (G4797) sugcheo; commixture, i.e. (figuratively) riotous disturbance -- confusion. see GREEK  (G4797) sugcheo
From  (G4862) sun and  (G2198) zao; to continue to live in common with, i.e. Co-survive (literally or figuratively) -- live with. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G2198) zao
From  (G4862) sun and the base of  (G2201) zeugos; to yoke together, i.e. (figuratively) conjoin (in marriage) -- join together. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G2201) zeugos

From  (G4862) sun and  (G2212) zeteo; to investigate jointly, i.e. Discuss, controvert, cavil -- dispute (with), enquire, question (with), reason (together). see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G2212) zeteo
From  (G4802) suzeteo; mutual questioning, i.e. Discussion -- disputation(-ting), reasoning. see GREEK  (G4802) suzeteo
From  (G4802) suzeteo; a disputant, i.e. Sophist -- disputer. see GREEK  (G4802) suzeteo
From  (G4801) suzeugnumi; co-yoked, i.e. (figuratively) as noun, a colleague; probably rather as a proper name; Syzygus, a Christian -- yokefellow. see GREEK  (G4801) suzeugnumi
From  (G4862) sun and  (G2227) zoopoieo; to reanimate conjointly with (figuratively) -- quicken together with. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G2227) zoopoieo
Of Hebrew origin ( (H8256) shaqam) in imitation of  (G4809) sukomoraia; a sycamore-fig tree -- sycamine tree. see GREEK  (G4809) sukomoraia see HEBREW  (H8256) shaqam
From  (G4810) sukon; a fig-tree -- fig tree. see GREEK  (G4810) sukon
From  (G4810) sukon and moron (the mulberry); the "sycamore"-fig tree -- sycamore tree. Compare  (G4807) sukaminos. see GREEK  (G4810) sukon see GREEK  (G4807) sukaminos
Apparently a primary word; a fig -- fig.

column8: accuse falsely, take by false accusation.
column9: From a compound of  (G4810) sukon and a derivative of  (G5316) phaino; to be a fig-informer (reporter of the law forbidding the exportation of figs from Greece), "sycophant", i.e. (genitive and by extension) to defraud (exact unlawfully, extort) -- accuse falsely, take by false accusation. see GREEK  (G4810) sukon see GREEK  (G5316) phaino
From the base of  (G4813) sulao and (the reduplicated form of)  (G71) ago; to lead away as booty, i.e. (figuratively) seduce -- spoil. see GREEK  (G4813) sulao see GREEK  (G71) ago
From a derivative of sullo (to strip; probably akin to  (G138) haireomai; compare  (G4661) skulon); to despoil -- rob. see GREEK  (G138) haireomai see GREEK  (G4661) skulon
From  (G4862) sun and  (G2980) laleo; to talk together, i.e. Converse -- commune (confer, talk) with, speak among. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G2980) laleo

column7: to collect, to take, by implication to take part with, to conceive
column9: From  (G4862) sun and  (G2983) lambano; to clasp, i.e. Seize (arrest, capture); specially, to conceive (literally or figuratively); by implication, to aid -- catch, conceive, help, take. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G2983) lambano
From  (G4862) sun and  (G3004) lego in its original sense; to collect -- gather (together, up). see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G3004) lego

column7: to reckon, to compute, to reason
column9: From  (G4862) sun and  (G3049) logizomai; to reckon together (with oneself), i.e. Deliberate -- reason with. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G3049) logizomai

column7: to be moved to grief with (pass.)
column9: From  (G4862) sun and  (G3076) lupeo; to afflict jointly, i.e. (passive) sorrow at (on account of) someone -- be grieved. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G3076) lupeo

column7: to come together, (of events) to come to pass
column9: From  (G4862) sun and the base of  (G939) basis; to walk (figuratively, transpire) together, i.e. Concur (take place) -- be(-fall), happen (unto). see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G939) basis

column7: to throw together, to discuss, consider, meet with
column9: From  (G4862) sun and  (G906) ballo; to combine, i.e. (in speaking) to converse, consult, dispute, (mentally) to consider, (by implication) to aid, (personally) to join, attack -- confer, encounter, help, make, meet with, ponder. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G906) ballo
From  (G4862) sun and  (G936) basileuo; to be co-regent (figuratively) -- reign with. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G936) basileuo

column7: to join together, to consider,  to teach
column9: From  (G4862) sun and bibazo (to force; causative (by reduplication) of the base of  (G939) basis); to drive together, i.e. Unite (in association or affection), (mentally) to infer, show, teach -- compact, assuredly gather, intrust, knit together, prove. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G939) basis

From  (G4862) sun and  (G1011) bouleuo; to give (or take) advice jointly, i.e. Recommend, deliberate or determine -- consult, (give, take) counsel (together). see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G1011) bouleuo

Neuter of a presumed derivative of  (G4825) sumboulos; advisement; specially, a deliberative body, i.e. The provincial assessors or lay-court -- consultation, counsel, council. see GREEK  (G4825) sumboulos
From  (G4862) sun and  (G1012) boule; a consultor, i.e. Adviser -- counsellor. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G1012) boule

column7: Symeon, Simeon, the name of several Israelites, also a tribe of Isr
column9: From the same as  (G4613) Simon; Symeon (i.e. Shimon), the name of five Israelites -- Simeon, Simon. see GREEK  (G4613) Simon
From a compound of  (G4862) sun and  (G3129) manthano; a co-learner (of Christianity) -- fellow disciple. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G3129) manthano

column7: to testify or bear witness with
column9: From  (G4862) sun and  (G3140) martureo; to testify jointly, i.e. Corroborate by (concurrent) evidence -- testify unto, (also) bear witness (with). see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G3140) martureo
Middle voice from  (G4862) sun and  (G3307) merizo; to share jointly, i.e. Participate in -- be partaker with. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G3307) merizo

column7: partaking with, subst. a joint partaker
column9: From  (G4862) sun and  (G3353) metochos; a co-participant -- partaker. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G3353) metochos
From a presumed compound of  (G4862) sun and  (G3401) mimeomai; a co-imitator, i.e. Fellow votary -- follower together. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G3401) mimeomai
From  (G4862) sun and  (G3444) morphe; jointly formed, i.e. (figuratively) similar -- conformed to, fashioned like unto. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G3444) morphe

column7: conform to, fashion self according to
column8: conform to, fashion self according to.
column9: From  (G4832) summorphos; to render like, i.e. (figuratively) to assimilate -- make conformable unto. see GREEK  (G4832) summorphos

column7: to have a fellow feeling with, sympathize with
column9: From  (G4835) sumpathes; to feel "sympathy" with, i.e. (by implication) to commiserate -- have compassion, be touched with a feeling of. see GREEK  (G4835) sumpathes
From  (G4841) sumpascho; having a fellow-feeling ("sympathetic"), i.e. (by implication) mutually commiserative -- having compassion one of another. see GREEK  (G4841) sumpascho

From  (G4862) sun and  (G3854) paraginomai; to be present together, i.e. To convene; by implication, to appear in aid -- come together, stand with. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G3854) paraginomai

column7: to exhort together, pass. to be strengthened with
column9: From  (G4862) sun and  (G3870) parakaleo; to console jointly -- comfort together. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G3870) parakaleo
From  (G4862) sun and  (G3880) paralambano; to take along in company -- take with. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G3880) paralambano
From  (G4862) sun and  (G3887) parameno; to remain in company, i.e. Still live -- continue with. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G3887) parameno
From  (G4862) sun and  (G3918) pareimi; to be at hand together, i.e. Now present -- be here present with. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G3918) pareimi

From  (G4862) sun and  (G3958) pascho (including its alternate); to experience pain jointly or of the same kind (specially, persecution; to "sympathize") -- suffer with. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G3958) pascho
From  (G4862) sun and  (G3992) pempo; to despatch in company -- send with. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G3992) pempo

From  (G4862) sun and a compound of  (G4012) peri and  (G2983) lambano; to take by enclosing altogether, i.e. Earnestly throw the arms about one -- embrace. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G4012) peri see GREEK  (G2983) lambano
From  (G4862) sun and  (G4095) pino; to partake a beverage in company -- drink with. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G4095) pino

column7: to fill up completely, to fulfill
column9: From  (G4862) sun and  (G4137) pleroo; to implenish completely, i.e. (of space) to swamp (a boat), or (of time) to accomplish (passive, be complete) -- (fully) come, fill up. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G4137) pleroo
From  (G4862) sun and  (G4155) pnigo; to strangle completely, i.e. (literally) to drown, or (figuratively) to crowd -- choke, throng. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G4155) pnigo
From  (G4862) sun and  (G4177) polites; a native of the same town, i.e. (figuratively) co-religionist (fellow-Christian) -- fellow- citizen. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G4177) polites

column7: to journey together, to come together
column9: From  (G4862) sun and  (G4198) poreuomai; to journey together; by implication, to assemble -- go with, resort. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G4198) poreuomai

column7: a drinking party, company (guests at a party)
column9: Neuter of a derivative of the alternate of  (G4844) sumpino; a drinking-party ("symposium"), i.e. (by extension) a room of guests -- company. see GREEK  (G4844) sumpino
From  (G4862) sun and  (G4245) presbuteros; a co-presbyter -- presbyter, also an elder. see GREEK  (G4245) presbuteros see GREEK  (G4862) sun

column7: to bring together, to be profitable
column8: bring together, be expedient, be profitable for.
column9: From  (G4862) sun and  (G5342) phero (including its alternate); to bear together (contribute), i.e. (literally) to collect, or (figuratively) to conduce; especially (neuter participle as a noun) advantage -- be better for, bring together, be expedient (for), be good, (be) profit(-able for). see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G5342) phero
From  (G4862) sun and  (G5346) phemi; to say jointly, i.e. Assent to -- consent unto. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G5346) phemi
From  (G4862) sun and a derivative of  (G5443) phule; a co-tribesman, i.e. Native of the same country -- countryman. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G5443) phule
From  (G4862) sun and a derivative of  (G5453) phuo; grown along with (connate), i.e. (figuratively) closely united to -- planted together. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G5453) phuo
From  (G4862) sun and  (G5453) phuo; passive, to grow jointly -- spring up with. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G5453) phuo

column7: to call out with, to be in harmony, generally to agree
column9: From  (G4859) sumphonos; to be harmonious, i.e. (figuratively) to accord (be suitable, concur) or stipulate (by compact) -- agree (together, with). see GREEK  (G4859) sumphonos
From  (G4856) sumphoneo; accordance -- concord. see GREEK  (G4856) sumphoneo
From  (G4859) sumphonos; unison of sound ("symphony"), i.e. A concert of instruments (harmonious note) -- music. see GREEK  (G4859) sumphonos
From  (G4862) sun and  (G5456) phone; sounding together (alike), i.e. (figuratively) accordant (neuter as noun, agreement) -- consent. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G5456) phone
From  (G4862) sun and  (G5585) psephizo; to compute jointly -- reckon. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G5585) psephizo
From  (G4862) sun and  (G5590) psuche; co-spirited, i.e. Similar in sentiment -- like-minded. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G5590) psuche

A primary preposition denoting union; with or together (but much closer than  (G3326) meta or  (G3844) para), i.e. By association, companionship, process, resemblance, possession, instrumentality, addition, etc. -- beside, with. In composition it has similar applications, including completeness. see GREEK  (G3326) meta see GREEK  (G3844) para

column7: to lead together, bring together, come together (pass.), entertain
column9: From  (G4862) sun and  (G71) ago; to lead together, i.e. Collect or convene; specially, to entertain (hospitably) -- + accompany, assemble (selves, together), bestow, come together, gather (selves together, up, together), lead into, resort, take in. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G71) ago

column7: a bringing together,  an assembling, a synagogue
column9: From (the reduplicated form of)  (G4863) sunago; an assemblage of persons; specially, a Jewish "synagogue" (the meeting or the place); by analogy, a Christian church -- assembly, congregation, synagogue. see GREEK  (G4863) sunago
From  (G4862) sun and  (G75) agonizomai; to struggle in company with, i.e. (figuratively) to be a partner (assistant) -- strive together with. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G75) agonizomai
From  (G4862) sun and  (G118) athleo; to wrestle in company with, i.e. (figuratively) to seek jointly -- labour with, strive together for. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G118) athleo
From  (G4862) sun and athroizo (to hoard); to convene -- call (gather) together. see GREEK  (G4862) sun

column7: to take up together, settle accounts
column9: From  (G4862) sun and  (G142) airo; to make up together, i.e. (figuratively) to compute (an account) -- reckon, take. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G142) airo
From  (G4862) sun and  (G164) aichmalotos; a co-captive -- fellowprisoner. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G164) aichmalotos
From  (G4862) sun and  (G190) akoloutheo; to accompany -- follow. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G190) akoloutheo
From  (G4862) sun and halizo (to throng); to accumulate, i.e. Convene -- assemble together. see GREEK  (G4862) sun
From  (G4862) sun and  (G305) anabaino; to ascend in company with -- come up with. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G305) anabaino
From  (G4862) sun and  (G345) anakeimai; to recline in company with (at a meal) -- sit (down, at the table, together) with (at meat). see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G345) anakeimai

column7: to mix up together, to associate with
column9: From  (G4862) sun and a compound of  (G303) ana and  (G3396) mignumi; to mix up together, i.e. (figurative) associate with -- (have, keep) company (with). see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G303) ana see GREEK  (G3396) mignumi

column7: to lie down to rest with, to be refreshed in spirit with
column9: Middle from  (G4862) sun and  (G373) anapano; to recruit oneself in company with -- refresh with. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G373) anapano
From  (G4862) sun and a derivative of  (G473) anti; to meet with; figuratively, to occur -- befall, meet. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G473) anti
From  (G4876) sunantao; a meeting with -- meet. see GREEK  (G4876) sunantao

column7: to take hold with at the side, to take a share in, generally to help
column9: From  (G4862) sun and  (G482) antilambanomai; to take hold of opposite together, i.e. Co-operate (assist) -- help. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G482) antilambanomai

column7: to lead away with, to be carried away with (pass.)
column9: From  (G4862) sun and  (G520) apago; to take off together, i.e. Transport with (seduce, passively, yield) -- carry (lead) away with, condescend. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G520) apago
From  (G4862) sun and  (G599) apothnesko; to decease (literally) in company with, or (figuratively), similarly to -- be dead (die) with. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G599) apothnesko

column7: to destroy with, mid. to perish together
column9: From  (G4862) sun and  (G622) apollumi; to destroy (middle voice or passively, be slain) in company with -- perish with. see GREEK  (G4862) sun see GREEK  (G622) apollumi
