Of Hebrew origin ( (H6439) Pnuw'el); Phanuel (i.e. Penuel), an Israelite -- Phanuel. see HEBREW  (H6439) Pnuw'el

column7: to make visible, to become visible
column9: From a derivative of  (G5316) phaino; to make apparent, i.e. (passively) to appear (neuter participle as noun, a spectacle) -- sight. see GREEK  (G5316) phaino
From a derivative of  (G5324) phantazo; (properly abstract) a (vain) show ("fantasy") -- pomp. see GREEK  (G5324) phantazo
From  (G5324) phantazo; (properly concrete) a (mere) show ("phantasm"), i.e. Spectre -- spirit. see GREEK  (G5324) phantazo
Properly, strengthened from the base of  (G4008) peran or rather of  (G4486) rhegnumi; a gap or chasm, i.e. Ravine (winter-torrent) -- valley. see GREEK  (G4486) rhegnumi see GREEK  (G4008) peran
Of foreign origin ( (H6547) Par'oh); Pharao (i.e. Pharoh), an Egyptian king -- Pharaoh. see HEBREW  (H6547) Par'oh
Of Hebrew origin ( (H6557) Perets); Phares (i.e. Perets), an Israelite -- Phares. see HEBREW  (H6557) Perets

column7: a Pharisee, member of a Jewish religious sect
column9: Of Hebrew origin (compare  (H6567) parash); a separatist, i.e. Exclusively religious; a Pharisean, i.e. Jewish sectary -- Pharisee. see HEBREW  (H6567) parash

column7: the use of medicine, drugs or spells
column9: From  (G5332) pharmakeus; medication ("pharmacy"), i.e. (by extension) magic (literally or figuratively) -- sorcery, witchcraft. see GREEK  (G5332) pharmakeus
From pharmakon (a drug, i.e. Spell-giving potion); a druggist ("pharmacist") or poisoner, i.e. (by extension) a magician -- sorcerer.
The same as  (G5332) pharmakeus -- sorcerer.
From  (G5346) phemi (not the same as "phase", which is from  (G5316) phaino); a saying, i.e. Report -- tidings. see GREEK  (G5346) phemi see GREEK  (G5316) phaino
Prolongation from the same as  (G5346) phemi; to assert -- affirm, profess, say. see GREEK  (G5346) phemi
From pateomai (to eat); a crib (for fodder) -- manager, stall.
Apparently a primary word; "foul" or "flawy", i.e. (figuratively) wicked -- evil.
Probably akin to the base of  (G5457) phos (compare  (G5350) phtheggomai); brilliancy -- light. see GREEK  (G5457) phos see GREEK  (G5350) phtheggomai
Of uncertain affinity; to be chary of, i.e. (subjectively) to abstain or (objectively) to treat leniently -- forbear, spare.
Adverb from participle of  (G5339) pheidomai; abstemiously, i.e. Stingily -- sparingly. see GREEK  (G5339) pheidomai
By transposition for a derivative probably of  (G5316) phaino (as showing outside the other garments); a mantle (surtout) -- cloke. see GREEK  (G5316) phaino

A primary verb -- for which other, and apparently not cognate ones are used in certain tenses only; namely, oio (oy'-o); and enegko (en-eng'-ko) to "bear" or carry (in a very wide application, literally and figuratively, as follows)
Apparently a primary verb; to run away (literally or figuratively); by implication, to shun; by analogy, to vanish -- escape, flee (away).

column7: fortunate, Felix, a governor of Judea
column9: Of Latin origin; happy; Phelix (i.e. Felix), a Roman -- Felix.
From  (G5346) phemi; a saying, i.e. Rumor ("fame") -- fame. see GREEK  (G5346) phemi

Properly, the same as the base of  (G5457) phos and  (G5316) phaino; to show or make known one's thoughts, i.e. Speak or say -- affirm, say. Compare  (G3004) lego. see GREEK  (G5457) phos see GREEK  (G5316) phaino see GREEK  (G3004) lego
Of Latin derivation; festal; Phestus (i.e. Festus), a Roman -- Festus.
Apparently a primary verb; to be beforehand, i.e. Anticipate or precede; by extension, to have arrived at -- (already) attain, come, prevent.
From  (G5351) phtheiro; decayed, i.e. (by implication) perishable -- corruptible. see GREEK  (G5351) phtheiro
Probably akin to  (G5338) pheggos and thus to  (G5346) phemi; to utter a clear sound, i.e. (generally) to proclaim -- speak. see GREEK  (G5346) phemi see GREEK  (G5338) pheggos

Probably strengthened from phthio (to pine or waste); properly, to shrivel or wither, i.e. To spoil (by any process) or (generally) to ruin (especially figuratively, by moral influences, to deprave) -- corrupt (self), defile, destroy.

From derivative of phthino (to wane; akin to the base of  (G5351) phtheiro) and  (G3703) opora (meaning late autumn); autumnal (as stripped of leaves) -- whose fruit withereth. see GREEK  (G5351) phtheiro see GREEK  (G3703) opora
From  (G5350) phtheggomai; utterance, i.e. A musical note (vocal or instrumental) -- sound. see GREEK  (G5350) phtheggomai
From  (G5355) phthonos; to be jealous of -- envy. see GREEK  (G5355) phthonos
Probably akin to the base of  (G5351) phtheiro; ill-will (as detraction), i.e. Jealousy (spite) -- envy. see GREEK  (G5351) phtheiro
From  (G5351) phtheiro; decay, i.e. Ruin (spontaneous or inflicted, literally or figuratively) -- corruption, destroy, perish. see GREEK  (G5351) phtheiro
Of uncertain affinity; a broad shallow cup ("phial") -- vial.
From  (G5384) philos and  (G18) agathos; fond to good, i.e. A promoter of virtue -- love of good men. see GREEK  (G5384) philos see GREEK  (G18) agathos
From Philadelphos (the same as  (G5361) philadelphos), a king of Pergamos; Philadelphia, a place in Asia Minor -- Philadelphia. see GREEK  (G5361) philadelphos

column7: the love of brothers, brotherly love
column9: From  (G5361) philadelphos; fraternal affection -- brotherly love (kindness), love of the brethren. see GREEK  (G5361) philadelphos
From  (G5384) philos and  (G80) adephos; fond of brethren, i.e. Fraternal -- love as brethren. see GREEK  (G5384) philos see GREEK  (G80) adephos

column7: loving men, (of a wife) loving her husband
column9: From  (G5384) philos and  (G435) aner; fond of man, i.e. Affectionate as a wife -- love their husbands. see GREEK  (G5384) philos see GREEK  (G435) aner
From the same as  (G5364) philanthropos; fondness of mankind, i.e. Benevolence ("philanthropy") -- kindness, love towards man. see GREEK  (G5364) philanthropos
Adverb from a compound of  (G5384) philos and  (G444) anthropos; fondly to man ("philanthropically"), i.e. Humanely -- courteously. see GREEK  (G5384) philos see GREEK  (G444) anthropos
From  (G5366) philarguros; avarice -- love of money. see GREEK  (G5366) philarguros
From  (G5384) philos and  (G696) arguros; fond of silver (money), i.e. Avaricious -- covetous. see GREEK  (G5384) philos see GREEK  (G696) arguros
From  (G5384) philos and  (G846) autos; fond of self, i.e. Selfish -- lover of own self. see GREEK  (G5384) philos see GREEK  (G846) autos

From  (G5384) philos; to be a friend to (fond of (an individual or an object)), i.e. Have affection for (denoting personal attachment, as a matter of sentiment or feeling; while  (G25) agapao is wider, embracing especially the judgment and the deliberate assent of the will as a matter of principle, duty and propriety: the two thus stand related very much as  (G2309) ethelo and  (G1014) boulomai, or as  (G2372) thumos and  (G3563) nous respectively; the former being chiefly of the heart and the latter of the head); specially, to kiss (as a mark of tenderness) -- kiss, love. see GREEK  (G5384) philos see GREEK  (G2372) thumos see GREEK  (G25) agapao see GREEK  (G2309) ethelo see GREEK  (G1014) boulomai see GREEK  (G3563) nous
From  (G5384) philos and  (G2237) hedone; fond of pleasure, i.e. Voluptuous -- lover of pleasure. see GREEK  (G5384) philos see GREEK  (G2237) hedone
From  (G5368) phileo; a kiss -- kiss. see GREEK  (G5368) phileo
From  (G5368) phileo; friendly; Philemon, a Christian -- Philemon. see GREEK  (G5368) phileo

column7: worthy of love, Philetus, an erring Christian at Ephesus
column9: From  (G5368) phileo; amiable; Philetus, an opposer of Christianity -- Philetus. see GREEK  (G5368) phileo
From  (G5384) philos; fondness -- friendship. see GREEK  (G5384) philos
From  (G5375) Philippoi; a Philippesian (Philippian), i.e. Native of Philippi -- Philippian. see GREEK  (G5375) Philippoi
Plural of  (G5376) Philippos; Philippi, a place in Macedonia -- Philippi. see GREEK  (G5376) Philippos

column7: horse-loving, Philip, two sons of Herod the Great, also two Christians
column9: From  (G5384) philos and  (G2462) hippos; fond of horses; Philippus, the name of four Israelites -- Philip. see GREEK  (G5384) philos see GREEK  (G2462) hippos
From  (G5384) philos and  (G2316) theos; fond of God, i.e. Pious -- lover of God. see GREEK  (G5384) philos see GREEK  (G2316) theos

From  (G5384) philos and  (G3056) logos; fond of words, i.e. Talkative (argumentative, learned, "philological"); Philologus, a Christian -- Philologus. see GREEK  (G5384) philos see GREEK  (G3056) logos
From  (G5380) philoneikos; quarrelsomeness, i.e. A dispute -- strife. see GREEK  (G5380) philoneikos
From  (G5384) philos and neikos (a quarrel; probably akin to  (G3534) nikos); fond of strife, i.e. Disputatious -- contentious. see GREEK  (G5384) philos see GREEK  (G3534) nikos
From  (G5382) philoxenos; hospitableness -- entertain stranger, hospitality. see GREEK  (G5382) philoxenos
From  (G5384) philos and  (G3581) xenos; fond of guests, i.e. Hospitable -- given to (lover of, use) hospitality. see GREEK  (G5384) philos see GREEK  (G3581) xenos
From a compound of  (G5384) philos and  (G4413) protos; to be fond of being first, i.e. Ambitious of distinction -- love to have the preeminence. see GREEK  (G5384) philos see GREEK  (G4413) protos
Properly, dear, i.e. A friend; actively, fond, i.e. Friendly (still as a noun, an associate, neighbor, etc.) -- friend.

column7: the love or pursuit of wisdom
column9: From  (G5386) philosophos; "philosophy", i.e. (specially), Jewish sophistry -- philosophy. see GREEK  (G5386) philosophos
From  (G5384) philos and  (G4680) sophos; fond of wise things, i.e. A "philosopher" -- philosopher. see GREEK  (G5384) philos see GREEK  (G4680) sophos

From  (G5384) philos and storge (cherishing one's kindred, especially parents or children); fond of natural relatives, i.e. Fraternal towards fellow Christian -- kindly affectioned. see GREEK  (G5384) philos
From  (G5384) philos and  (G5043) teknon; fond of one's children, i.e. Maternal -- love their children. see GREEK  (G5384) philos see GREEK  (G5043) teknon

column7: to love or seek after honor
column9: Middle voice from a compound of  (G5384) philos and  (G5092) time; to be fond of honor, i.e. Emulous (eager or earnest to do something) -- labour, strive, study. see GREEK  (G5384) philos see GREEK  (G5092) time
Adverb from  (G5391) philophron; with friendliness of mind, i.e. Kindly -- courteously. see GREEK  (G5391) philophron
From  (G5384) philos and  (G5424) phren; friendly of mind, i.e. Kind -- courteous. see GREEK  (G5384) philos see GREEK  (G5424) phren

column7: to muzzle, to put to silence
column9: From phimos (a muzzle); to muzzle -- muzzle.
Active participle of the base of  (G5395) phlox; blazing; Phlegon, a Christian -- Phlegon. see GREEK  (G5395) phlox
From  (G5395) phlox; to cause a blaze, i.e. Ignite (figuratively, to inflame with passion) -- set on fire. see GREEK  (G5395) phlox
From a primary phlego (to "flash" or "flame"); a blaze -- flame(-ing).
From  (G5397) phluaros; to be a babbler or trifler, i.e. (by implication) to berate idly or mischievously -- prate against. see GREEK  (G5397) phluaros
From phluo (to bubble); a garrulous person, i.e. Prater -- tattler.
From  (G5401) phobos; frightful, i.e. (objectively) formidable -- fearful, terrible. see GREEK  (G5401) phobos

column7: to put to flight, to terrify, frighten
column9: From  (G5401) phobos; to frighten, i.e. (passively) to be alarmed; by analogy, to be in awe of, i.e. Revere -- be (+ sore) afraid, fear (exceedingly), reverence. see GREEK  (G5401) phobos
Neuter of a derivative of  (G5399) phobeo; a frightening thing, i.e. Terrific portent -- fearful sight. see GREEK  (G5399) phobeo

column7: panic flight, fear, the causing of fear, terror
column9: From a primary phebomai (to be put in fear); alarm or fright -- be afraid, + exceedingly, fear, terror.
Feminine of phoibos (bright; probably akin to the base of  (G5457) phos); Phoebe, a Christian woman -- Phebe. see GREEK  (G5457) phos

column7: Phoenicia, a region North of Galilee
column9: From  (G5404) phoinix; palm-country; Phoenice (or Phoenicia), a region of Palestine -- Phenice, Phenicia. see GREEK  (G5404) phoinix
Of uncertain derivation; a palm-tree -- palm (tree).

column7: a Phoenician (an inhabitant of Phoenicia), Phoenix (a city of Crete)
column9: Probably the same as  (G5404) phoinix; Phoenix, a place in Crete -- Phenice. see GREEK  (G5404) phoinix

From  (G5408) phonos; a murderer (always of criminal (or at least intentional) homicide; which  (G443) anthropoktonos does not necessarily imply; while  (G4607) sikarios is a special term for a public bandit) -- murderer. see GREEK  (G5408) phonos see GREEK  (G443) anthropoktonos see GREEK  (G4607) sikarios
From  (G5406) phoneus; to be a murderer (of) -- kill, do murder, slay. see GREEK  (G5406) phoneus
From an obsolete primary pheno (to slay); murder -- murder, + be slain with, slaughter.
From  (G5411) phoros; to have a burden, i.e. (by analogy) to wear as clothing or a constant accompaniment -- bear, wear. see GREEK  (G5411) phoros
Of Latin origin; a forum or market-place; only in comparative with  (G675) Appios; a station on the Appian road -- forum. see GREEK  (G675) Appios

From  (G5342) phero; a load (as borne), i.e. (figuratively) a tax (properly, an individual assessment on persons or property; whereas  (G5056) telos is usually a general toll on goods or travel) -- tribute. see GREEK  (G5342) phero see GREEK  (G5056) telos
From  (G5414) phortos; to load up (properly, as a vessel or animal), i.e. (figuratively) to overburden with ceremony (or spiritual anxiety) -- lade, by heavy laden. see GREEK  (G5414) phortos
Diminutive of  (G5414) phortos; an invoice (as part of freight), i.e. (figuratively) a task or service -- burden. see GREEK  (G5414) phortos
From  (G5342) phero; something carried, i.e. The cargo of a ship -- lading. see GREEK  (G5342) phero
Of Latin origin; "fortunate"; Fortunatus, a Christian -- Fortunatus.
Neuter of a derivative from the base of  (G5417) phragelloo; a whip, i.e. Roman lash as a public punishment -- scourge. see GREEK  (G5417) phragelloo
From a presumed equivalent of the Latin flagellum; to whip, i.e. Lash as a public punishment -- scourge.
From  (G5420) phrasso; a fence, or inclosing barrier (literally or figuratively) -- hedge (+ round about), partition. see GREEK  (G5420) phrasso
Probably akin to  (G5420) phrasso through the idea of defining; to indicate (by word or act), i.e. (specially), to expound -- declare. see GREEK  (G5420) phrasso
Apparently a strengthening form of the base of  (G5424) phren; to fence or inclose, i.e. (specially), to block up (figuratively, to silence) -- stop. see GREEK  (G5424) phren
Of uncertain derivation; a hole in the ground (dug for obtaining or holding water or other purposes), i.e. A cistern or well; figuratively, an abyss (as a prison) -- well, pit.
From  (G5423) phrenapates; to be a mind-misleader, i.e. Delude -- deceive. see GREEK  (G5423) phrenapates
From  (G5424) phren and  (G539) apate; a mind-misleader, i.e. Seducer -- deceiver. see GREEK  (G5424) phren see GREEK  (G539) apate

Probably from an obsolete phrao (to rein in or curb; compare  (G5420) phrasso); the midrif (as a partition of the body), i.e. (figuratively and by implication, of sympathy) the feelings (or sensitive nature; by extension (also in the plural) the mind or cognitive faculties) -- understanding. see GREEK  (G5420) phrasso

column7: to be rough, to shiver, shudder
column9: Apparently a primary verb; to "bristle" or chill, i.e. Shudder (fear) -- tremble.

From  (G5424) phren; to exercise the mind, i.e. Entertain or have a sentiment or opinion; by implication, to be (mentally) disposed (more or less earnestly in a certain direction); intensively, to interest oneself in (with concern or obedience) -- set the affection on, (be) care(-ful), (be like-, + be of one, + be of the same, + let this) mind(-ed), regard, savour, think. see GREEK  (G5424) phren

column7: the thought (that which is in the mind)
column8: be, be carnally, be spiritually minded.
column9: From  (G5426) phroneo; (mental) inclination or purpose -- (be, + be carnally, + be spiritually) mind(-ed). see GREEK  (G5426) phroneo
From  (G5426) phroneo; mental action or activity, i.e. Intellectual or moral insight -- prudence, wisdom. see GREEK  (G5426) phroneo

From  (G5424) phren; thoughtful, i.e. Sagacious or discreet (implying a cautious character; while  (G4680) sophos denotes practical skill or acumen; and  (G4908) sunetos indicates rather intelligence or mental acquirement); in a bad sense conceited (also in the comparative) -- wise(-r). see GREEK  (G5424) phren see GREEK  (G4680) sophos see GREEK  (G4908) sunetos
Adverb from  (G5429) phronimos; prudently -- wisely. see GREEK  (G5429) phronimos
From a derivative of  (G5424) phren; to exercise thought, i.e. Be anxious -- be careful. see GREEK  (G5424) phren

From a compound of  (G4253) pro and  (G3708) horao; to be a watcher in advance, i.e. To mount guard as a sentinel (post spies at gates); figuratively, to hem in, protect -- keep (with a garrison). Compare  (G5083) tereo. see GREEK  (G4253) pro see GREEK  (G3708) horao see GREEK  (G5083) tereo

column7: to neigh, whinny, to be wanton
column9: Akin to  (G1032) bruo,  (G1031) brucho; to snort (as a spirited horse), i.e. (figuratively) to make a tumult -- rage. see GREEK  (G1031) brucho see GREEK  (G1032) bruo
Neuter of a presumed derivative of phrugo (to roast or parch; akin to the base of  (G5395) phlox); something desiccated, i.e. A dry twig -- stick. see GREEK  (G5395) phlox

column7: Phrygia, a region of Asia Minor
column9: Probably of foreign origin; Phrygia, a region of Asia Minor -- Phrygia.
Probably from  (G5343) pheugo; fugitive; Phygellus, an apostate Christian -- Phygellus. see GREEK  (G5343) pheugo
From  (G5343) pheugo; a fleeing, i.e. Escape -- flight. see GREEK  (G5343) pheugo

From  (G5442) phulasso; a guarding or (concretely, guard), the act, the person; figuratively, the place, the condition, or (specially), the time (as a division of day or night), literally or figuratively -- cage, hold, (im-)prison(-ment), ward, watch. see GREEK  (G5442) phulasso
From  (G5441) phulax; to incarcerate -- imprison. see GREEK  (G5441) phulax
Neuter of a derivative of  (G5442) phulasso; a guard-case, i.e. "phylactery" for wearing slips of Scripture texts -- phylactery. see GREEK  (G5442) phulasso
From  (G5442) phulasso; a watcher or sentry -- keeper. see GREEK  (G5442) phulasso

Probably from  (G5443) phule through the idea of isolation; to watch, i.e. Be on guard (literally of figuratively); by implication, to preserve, obey, avoid -- beward, keep (self), observe, save. Compare  (G5083) tereo. see GREEK  (G5443) phule see GREEK  (G5083) tereo
From  (G5453) phuo (compare  (G5444) phullon); an offshoot, i.e. Race or clan -- kindred, tribe. see GREEK  (G5453) phuo see GREEK  (G5444) phullon
From the same as  (G5443) phule; a sprout, i.e. Leaf -- leaf. see GREEK  (G5443) phule
From a prolonged form of phuro (to mix a liquid with a solid; perhaps akin to  (G5453) phuo through the idea of swelling in bulk), mean to knead; a mass of dough -- lump. see GREEK  (G5453) phuo
From  (G5449) phusis; "physical", i.e. (by implication) instinctive -- natural. Compare  (G5591) psuchikos. see GREEK  (G5449) phusis see GREEK  (G5591) psuchikos
Adverb from  (G5446) phusikos; "physically", i.e. (by implication) instinctively -- naturally. see GREEK  (G5446) phusikos
From  (G5449) phusis in the primary sense of blowing; to inflate, i.e. (figuratively) make proud (haughty) -- puff up. see GREEK  (G5449) phusis

From  (G5453) phuo; growth (by germination or expansion), i.e. (by implication) natural production (lineal descent); by extension, a genus or sort; figuratively, native disposition, constitution or usage -- (man-)kind, nature(-al). see GREEK  (G5453) phuo
From  (G5448) phusioo; inflation, i.e. (figuratively) haughtiness -- swelling. see GREEK  (G5448) phusioo
From  (G5452) phuteuo; trans-planting, i.e. (concretely) a shrub or vegetable -- plant. see GREEK  (G5452) phuteuo
From a derivative of  (G5453) phuo; to set out in the earth, i.e. Implant; figuratively, to instil doctrine -- plant. see GREEK  (G5453) phuo
A primary verb; probably originally, to "puff" or blow, i.e. To swell up; but only used in the implied sense, to germinate or grow (sprout, produce), literally or figuratively -- spring (up).
Of uncertain derivative; a burrow or lurking-place -- hole.
From  (G5456) phone; to emit a sound (animal, human or instrumental); by implication, to address in words or by name, also in imitation -- call (for), crow, cry. see GREEK  (G5456) phone

Probably akin to  (G5316) phaino through the idea of disclosure; a tone (articulate, bestial or artificial); by implication, an address (for any purpose), saying or language -- noise, sound, voice. see GREEK  (G5316) phaino

From an obsolete phao (to shine or make manifest, especially by rays; compare  (G5316) phaino,  (G5346) phemi); luminousness (in the widest application, natural or artificial, abstract or concrete, literal or figurative) -- fire, light. see GREEK  (G5316) phaino see GREEK  (G5346) phemi
From  (G5457) phos; an illuminator, i.e. (concretely) a luminary, or (abstractly) brilliancy -- light. see GREEK  (G5457) phos
From  (G5457) phos and  (G5342) phero; light-bearing ("phosphorus"), i.e. (specially), the morning-star (figuratively) -- day star. see GREEK  (G5457) phos see GREEK  (G5342) phero
From  (G5457) phos; lustrous, i.e. Transparent or well-illuminated (figuratively) -- bright, full of light. see GREEK  (G5457) phos
From  (G5457) phos; to shed rays, i.e. To shine or (transitively) to brighten up (literally or figuratively) -- enlighten, illuminate, (bring to, give) light, make to see. see GREEK  (G5457) phos
From  (G5461) photizo; illumination (figuratively) -- light. see GREEK  (G5461) photizo

column8: farewell, be glad, God speed, rejoice.
column9: A primary verb; to be "cheer"ful, i.e. Calmly happy or well-off; impersonally, especially as salutation (on meeting or parting), be well -- farewell, be glad, God speed, greeting, hall, joy(- fully), rejoice.
Probably from  (G5465) chalao; hail -- hail. see GREEK  (G5465) chalao
From the base of  (G5490) chasma; to lower (as into a void) -- let down, strike. see GREEK  (G5490) chasma

column7: a Chaldean, an inhabitant of Chaldea
column9: Probably of Hebrew or ( (H3778) Kasdiy); a Chaldoean (i.e. Kasdi), or native or the region of the lower Euphrates -- Chaldaean. see HEBREW  (H3778) Kasdiy
Perhaps from  (G5465) chalao through the idea of reducing the strength; difficult, i.e. Dangerous, or (by implication) furious -- fierce, perilous. see GREEK  (G5465) chalao
From a compound of  (G5469) chalinos and the reduplicated form of  (G71) ago; to be a bit-leader, i.e. To curb (figuratively) -- bridle. see GREEK  (G5469) chalinos see GREEK  (G71) ago
From  (G5465) chalao; a curb or head-stall (as curbing the spirit) -- bit, bridle. see GREEK  (G5465) chalao
From  (G5475) chalkos; coppery -- brass. see GREEK  (G5475) chalkos
From  (G5475) chalkos; a copper-worker or brazier -- coppersmith. see GREEK  (G5475) chalkos
From  (G5475) chalkos and perhaps  (G1491) eidos; copper-like, i.e. "chalcedony" -- chalcedony. see GREEK  (G5475) chalkos see GREEK  (G1491) eidos

column7: a brazen (i.e. of copper, bronze, brass) vessel
column9: Diminutive from  (G5475) chalkos; a copper dish -- brazen vessel. see GREEK  (G5475) chalkos

Neuter of a compound of  (G5475) chalkos and  (G3030) libanos (in the implied mean of whiteness or brilliancy); burnished copper, an alloy of copper (or gold) and silver having a brilliant lustre -- fine brass. see GREEK  (G5475) chalkos see GREEK  (G3030) libanos

Perhaps from  (G5465) chalao through the idea of hollowing out as a vessel (this metal being chiefly used for that purpose); copper (the substance, or some implement or coin made of it) -- brass, money. see GREEK  (G5465) chalao
Adverb perhaps from the base of  (G5490) chasma through the idea of a fissure in the soil; earthward, i.e. Prostrate -- on (to) the ground. see GREEK  (G5490) chasma
Of Hebrew origin ( (H3667) Kna'an); Chanaan (i.e. Kenaan), the early name of Palestine -- Chanaan. see HEBREW  (H3667) Kna'an
From  (G5477) Chanaan; a Chanaanoean (i.e. Kenaanite), or native of gentile Palestine -- of Canaan. see GREEK  (G5477) Chanaan
From  (G5463) chairo; cheerfulness, i.e. Calm delight -- gladness, X greatly, (X be exceeding) joy(-ful, -fully, -fulness, -ous). see GREEK  (G5463) chairo
From the same as  (G5482) charax; a scratch or etching, i.e. Stamp (as a badge of servitude), or scupltured figure (statue) -- graven, mark. see GREEK  (G5482) charax

From the same as  (G5482) charax; a graver (the tool or the person), i.e. (by implication) engraving (("character"), the figure stamped, i.e. An exact copy or (figuratively) representation) -- express image. see GREEK  (G5482) charax

From charasso (to sharpen to a point; akin to  (G1125) grapho through the idea of scratching); a stake, i.e. (by implication) a palisade or rampart (military mound for circumvallation in a siege) -- trench. see GREEK  (G1125) grapho
Middle voice from  (G5485) charis; to grant as a favor, i.e. Gratuitously, in kindness, pardon or rescue -- deliver, (frankly) forgive, (freely) give, grant. see GREEK  (G5485) charis

column7: in favor of, for the pleasure of
column9: Accusative case of  (G5485) charis as preposition; through favor of, i.e. On account of -- be-(for) cause of, for sake of, +...fore, X reproachfully. see GREEK  (G5485) charis

From  (G5463) chairo; graciousness (as gratifying), of manner or act (abstract or concrete; literal, figurative or spiritual; especially the divine influence upon the heart, and its reflection in the life; including gratitude) -- acceptable, benefit, favour, gift, grace(- ious), joy, liberality, pleasure, thank(-s, -worthy). see GREEK  (G5463) chairo

column7: a gift of grace, a free gift
column9: From  (G5483) charizomai; a (divine) gratuity, i.e. Deliverance (from danger or passion); (specially), a (spiritual) endowment, i.e. (subjectively) religious qualification, or (objectively) miraculous faculty -- (free) gift. see GREEK  (G5483) charizomai

column7: to make graceful, endow with grace
column9: From  (G5485) charis; to grace, i.e. Indue with special honor -- make accepted, be highly favoured. see GREEK  (G5485) charis

column7: Haran, a city in northwest Mesopotamia
column9: Of Hebrew origin ( (H2771) Charan); Charrhan (i.e. Charan), a place in Mesopotamia -- Charran. see HEBREW  (H2771) Charan

column7: a sheet of paper (made of papyrus strips)
column9: From the same as  (G5482) charax; a sheet ("chart") of writing-material (as to be scribbled over) -- paper. see GREEK  (G5482) charax
From a form of an obsolete primary chao (to "gape" or "yawn"); a "chasm" or vacancy (impassable interval) -- gulf.
From a form of the same as  (G5490) chasma; a lip (as a pouring place); figuratively, a margin (of water) -- lip, shore. see GREEK  (G5490) chasma

column7: to expose to winter cold, to drive with storm
column9: From the same as  (G5494) cheimon; to storm, i.e. (passively) to labor under a gale -- be tossed with tempest. see GREEK  (G5494) cheimon
From the base of  (G5494) cheimon and  (G4482) rheo; a storm-runlet, i.e. Winter-torrent -- brook. see GREEK  (G5494) cheimon see GREEK  (G4482) rheo

From a derivative of cheo (to pour; akin to the base of  (G5490) chasma through the idea of a channel), meaning a storm (as pouring rain); by implication, the rainy season, i.e. Winter -- tempest, foul weather, winter.

Perhaps from the base of  (G5494) cheimon in the sense of its congener the base of  (G5490) chasma (through the idea of hollowness for grasping); the hand (literally or figuratively (power); especially (by Hebraism) a means or instrument) -- hand. see GREEK  (G5494) cheimon see GREEK  (G5490) chasma
From  (G5497) cheiragogos; to be a hand-leader, i.e. To guide (a blind person) -- lead by the hand. see GREEK  (G5497) cheiragogos
From  (G5495) cheir and a reduplicated form of  (G71) ago; a hand-leader, i.e. Personal conductor (of a blind person) -- some to lead by the hand. see GREEK  (G5495) cheir see GREEK  (G71) ago

Neuter of a compound of  (G5495) cheir and  (G1125) grapho; something hand-written ("chirograph"), i.e. A manuscript (specially, a legal document or bond (figuratively)) -- handwriting. see GREEK  (G5495) cheir see GREEK  (G1125) grapho
From  (G5495) cheir and a derivative of  (G4160) poieo; manufactured, i.e. Of human construction -- made by (make with) hands. see GREEK  (G5495) cheir see GREEK  (G4160) poieo

column7: to vote by stretching out the hand, to appoint
column9: From a comparative of  (G5495) cheir and teino (to stretch); to be a hand-reacher or voter (by raising the hand), i.e. (generally) to select or appoint -- choose, ordain. see GREEK  (G5495) cheir

Irregular comparative of  (G2556) kakos; from an obsolete equivalent cheres (of uncertain derivation); more evil or aggravated (physically, mentally or morally) -- sorer, worse. see GREEK  (G2556) kakos

column7: Cherubim, heavenly beings who serve God
column9: Plural of Hebrew origin ( (H3742) kruwb); "cherubim" (i.e. Cherubs or kerubim) -- cherubims. see HEBREW  (H3742) kruwb

Feminine of a presumed derivative apparently from the base of  (G5490) chasma through the idea of deficiency; a widow (as lacking a husband), literally or figuratively -- widow. see GREEK  (G5490) chasma
Of uncertain derivation; "yesterday"; by extension, in time past or hitherto -- yesterday.
From  (G5507) chilioi; one thousand ("chiliad") -- thousand. see GREEK  (G5507) chilioi

column7: a chiliarch, a commander of a thousand
column9: From  (G5507) chilioi and  (G757) archo; the commander of a thousand soldiers ("chiliarch"; i.e. Colonel -- (chief, high) captain. see GREEK  (G5507) chilioi see GREEK  (G757) archo
Plural of uncertain affinity; a thousand -- thousand.

column7: Chios, an island in the Aegean Sea
column9: Of uncertain derivation; Chios, an island in the Mediterranean -- Chios.
Of foreign origin ( (H3801) kthoneth); a tunic or shirt -- clothes, coat, garment. see HEBREW  (H3801) kthoneth

Perhaps akin to the base of  (G5490) chasma ( (G5465) chalao) or  (G5494) cheimon (as descending or empty); snow -- snow. see GREEK  (G5490) chasma see GREEK  (G5465) chalao see GREEK  (G5494) cheimon
Of uncertain derivation; a military cloak -- robe.
From a derivative probably of  (G5491) cheilos; to throw out the lip, i.e. Jeer at -- mock. see GREEK  (G5491) cheilos
From chlio (to warm); tepid -- lukewarm.
Feminine of apparently a primary word; "green"; Chloe, a Christian female -- Chloe.
From the same as  (G5514) Chloe; greenish, i.e. Verdant, dun-colored -- green, pale. see GREEK  (G5514) Chloe

The 22nd, 14th and an obsolete letter ( (G4742) stigma as a cross) of the Greek alphabet (intermediate between the 5th and 6th), used as numbers; denoting respectively 600, 60, and 6; 666 as a numeral -- six hundred threescore and six. see GREEK  (G4742) stigma
From  (G5522) choos; dusty or dirty (soil-like), i.e. (by implication) terrene -- earthy. see GREEK  (G5522) choos

column7: a choenix (a dry measure of less than a quart)
column9: Of uncertain derivation; a choenix or certain dry measure -- measure.
Of uncertain derivation; a hog -- swine.
From  (G5521) chole; to be bilious, i.e. (by implication) irritable (enraged, "choleric") -- be angry. see GREEK  (G5521) chole
Feminine of an equivalent perhaps akin to the same as  (G5514) Chloe (from the greenish hue); "gall" or bile, i.e. (by analogy) poison or an anodyne (wormwood, poppy, etc.) -- gall.
From the base of  (G5494) cheimon; a heap (as poured out), i.e. Rubbish; loose dirt -- dust. see GREEK  (G5494) cheimon
Of uncertain derivation; Chorazin, a place in Palestine -- Chorazin.

column7: to lead a chorus (i.e. a group of performers), to defray the cost of a chorus
column9: From a compound of  (G5525) choros and  (G71) ago; to be a dance-leader, i.e. (generally) to furnish -- give, minister. see GREEK  (G5525) choros see GREEK  (G71) ago
Of uncertain derivation; a ring, i.e. Round dance ("choir" -- dancing.
From  (G5528) chortos; to fodder, i.e. (generally) to gorge (supply food in abundance) -- feed, fill, satisfy. see GREEK  (G5528) chortos
From  (G5526) chortazo; forage, i.e. Food -- sustenance. see GREEK  (G5526) chortazo
Apparently a primary word; a "court" or "garden", i.e. (by implication, of pasture) herbage or vegetation -- blade, grass, hay.
Of uncertain origin; Chuzas, an officer of Herod -- Chuza.

Middle voice of a primary verb (perhaps rather from  (G5495) cheir, to handle); to furnish what is needed; (give an oracle, "graze" (touch slightly), light upon, etc.), i.e. (by implication) to employ or (by extension) to act towards one in a given manner -- entreat, use. Compare  (G5531) chrao;  (G5534) chre. see GREEK  (G5531) chrao see GREEK  (G5495) cheir see GREEK  (G5534) chre
Probably the same as the base of  (G5530) chraomai; to loan -- lend. see GREEK  (G5530) chraomai

From the base of  (G5530) chraomai or  (G5534) chre; employment, i.e. An affair; also (by implication) occasion, demand, requirement or destitution -- business, lack, necessary(-ity), need(-ful), use, want. see GREEK  (G5534) chre see GREEK  (G5530) chraomai
From a derivative of  (G5531) chrao and  (G3781) opheiletes; a loan-ower, i.e. Indebted person -- debtor. see GREEK  (G5531) chrao see GREEK  (G3781) opheiletes
Third person singular of the same as  (G5530) chraomai or  (G5531) chrao used impersonally; it needs (must or should) be -- ought. see GREEK  (G5530) chraomai see GREEK  (G5531) chrao
From  (G5532) chreia; to make (i.e. Have) necessity, i.e. Be in want of -- (have) need. see GREEK  (G5532) chreia

column7: a thing that one uses or needs
column9: Something useful or needed, i.e. Wealth, price -- money, riches.

column7: to transact business, to make answer
column9: From  (G5536) chrema; to utter an oracle (compare the original sense of  (G5530) chraomai), i.e. Divinely intimate; by implication, (compare the secular sense of  (G5532) chreia) to constitute a firm for business, i.e. (generally) bear as a title -- be called, be admonished (warned) of God, reveal, speak. see GREEK  (G5536) chrema see GREEK  (G5530) chraomai see GREEK  (G5532) chreia
From  (G5537) chrematizo; a divine response or revelation -- answer of God. see GREEK  (G5537) chrematizo
From  (G5540) chresis; serviceable -- profit. see GREEK  (G5540) chresis
From  (G5530) chraomai; employment, i.e. (specially), sexual intercourse (as an occupation of the body) -- use. see GREEK  (G5530) chraomai
Middle voice from  (G5543) chrestos; to show oneself useful, i.e. Act benevolently -- be kind. see GREEK  (G5543) chrestos
From a compound of  (G5543) chrestos and  (G3004) lego; fair speech, i.e. Plausibility -- good words. see GREEK  (G5543) chrestos see GREEK  (G3004) lego
From  (G5530) chraomai; employed, i.e. (by implication) useful (in manner or morals) -- better, easy, good(-ness), gracious, kind. see GREEK  (G5530) chraomai
From  (G5543) chrestos; usefulness, i.e. Morally, excellence (in character or demeanor) -- gentleness, good(-ness), kindness. see GREEK  (G5543) chrestos
From  (G5548) chrio; an unguent or smearing, i.e. (figuratively) the special endowment ("chrism") of the Holy Spirit -- anointing, unction. see GREEK  (G5548) chrio
From  (G5547) Christos; a Christian, i.e. Follower of Christ -- Christian. see GREEK  (G5547) Christos
From  (G5548) chrio; Anointed One, i.e. The Messiah, an epithet of Jesus -- Christ. see GREEK  (G5548) chrio
Probably akin to  (G5530) chraomai through the idea of contact; to smear or rub with oil, i.e. (by implication) to consecrate to an office or religious service -- anoint. see GREEK  (G5530) chraomai

column7: to spend or take time, delay
column9: From  (G5550) chronos; to take time, i.e. Linger -- delay, tarry. see GREEK  (G5550) chronos

Of uncertain derivation; a space of time (in general, and thus properly distinguished from  (G2540) kairos, which designates a fixed or special occasion; and from  (G165) aion, which denotes a particular period) or interval; by extension, an individual opportunity; by implication, delay -- + years old, season, space, (X often-)time(-s), (a) while. see GREEK  (G2540) kairos see GREEK  (G165) aion
From a presumed compound of  (G5550) chronos and the base of  (G5147) tribos; to be a time-wearer, i.e. To procrastinate (linger) -- spend time. see GREEK  (G5550) chronos see GREEK  (G5147) tribos
From  (G5557) chrusos; made of gold -- of gold, golden. see GREEK  (G5557) chrusos
Diminutive of  (G5557) chrusos; a golden article, i.e. Gold plating, ornament, or coin -- gold. see GREEK  (G5557) chrusos
From  (G5557) chrusos and  (G1146) daktulios; gold-ringed, i.e. Wearing a golden finger-ring or similar jewelry -- with a gold ring. see GREEK  (G5557) chrusos see GREEK  (G1146) daktulios
From  (G5557) chrusos and  (G3037) lithos; gold-stone, i.e. A yellow gem ("chrysolite") -- chrysolite. see GREEK  (G5557) chrusos see GREEK  (G3037) lithos
From  (G5557) chrusos and prason (a leek); a greenish-yellow gem ("chrysoprase") -- chrysoprase. see GREEK  (G5557) chrusos
Perhaps from the base of  (G5530) chraomai (through the idea of the utility of the metal); gold; by extension, a golden article, as an ornament or coin -- gold. see GREEK  (G5530) chraomai

column7: to gild, to cover with gold
column9: From  (G5557) chrusos; to gild, i.e. Bespangle with golden ornaments -- deck. see GREEK  (G5557) chrusos

column7: the surface of the body, skin
column9: Probably akin to the base of  (G5530) chraomai through the idea of handling; the body (properly, its surface or skin) -- body. see GREEK  (G5530) chraomai
Apparently a primary word; "halt", i.e. Limping -- cripple, halt, lame.

Feminine of a derivative of the base of  (G5490) chasma through the idea of empty expanse; room, i.e. A space of territory (more or less extensive; often including its inhabitants) -- coast, county, fields, ground, land, region. Compare  (G5117) topos. see GREEK  (G5117) topos see GREEK  (G5490) chasma

From  (G5561) chora; to be in (give) space, i.e. (intransitively) to pass, enter, or (transitively) to hold, admit (literally or figuratively) -- come, contain, go, have place, (can, be room to) receive. see GREEK  (G5561) chora
From  (G5561) chora; to place room between, i.e. Part; reflexively, to go away -- depart, put asunder, separate. see GREEK  (G5561) chora
Diminutive of  (G5561) chora; a spot or plot of ground -- field, land, parcel of ground, place, possession. see GREEK  (G5561) chora
Adverb from  (G5561) chora; at a space, i.e. Separately or apart from (often as preposition) -- beside, by itself, without. see GREEK  (G5561) chora
Of Latin origin; the north-west wind -- north west.

column7: to pull, twitch, twang, play, sing
column9: Probably strengthened from psao (to rub or touch the surface; compare  (G5597) psocho); to twitch or twang, i.e. To play on a stringed instrument (celebrate the divine worship with music and accompanying odes) -- make melody, sing (psalms). see GREEK  (G5597) psocho

column7: a striking (of musical strings), a psalm
column9: From  (G5567) psallo; a set piece of music, i.e. A sacred ode (accompanied with the voice, harp or other instrument; a "psalm"); collectively, the book of the Psalms -- psalm. Compare  (G5603) oide. see GREEK  (G5567) psallo see GREEK  (G5603) oide
From  (G5571) pseudes and  (G80) adephos; a spurious brother, i.e. Pretended associate -- false brethren. see GREEK  (G5571) pseudes see GREEK  (G80) adephos
From  (G5571) pseudes and  (G652) apostolos; a spurious apostle, i.e. Pretended pracher -- false teacher. see GREEK  (G5571) pseudes see GREEK  (G652) apostolos
From  (G5574) pseudomai; untrue, i.e. Erroneous, deceitful, wicked -- false, liar. see GREEK  (G5574) pseudomai
From  (G5571) pseudes and  (G1320) didaskalos; a spurious teacher, i.e. Propagator of erroneous Christian doctrine -- false teacher. see GREEK  (G5571) pseudes see GREEK  (G1320) didaskalos
From  (G5571) pseudes and  (G3004) lego; mendacious, i.e. Promulgating erroneous Christian doctrine -- speaking lies. see GREEK  (G5571) pseudes see GREEK  (G3004) lego
Middle voice of an apparently primary verb; to utter an untruth or attempt to deceive by falsehood -- falsely, lie.

column4: Noun, MasculinePhonetic Spelling: (psyoo-dom-ar\'-toor)Definition: false witnessUsage: a false witness.Thayer\'s Greek LexiconSTRONGS NT 5575: \xcf\x88\xce\xb5\xcf\x85\xce\xb4\xce\xbf\xce\xbc\xce\xb1\xcf\x81\xcf\x84\xcf\x85\xcf\x81\xcf\x88\xce\xb5\xcf\x85\xce\xb4\xce\xbf\xce\xbc\xce\xb1\xcf\x81\xcf\x84\xcf\x85\xcf\x81, unless more correctly \xcf\x88\xce\xb5\xcf\x85\xce\xb4\xcf\x8c\xce\xbc\xce\xb1\xcf\x81\xcf\x84\xcf\x85\xcf\x82 or rather \xcf\x88\xce\xb5\xcf\x85\xce\xb4\xcf\x8c\xce\xbc\xce\xb1\xcf\x81\xcf\x84\xcf\x85\xcf\x82 (as \xe1\xbc\x80\xcf\x85\xcf\x84\xce\xbf\xce\xbc\xce\xb1\xcf\x81\xcf\x84\xcf\x85\xcf\x81; see Passow, under the word, \xcf\x88\xce\xb5\xcf\x85\xce\xb4\xcf\x8c\xce\xbc\xce\xb1\xcf\x81\xcf\x84\xcf\x85\xcf\x82 (especially Lob. Paralip., p. 217; cf. Etym. Magn. 506, 26)), \xcf\x88\xce\xb5\xcf\x85\xce\xb4\xce\xbf\xce\xbc\xce\xb1\xcf\x81\xcf\x84\xcf\x85\xcf\x81\xce\xbf\xcf\x82, \xe1\xbd\x81, (\xcf\x88\xce\xb5\xcf\x85\xce\xb4\xce\xae\xcf\x82 and \xce\xbc\xce\xac\xcf\x81\xcf\x84\xcf\x85\xcf\x81 (which see)), a false witness: Matthew 26:60; \xcf\x84\xce\xbf\xe1\xbf\xa6 \xce\xb8\xce\xb5\xce\xbf\xe1\xbf\xa6, false witnesses of i. e. concerning God (Winer\'s Grammar, \xc2\xa7 30, 1 a.), 1 Corinthians 15:15. (Plato, Gorgias, p. 472b.; Aristotle, pol. 2, 9, 8 (p. 1274b, 6; but the true reading here is \xcf\x88\xce\xb5\xcf\x85\xce\xb4\xce\xbf\xce\xbc\xce\xb1\xcf\x81\xcf\x84\xcf\x85\xcf\x81\xce\xb9\xcf\x89\xce\xbd (see Bentley\'s Works, Dyce edition, vol. i., p. 408); a better example is Aristotle, rhet. ad Alex. 16, p. 1432{a}, 6; cf. Plutarch, praec. ger. reip. 29, 1; Apostolic Constitutions 5, 9; Pollux 6, 36, 153).)   STRONGS NT 5575: \xcf\x88\xce\xb5\xcf\x85\xce\xb4\xcf\x8c\xce\xbc\xce\xb1\xcf\x81\xcf\x84\xcf\x85\xcf\x82\xcf\x88\xce\xb5\xcf\x85\xce\xb4\xcf\x8c\xce\xbc\xce\xb1\xcf\x81\xcf\x84\xcf\x85\xcf\x82, see  \xcf\x88\xce\xb5\xcf\x85\xce\xb4\xce\xbf\xce\xbc\xce\xb1\xcf\x81\xcf\x84\xcf\x85\xcf\x81.   Strong\'s Exhaustive Concordancefalse witness. From pseudes and a kindred form of martus; a spurious witness, i.e. Bearer of untrue testimony -- false witness. see GREEK pseudes see GREEK martus g,5576,ψευδομαρτυρέω,Verb,pseudomartureó,(psyoo-dom-ar-too-reh'-o),to bear false witness
column7: From  (G5575) pseudomartur; to be an untrue testifier, i.e. Offer falsehood in evidence -- be a false witness. see GREEK  (G5575) pseudomartur

column9: From  (G5575) pseudomartur; untrue testimony -- false witness. see GREEK  (G5575) pseudomartur
From  (G5571) pseudes and  (G4396) prophetes; a spurious prophet, i.e. Pretended foreteller or religious impostor -- false prophet. see GREEK  (G5571) pseudes see GREEK  (G4396) prophetes
From  (G5574) pseudomai; a falsehood -- lie, lying. see GREEK  (G5574) pseudomai
From  (G5571) pseudes and  (G5547) Christos; a spurious Messiah -- false Christ. see GREEK  (G5571) pseudes see GREEK  (G5547) Christos

column7: under a false name, falsely called
column9: From  (G5571) pseudes and  (G3686) onoma; untruly named -- falsely so called. see GREEK  (G5571) pseudes see GREEK  (G3686) onoma
From  (G5574) pseudomai; a fabrication, i.e. Falsehood -- lie. see GREEK  (G5574) pseudomai

column5: pseustés from the same as NG5574
column9: From  (G5574) pseudomai; a falsifier -- liar. see GREEK  (G5574) pseudomai

From the base of  (G5567) psallo (compare  (G5586) psephos); to manipulate, i.e. Verify by contact; figuratively, to search for -- feel after, handle, touch. see GREEK  (G5567) psallo see GREEK  (G5586) psephos
From  (G5586) psephos; to use pebbles in enumeration, i.e. (generally) to compute -- count. see GREEK  (G5586) psephos

column7: a small smooth stone, a pebble
column9: From the same as  (G5584) pselaphao; a pebble (as worn smooth by handling), i.e. (by implication, of use as a counter or ballot) a verdict (of acquittal) or ticket (of admission); a vote -- stone, voice. see GREEK  (G5584) pselaphao
From a derivative of psithos (a whisper; by implication, a slander; probably akin to  (G5574) pseudomai); whispering, i.e. Secret detraction -- whispering. see GREEK  (G5574) pseudomai
From the same as  (G5587) psithurismos; a secret calumniator -- whisperer. see GREEK  (G5587) psithurismos
Diminutive from a derivative of the base of  (G5567) psallo (meaning a crumb); a little bit or morsel -- crumb. see GREEK  (G5567) psallo

From  (G5594) psucho; breath, i.e. (by implication) spirit, abstractly or concretely (the animal sentient principle only; thus distinguished on the one hand from  (G4151) pneuma, which is the rational and immortal soul; and on the other from  (G2222) zoe, which is mere vitality, even of plants: these terms thus exactly correspond respectively to the Hebrew  (H5315) nephesh,  (H7307) ruwach and  (H2416) chay) -- heart (+ -ily), life, mind, soul, + us, + you. see GREEK  (G5594) psucho see GREEK  (G4151) pneuma see GREEK  (G2222) zoe see HEBREW  (H5315) nephesh see HEBREW  (H7307) ruwach see HEBREW  (H2416) chay

column7: natural, of the soul or mind
column9: From  (G5590) psuche; sensitive, i.e. Animate (in distinction on the one hand from  (G4152) pneumatikos, which is the higher or renovated nature; and on the other from  (G5446) phusikos, which is the lower or bestial nature) -- natural, sensual. see GREEK  (G5590) psuche see GREEK  (G4152) pneumatikos see GREEK  (G5446) phusikos
From  (G5594) psucho; coolness -- cold. see GREEK  (G5594) psucho
From  (G5592) psuchos; chilly (literally or figuratively) -- cold. see GREEK  (G5592) psuchos

column7: to breathe, blow, to make cool
column9: A primary verb; to breathe (voluntarily but gently, thus differing on the one hand from  (G4154) pneo, which denotes properly a forcible respiration; and on the other from the base of  (G109) aer, which refers properly to an inanimate breeze), i.e. (by implication, of reduction of temperature by evaporation) to chill (figuratively) -- wax cold. see GREEK  (G4154) pneo see GREEK  (G109) aer
From the base of  (G5596) psomion; to supply with bits, i.e. (generally) to nourish -- (bestow to) feed. see GREEK  (G5596) psomion
Diminutive from a derivative of the base of  (G5597) psocho; a crumb or morsel (as if rubbed off), i.e. A mouthful -- sop. see GREEK  (G5597) psocho
Prolongation from the same base as  (G5567) psallo; to triturate, i.e. (by analogy) to rub out (kernels from husks with the fingers or hand) -- rub. see GREEK  (G5567) psallo

column7: the last letter of the Greek  alphabet
column9: The last letter of the Greek alphabet, i.e. (figuratively) the finality -- Omega.
A primary interjection; as a sign of the vocative case, O; as a note of exclamation, oh -- O.

Including the oblique forms, as well as es (ace); e (ay); etc. The subjunctive of  (G1510) eimi; (may, might, can, could, would, should, must, etc.; also with  (G1487) ei and its comparative, as well as with other particles) be -- + appear, are, (may, might, should) be, X have, is, + pass the flower of her age, should stand, were. see GREEK  (G1510) eimi see GREEK  (G1487) ei
Of Hebrew origin ( (H5744) Owbed); Obed, an Israelite -- Obed. see HEBREW  (H5744) Owbed

column8: here, hither, in this place, there.
column9: From an adverb form of  (G3592) hode; in this same spot, i.e. Here or hither -- here, hither, (in) this place, there. see GREEK  (G3592) hode

From  (G103) aido; a chant or "ode" (the general term for any words sung; while  (G5215) humnos denotes especially a religious metrical composition, and  (G5568) psalmos still more specially, a Hebrew cantillation) -- song. see GREEK  (G103) aido see GREEK  (G5215) humnos see GREEK  (G5568) psalmos
Akin to  (G3601) odune; a pang or throe, especially of childbirth -- pain, sorrow, travail. see GREEK  (G3601) odune

column7: to have birth pangs, to travail
column9: From  (G5604) odin; to experience the pains of parturition (literally or figuratively) -- travail in (birth). see GREEK  (G5604) odin
Perhaps from the alternate of  (G5342) phero; the shoulder (as that on which burdens are borne) -- shoulder. see GREEK  (G5342) phero
Including the feminine ousa (oo'-sah); and the neuter on (on) present participle of  (G1510) eimi; being -- be, come, have. see GREEK  (G1510) eimi
Middle voice from an apparently primary onos (a sum or price); to purchase (synonymous with the earlier  (G4092) pimpremi) -- buy. see GREEK  (G4092) pimpremi
Apparently a primary word; an "egg" -- egg.

column7: a time or period, an hour
column9: Apparently a primary word; an "hour" (literally or figuratively) -- day, hour, instant, season, X short, (even-)tide, (high) time.
From  (G5610) hora; belonging to the right hour or season (timely), i.e. (by implication) flourishing (beauteous (figuratively)) -- beautiful. see GREEK  (G5610) hora
Middle voice of an apparently primary verb; to "roar" -- roar.

column7: as, like as, even as, when, since, as long as
column9: Probably adverb of comparative from  (G3739) hos; which how, i.e. In that manner (very variously used, as follows) -- about, after (that), (according) as (it had been, it were), as soon (as), even as (like), for, how (greatly), like (as, unto), since, so (that), that, to wit, unto, when(-soever), while, X with all speed. see GREEK  (G3739) hos
Of Hebrew origin ( (H3467) yasha' and  (H4994) na'); oh save!; hosanna (i.e. Hoshia-na), an exclamation of adoration -- hosanna. see HEBREW  (H3467) yasha' see HEBREW  (H4994) na'
From  (G5613) hos and an adverb from  (G846) autos; as thus, i.e. In the same way -- even so, likewise, after the same (in like) manner. see GREEK  (G5613) hos see GREEK  (G846) autos

column7: as if, as it were, like
column9: From  (G5613) hos and  (G1487) ei; as if -- about, as (it had been, it were), like (as). see GREEK  (G5613) hos see GREEK  (G1487) ei
Of Hebrew origin ( (H1954) Howshea'); Hosee (i.e. Hoshea), an Israelite -- Osee. see HEBREW  (H1954) Howshea'
From  (G5613) hos and  (G4007) per; just as, i.e. Exactly like -- (even, like) as. see GREEK  (G5613) hos see GREEK  (G4007) per
From  (G5618) hosper and  (G1487) ei; just as if, i.e. As it were -- as. see GREEK  (G5618) hosper see GREEK  (G1487) ei

column7: so as to, so then, therefore
column9: From  (G5613) hos and  (G5037) te; so too, i.e. Thus therefore (in various relations of consecution, as follow) -- (insomuch) as, so that (then), (insomuch) that, therefore, to, wherefore. see GREEK  (G5613) hos see GREEK  (G5037) te
Diminutive of  (G3775) ous; an earlet, i.e. One of the ears, or perhaps the lobe of the ear -- ear. see GREEK  (G3775) ous
From a derivative of the base of  (G5624) ophelimos; usefulness, i.e. Benefit -- advantage, profit. see GREEK  (G5624) ophelimos
From the same as  (G5622) opheleia; to be useful, i.e. To benefit -- advantage, better, prevail, profit. see GREEK  (G5622) opheleia
From a form of  (G3786) ophelos; helpful or serviceable, i.e. Advantageous -- profit(-able). see GREEK  (G3786) ophelos
